| before= [[Kasey Kahne]]\n| title= [[NASCAR Rookie of the Year|NASCAR Nextel Cup Series Rookie of the Year]]\n| years= [[2005 NASCAR Nextel Cup Series|2005]]\n| after= [[Denny Hamlin]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before= [[David Stremme]]\n| title= [[NASCAR Rookie of the Year|NASCAR Busch Series Rookie of the Year]]\n| years= [[2004 NASCAR Busch Series|2004]]\n| after= [[Carl Edwards]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Kevin Harvick]]\n| after = [[Lewis Hamilton]]\n| title = [[Best Driver ESPY Award]]\n| years = [[2016 ESPY Awards|2016]]\n|}}\n\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Joe Gibbs Racing}}\n{{Kyle Busch Motorsports}}\n{{Billy Ballew Motorsports}}\n{{Hendrick Motorsports}}\n{{Roush Fenway Racing}}\n{{NASCAR Sprint Cup Champions}}\n{{NASCAR Xfinity Series Champions}}\n{{NASCARROTY}}\n{{TRIPLE}}\n{{Brickyard 400 Winners}}\n{{Busch Clash Winners}}\n{{Busch racing family}}\n{{WWE 24/7 Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Busch, Kyle}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from Nevada]]\n[[Category:NASCAR drivers]]\n[[Category:NASCAR Cup Series champions]]\n[[Category:NASCAR Xfinity Series champions]]\n[[Category:NASCAR team owners]]\n[[Category:ARCA Menards Series drivers]]\n[[Category:American Speed Association drivers]]\n[[Category:Rolex Sports Car Series drivers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American racing drivers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American racing drivers]]\n[[Category:WWE 24/7 Champions]]\n", "name_user": "Rocket Man448", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyle_Busch"}
{"title_page": "Inca society", "text_new": "{{Short description|Pre-Columbian civilization}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2008}}\n{{Weasel|date=February 2010}}\n}}\n\n{{Inca civilization}}\n\nThe '''Inca society''' was the society of the Inca civilization in [[Peru]]. The [[Inca Empire]], which lasted from 1438 to 1533 AD, represented the height of this civilization. The Inca state was known as the [[Kingdom of Cusco]] before 1438. Over the course of the empire, the rulers used conquest and peaceful assimilation to incorporate a large portion of western South America, centred on the [[Andes|Andean]] mountain ranges. The empire proved relatively short-lived, however: by 1533, [[Atahualpa]], the last [[Sapa Inca]] (emperor) of the Inca Empire, was killed on the orders of the [[conquistador]] [[Francisco Pizarro]], marking the beginning of Spanish rule. The last Inca stronghold, the [[Neo-Inca State]] in [[Vilcabamba, Peru|Vilcabamba]] was conquered by the Spanish in 1572.\n\n==Population==\n\nPopulation estimates for the Tawantinsuyu society range from as few as 4.1 million people to more than 37 million. Most estimates are between 6 and 14 million people. The reason for these various estimates is that, despite that the Inca kept excellent census records using their [[quipus]], knowledge of how to read them has been lost. Almost all of them were destroyed by the Spanish in the course of their conquest and rule.<ref>{{Cite book | last=McEwan | first=Gordon Francis | authorlink=Gordon Francis McEwan | title=The Incas: New Perspectives | year=2006 | publisher=W. W. Norton | location= | isbn=0-393-33301-9 | pages=93\u201396}} There is some debate about the size of the population.</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\nWomen and men had paralleled roles, but were separate in Inca society. They were equally valued for the part they played in their society despite their differing roles.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Powers|first=Karen Vieira|title=Andeans and Spaniards in the Contact Zone: A Gendered Collision|url=|journal=American Indian Quarterly|volume=24|issue=4|pages=511\u2013536|doi=10.1353/aiq.2000.0025|year=2000}}</ref> Marriage was no different.\n\nIncan women were typically married at the age of sixteen, while men married at the age of twenty. Age, however, was not as important as keeping track of the stage of life that a person was at, such as whether or not they were able to work or be married.<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Altroy|first1=Terence|title=The Incas|date=2015|publisher=Wiley Blackwell|location=West Sussex|isbn=9781444331158|page=295|edition=2nd}}</ref> Ranks played a role in a person's marriage status as well. Men of lower rank could only have one wife; people of ranks higher than the [[kuraka]] [[Polygyny|were allowed more]].<ref>{{cite book |author= |title=Incas: lords of gold and glory |publisher=Time-Life Books |location=New York |year=1992 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/incaslordsofgold00time/page/130 130] |isbn=0-8094-9870-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/incaslordsofgold00time/page/130 }}</ref> If a man had more than one wife, one served as the principal wife while the other(s) were considered secondary. Having more wives showed that the man had more labour showing that the household was wealthy. The death of the principal wife was sometimes met with suspicion that the husband played a role in her death. The man had to find a new principal wife before he was able to recover from the previous wife's death.<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Altroy|first1=Terence|title=The Incas|date=2015|publisher=Wiley Blackwell|location=West Sussex, UK|isbn=9781444331158|pages=305\u2013306|edition=2nd}}</ref> To prevent such suspicion and to increase the likelihood of a successful marriage, there were situations in which the couple could test how well the marriage would work out.\n\nTrial marriages were typical of Inca culture. In this type of marriage, the man and woman would agree to try out being married to one another for a few years. At the end of this time, the woman could go home to her parents if she wished, and her husband could also send her home if he did not think it would work out. However, once the marriage was made final, they could only divorce if the woman was childless. To make the marriage final, the provincial governor had to approve the union.<ref name=\"The Incas\">{{cite book|last1=D'Altroy|first1=Terence|title=The Incas|date=2015|publisher=Wiley Blackwell|location=West Sussex, UK|isbn=9781444331158|page=304|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nIn the Inca society, a wedding was a simple event.<ref name=\"The Incas\"/>  Instead, it was looked at more as a business-like agreement. Therefore, marriage was an economic agreement between two families. Parents on either side had to come to an agreement before the marriage took place and the couple could not be directly related to one another.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Silverblatt|first1=Irene|title=Andean Women in the Inca Empire|journal=Feminist Studies|date=October 1978|volume=4|issue=3|page=39|doi=10.2307/3177537|jstor=3177537}}</ref> Women would almost always marry men in the same social class as themselves. However, while it was very rare for them to marry a man with a higher social ranking, it was still possible for some young women. The only way for a young woman to alter her social ranking would be if a man of higher ranking took notice of her.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}\n\nOnce a woman was married, she was expected to collect food and cook, watch over the animals and the children, and to supply cloth to the government. Women of higher ranking also weaved, like those of lower ranks, but their work was used in special clothing for the higher ranks.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Silverblatt|first1=Irene|title=Andean Women in the Inca Empire|journal=Feminist Studios, Inc.|date=Oct 1978|volume=4|issue=3|page=42}}</ref> A man's role sometimes resembled those of a woman, but acted in conjunction with one another.<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Altroy|first1=Terence|title=The Incas|date=2015|publisher=Wiley Blackwell|location=West Sussex, UK|isbn=9781444331158|page=300}}</ref> A woman\u2019s household obligations would not change after she became pregnant. When she did find out she was pregnant she prayed and made offerings to an Inca god, Kanopa.Using marriage as an alliance strategy was also common among the Inca. Even before the Spaniards' arrival, the Inca used marriage as a way to claim themselves to power. After the [[Spanish conquest of the Inca Empire|Spaniards arrival]] the Inca allowed marriages between the Inca and Spaniards in order to gain power during a time of civil war.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Guengerich|first1=Sara Vicuna|title=Capac Women and the Politics of Marriage in Early Colonial Peru|journal=Colonial Latin America Review|date=2015|volume=24|issue=2|pages=147\u2013148|doi=10.1080/10609164.2015.1040275}}</ref>\n\n==Arts==\nThe Inca were a conquering society, and their expansionist assimilation of other cultures is evident in their artistic style.  The artistic style of the Inca utilized the vocabulary of many regions and cultures, but incorporated these themes into a standardized imperial style that could easily be replicated and spread throughout the empire.  The simple abstract geometric forms and highly stylised animal representation in ceramics, wood carvings, textiles and metalwork were all part of the Inca culture.  The motifs were not as revivalist as previous empires. No motifs of other societies were directly used with the exception of [[Huari culture|Huari]] and [[Tiwanaku]] arts.\n\n===Shipbuilding===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Totora titicaca.jpg|thumb|Reproduction of Inca ship sailing on Lake Titicaca in Bolivia]] -->\n\nFor fishing, trade, construction, transport and military purposes, the Inca built seagoing vessels called [[Balsa (ship)|''balsas'']] by weaving together [[totora (plant)|totora]] reeds. The largest of these vessels were 20 to 30 meters long, making them comparable in length to the Spanish ''[[caravel]]'' .{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} This method of constructing ships from woven reeds is an ancient Peruvian tradition which long predates the Inca. There are depictions of such vessels in [[Moche (culture)|Moche]] pottery dating back to 100 A.D.\n\n===Clothing===\n[[File:Tupa-inca-tunic.png|thumb|Inca tunic]]\n\nInca officials wore stylized [[tunic]]s that indicated their status. It contains an amalgamation of motifs used in the tunics of particular officeholders. For instance, the black and white [[checkerboard]] pattern topped with a pink triangle is believed to have been worn by soldiers of the army. Some of the motifs make reference to earlier cultures, such as the stepped diamonds of the [[Huari culture|Huari]] and the three-step stairstep motif of the [[Moche (culture)|Moche]].\n\nCloth was divided into three classes. ''Awaska'' was used for household use, and usually made from [[llama]] wool. Finer cloth, ''qunpi'', was divided into two classes: The first, woven by male ''qunpikamayuq'' (keepers of fine cloth) from [[alpaca]] wool, was collected as tribute from throughout the country and was used for trade. The other class of ''qunpi'' ranked highest. It was woven in the Acllawasi (acllahuasi) by \"aclla\" (female virgins of the sun god temple) from [[vicu\u00f1a]] wool and used solely for royal and religious use.  These had thread counts of 300 or more per inch, unsurpassed anywhere in the world, until the [[Industrial Revolution]] of the 19th century.\n\nAside from the tunic, a person of importance wore a ''[[llawt'u]]'', a series of cords wrapped around the head. To establish his importance, the Inca [[Atahualpa]] commissioned a ''llawt'u'' woven from vampire bat hair. The leader of each [[ayllu]], or extended family, had its own headdress.\n\nIn conquered regions, traditional clothing continued to be worn, but the finest weavers, such as those of [[Chan Chan]], were transferred to Cusco and kept there to weave ''qunpi''. (The [[Chimu|Chim\u00fa]] had previously transferred these same weavers to Chan Chan from [[Sican culture|Sican]].)\n\nThe Incan government controlled all clothing of their society.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} One would receive two outfits of clothing, one formal and one casual pair, and they would then proceed to wear those same outfits until they could literally be worn no longer. Since the government was in such strict control on their clothing, the Incas could not alter their clothing without the permission of the government.\n\n===Jewelry===\nThe wearing of [[jewellery]] was not uniform throughout the empire. Chim\u00fa [[artisan]]s, for example, continued to wear [[earrings]] after their integration into the empire, but in many other regions, usually, only local leaders wore them.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} Jewelry may have been common among the Inca people, however it did not hold as much value to them because labor was the main way people paid each other.<ref name=\"Karen Spalding\">{{cite book|last1=Spalding|first1=Karen|title=Huarochir\u00c3: An Andean Society Under Inca and Spanish Rule|date=1984|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=Stanford, California|isbn=0-8047-1516-5|pages=83\u201384|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kTPgOxyliqQC&pg=PA1&dq=inca+jewelry#v=onepage&q=inca%20jewelry&f=false|accessdate=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ceramics and metalwork===\n[[File:Recipiente Chim\u00fa-Inca caim\u00e1n (M. Am\u00e9rica, Madrid) 01.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Chim\u00fa]]-Inca ceramic from the [[Cultural periods of Peru|Late Horizon]].]]\n\nCeramics were for the most part utilitarian in nature, but also incorporated the imperialist style that was prevalent in the Inca textiles and metalwork.  In addition, the Inca played drums and on woodwind instruments including [[flute]]s, [[pan-pipe]]s and [[trumpet]]s made of shell and ceramics.\n\nThe Inca made beautiful objects of gold, silver, copper, bronze and [[tumbaga]] . But precious metals were in shorter supply than in earlier Peruvian cultures. The Inca metalworking style draws much of its inspiration from [[Chim\u00fa]] art and in fact the best metal workers of [[Chan Chan]] were transferred to Cusco when the Kingdom of [[Chimor]] was incorporated into the empire. Unlike the Chim\u00fa, the Inca do not seem to have regarded metals to be as precious as fine cloth. Nonetheless, the metalworks of the Incas were perhaps the most advanced in America. When the Spanish first encountered the Inca they were offered gifts of ''qunpi'' cloth.\n\nIncan ceramics are usually very distinct and easy to recognize. The shapes of the vessels are highly standardized. The most typical Incan pottery would have a spherical body with a cone shaped base. This spherical body usually includes two vertical side handles with a tall neck and flaring rim. The Incans often would place animal heads on their pottery as well usually near the top of the vessel. There were also several other popular styles for Incan ceramics which included a shallow dish with a single bird head and handle, a pedestal beaker, and a single or double handled bottle.\n\nIncans often decorated their ceramics with a multitude of images and colors. They usually decorated their pottery with bright colors of red, yellow, orange, black and white. Much like all other forms of Incan art, the pottery was often decorated with geometric shapes. The Incans would put diamonds, squares, checkers, triangles, circles and dots on almost all of their ceramic work. Other common themes were animals and insects like llamas, birds, jaguars, alpacas, bees, butterflies as well as block-like humans.\n\nAs part of a tax obligation to the commoners, mining was required in all the provinces. Even though the Inca Empire contained a lot of precious metals, the Incans did not value their metal as much as fine cloth.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} The Incans adopted much of their metal-working characteristics from the metalwork of [[Chimu]]. Because of their expertise in metalworking, after the fall of Chimu many metalworkers were taken back to the capital city of Cuzco to continue their metalworking for the emperor. Copper, tin, gold, and silver were all obtained from mines or washed from the river gravels. These metals would then be handed over to metallurgists. Because the Inca had a system that emphasized political and religious organization, there were many specialized artisans like metallurgists. There were also specialized weavers, cloth makers, pottery makers, and many more. Both copper and bronze would be used for basic farming tools or weapons. Some of the common bronze and copper pieces found in the Incan empire included sharp sticks for digging, club-heads, knives with curved blades, axes, chisels, needles and pins. All of these items would be forged by a metallurgist and then spread throughout the empire.\n\nThe Incans reserved their more precious metals for ornaments and decorations. Gold and silver were common themes throughout the palaces of Incan emperors. It was said that the walls and thrones were covered with gold and that the emperor dined on gold and silver service. These golden plated services would often be inlaid with llamas, butterflies or other creatures. Even beyond the gold and decoration of the emperor\u2019s palace were the ornaments that decorated all of the temples throughout the empire. The temples of the Incans were strewn with sacred and highly precious objects. Headdresses, crowns, ceremonial knives, cups, and a lot of ceremonial clothing were all inlaid with gold or silver.\n\nMany historians{{Who|date=February 2010}} believe that the choice of gold was to distinguish the more \u201csacred\u201d or \u201choly\u201d pieces from others.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} The commonality of gold has much to do with the Incan religion surrounding the sun. Because of the beautiful reflection that gold casts, it gave the appearance of containing the sun, making the precious metal even more valued in a sun-obsessed society. Gold was reserved for the highest class of Incan society which consisted of priests, lords and of course the Sapa Inca or emperor.\n\n==Politics==\n\nInca government is generally seen as an omnipotent emperor that ruled over a bureaucracy made up of local elites who had been recruited to serve in the state.<ref name=\":1z\">{{Cite book|title=The Incas|last=D'Altroy|first=Terence|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4443-3115-8|location=West Sussex, UK|pages=174}}</ref> This style of rule is often credited to Cuzco's success.<ref name=\":1z\" />\n\nThe Inca empire was adamant about expansion and did so through two imperialism strategies: territorial administration and indirect-hegemonic control. Territorial administration consisted of a complete take over of provinces by reorganizing the economy through increased agricultural production and control of exchange routes via the Incan road system. The territorial administration allowed the Inca empire to put in a great deal of effort to control a new territory in hopes to strengthen the empire by a flow of surplus goods back to the empire core from the overtaken province. Indirect-hegemonic control enabled the Incas to gain control over a province but would allow the local leaders to govern the province. The reason behind this strategy was to gain land and flow of surplus goods back to the empire core without spending a great deal of effort to overtake and govern.<ref name=\":3\">Distant Provinces in the Inka Empire : Toward a Deeper Understanding of Inka Imperialism, edited by Michael A. Malpass, and Sonia Alconini, University of Iowa Press, 2010. ProQuest Ebook Central, <nowiki>https://ebookcentral-.proquest.com/lib/umr-ebooks/detail.action?docID=843228</nowiki>.</ref>\n\nImperial rule was sustained through enforcement by Incan rulers and military troops on a random basis, as well as education of the provincial elite youth of the Incan way of life. Temples and shrines were also constructed in overtaken provinces to inflict Incan religion upon provincial peoples.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Education==\n{{Main|Inca education}}\n[[File:Quipu.png|thumb|Representation of an Incan quipu]]\n\nThe Inca used [[quipu]] or bunches of knotted strings, for accounting and census purposes.  Much of the information on the surviving quipus has been shown to be numeric data; some numbers seem to have been used as mnemonic labels, and the colour, spacing, and structure of the quipu carried information as well.  Since it isn't known how to interpret the coded or non-numeric data, the associated information is considered lost.\n\n==Religion==\n{{Main|Inca religion}}\n\nThe belief system of the Incas was polytheistic. Viracocha, the creator of the universe and Inti, the Sun God, were the most important gods. Viracocha was believed to have created humanity on an island in the middle of [[Lake Titicaca]]. Inti was devoutly loved so much that the Inca people called themselves \"Intip Churin\" which in the Inca language means \"the children of the sun.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe Inca took part in spiritual human sacrifices known as the [[Capacocha]]. These sacrifices were taken out onto mountains all throughout the Andes and placed alive into burial tombs where they were left with items such as figurines, coca leaves, food, alcoholic beverages, and pottery. These offerings were carried out on large mountains where ceremonial sites were constructed, and were believed to have been made for numerous events such as: important festivals, natural phenomenon, and efforts to please the mountain deities. The ''vilca camayos'' were the overseers of the offerings, in which they had decision on where the sacrifices were made and the amount of sacrifices made on each mountain. Mountain deities were worshiped because it was believed that they controlled things like rainfall, water flow and therefore, the abundance and fertility of crops.,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Reinhard|first1=Johan|title=Frozen Mummies of the Andes|date=September 2016|url=http://um9mh3ku7s.search.serialssolutions.com/?ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_enc=info%3Aofi%2Fenc%3AUTF-8&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fsummon.serialssolutions.com&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=FROZEN+MUMMIES+of+the+ANDES&rft.jtitle=Expedition&rft.au=Johan+Reinhard&rft.date=2016-10-01&rft.pub=University+of+Pennsylvania%2C+University+Museum&rft.issn=0014-4738&rft.volume=58&rft.issue=2&rft.spage=8&rft.externalDocID=4187432271&paramdict=en-US|accessdate=18 October 2017}}</ref><ref>[Reinhard, Johan and Constanza Ceruti. \"Sacred Mountains, Ceremonial Sites, and Human Sacrifice among the Incas.\" Archaeoastronomy, vol. 19, June 2005, pp. 1-43. EBSCOhost, libproxy.mst.edu/login?url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=aph&AN=22773113&site=ehost-live.]</ref>\n\n==Other practices==\nThe Inca practiced ''[[artificial cranial deformation|cranial deformation]]''. They achieved this by wrapping tight cloth straps around the heads of newborns in order to alter the shape of their still-soft skulls. These deformations did not result in brain damage. Researchers at the Field Museum believe that the practice was used to mark different ethnicities across the Inca Empire.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fieldmuseum.org/machupicchu/ongoing.html |title=Machu Picchu: Ongoing Investigations<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2006-05-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090317221142/http://www.fieldmuseum.org/machupicchu/ongoing.html |archive-date=2009-03-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Inca preserved bodies through mummification. Bodies were wrapped in the fetal position in cloth or leather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/peru/mummies/mworld2.html|title=NOVA Online {{!}} Ice Mummies of the Inca {{!}} Mummies of the World (2)|website=www.pbs.org|access-date=2017-09-29}}</ref> Rank determined how the Incas were buried. Common people were placed in an open cave or chullpa for possible visiting. Emperors organs were removed and placed in jars separate from their bodies. After preparation they were placed where they most occupied in life.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Incas : new perspectives|last=Francis.|first=McEwan, Gordon|date=2006|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781851095797|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|oclc=63189780}}</ref>\n\n== Agriculture ==\n{{Main|Inca cuisine}}\n[[File:Patates.jpg|left|thumb|Around 200 varieties of Peruvian potatoes were cultivated by the Incas and their predecessors]]\nIt is estimated that the Inca cultivated around seventy crop species.  The main crops were [[potato]]es, [[sweet potato]]es, [[maize]], [[Chile pepper|chili peppers]], [[cotton]], [[tomato]]es, [[peanut]]s, an edible root called [[oxalis tuberosa|oca]], and the [[pseudograin]]s [[quinoa]] and [[amaranth]]. The crops developed by the Inca and preceding cultures makes South America one of the historic centers of [[crop diversity]] (along with the [[Middle East]], [[India]], [[Mesoamerica]], [[Ethiopia]], and the [[Far East]]). Many of these crops were widely distributed by the Spanish and are now important crops worldwide. [[Salsa (sauce)|Salsa]] was originated by the [[Inca people]] using tomatoes, chili peppers, and other spices.\n\nIn the Incan settlement of Vitcos, pollen from maize and quinoa was found in several soil samples which date back as early as the Incan period.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Meseth|first=Enrique|display-authors=etal|date=July 2015|title=Reconstructing Agriculture in Vitcos Inca Settlement, Peru|url=|journal=Irrigation and Drainage|volume=64|issue=3|pages=340\u2013352|via=Database|doi=10.1002/ird.1891}}</ref>\n\nThe Inca cultivated food crops on dry Pacific coastlines, high on the slopes of the Andes, and in the lowland [[Amazon rainforest]]. In mountainous Andean environments, they made extensive use of [[Terrace (agriculture)|terraced]] fields which not only allowed them to put to use the mineral-rich mountain soil which other peoples left fallow, but also took advantage of micro-climates conducive to a variety of crops being cultivated throughout the year. A contributing factor for the ability of the Inca to expand their population and agriculture as quick as they did, was because of a small climate shift that allowed for slightly warmer temperatures and a small increase in annual precipitation.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Chepstow-Lusty|first=A. J.|last2=Frogley|first2=M. R.|last3=Bauer|first3=B. S.|last4=Leng|first4=M. J.|last5=Boessenkool|first5=K. P.|last6=Carcaillet|first6=C.|last7=Ali|first7=A. A.|last8=Gioda|first8=A.|date=2009-07-22|title=Putting the rise of the Inca Empire within a climatic and land management context|journal=Clim. Past|volume=5|issue=3|pages=375\u2013388|doi=10.5194/cp-5-375-2009|issn=1814-9332|doi-access=free}}</ref> This contributed to the Inca's ability to use terraced and irrigated fields in higher elevations, opening up vast amount of the Andes Mountains for Inca agriculture.<ref name=\":0\" /> Agricultural tools consisted mostly of simple [[digging stick]]s. {{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}\n\nThe Inca developed [[Qollqa]]s, a building made of \"adobe, field stone, clay mortar, plaster and pirca\" used for food storage.<ref name=\":1x\">{{Cite journal|last=Brandlin|first=Daniela|last2=Schexnayder|first2=Cliff|title=Lessons in Sustainability from the Inca Empire|journal=Practice Periodical on Structural Design and Construction|language=en|volume=18|issue=1|pages=52\u201355|doi=10.1061/(asce)sc.1943-5576.0000138|year=2013}}</ref> These granaries stored \"maize, quinoa, potatoes, potatoes, chica (maize beer), fruit, salt, fish, tubers, and grain\".<ref name=\":1x\" /> Qollqas allowed for the survival of food supplies in the cold climate of the Andes.<ref name=\":1x\" />\n[[File:Peruvian corn.jpg|thumb|Many varieties of Peruvian maize (corn) were well-known to the Incas for centuries]]\n\nThe Inca also raised [[llama]]s and [[alpaca]]s for their wool, meat, and to use them as pack animals and captured wild [[vicu\u00f1a]]s for their fine hair.\n\nThe [[Inca road system]] was key to farming success as it allowed distribution of foods over long distances. The Inca also constructed vast storehouses, which allowed them to live through [[El Ni\u00f1o]] years while some neighboring civilizations suffered.\n\nInca leaders kept records of what each ''ayllu'' in the empire produced, but did not tax them on their production. They instead used the ''mita'' for the support of the empire.\n\nThe Inca diet consisted primarily of fish and vegetables, supplemented less frequently with the meat of [[guinea pig|cuyes]] (guinea pigs) and camelids. In addition, they hunted various animals for meat, skins and feathers.  Maize was malted and used to make [[chicha]], a fermented alcoholic [[beverage]].\n<!--\n==Currency==\nInca society was based on a [[barter]] system. Workers got labor credit, which was work paid for in goods or food. It was well used in their day. It was a very good system for their needs\n\nW don't know this, we have yet to decipher their accounting system. But its very existence makes barter seem quaint; They may very well have had a credit based system. ...\n[[User:Zenyu|Zenyu]] 18:42, Dec 7, 2004 (UTC) -->\n\n'''\n\n== Economy ==\n\nAccording to Ferreira and Chamot:\n:\"''The social system of the Incas had an ancient Andean origin based on the ayllu, an extended family group with a common ancestor. The economic system was also based on ancient social structures and can be explained through several principles, namely reciprocity, redistribution, and vertical control.''\"\n\nThese authors also add:\n:\"''Redistribution, a practice employed by the state, ensured that all agricultural goods not exchanged by reciprocity were to be distributed in the different areas of the empire in the case of bad crops.''\"<ref>Darget-Chamot, Ferreira ''''''''Cultures and Customs of Peru''; '''Greenwood Press; Westport Ct/London; 2003; pp 13'''</ref>\n\nIn essence, the government of the Inca functioned as a safeguard against mass starvation.\n\nUnlike the Europeans, gold and silver were not used as a form of currency. Instead, clothing and food were distributed by the rulers in exchange for labor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/ancient/lost-inca-empire.html|title=The Lost Inca Empire \u2014 NOVA {{!}} PBS|website=www.pbs.org|access-date=2017-09-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Incan required tribute from those they conquered. Historical records show that agricultural production as well as cloth production increases after Incan conquest.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Costin|first=Cathy Lynne|date=May 1, 2016|title=Who Benefits? Structural Change and lived Experience in the Late Prehispanic Andes|journal=Archeological Papers of the American Anthropological Association|volume=27|pages=120\u2013142|doi=10.1111/apaa.12078}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\nThe \"Qhapaq \u00d1an\" (Inca Road) was largely used and constructed across the Inca Empire. Uses were not only for nobility to spread information and expand the empire, but was also used for soldiers, for transportation of goods, and for private usage. Not only were Incan roads expansive, but they were also well planned and maintained. The Incans made a standard design for the roads and carried out the standard throughout the empire. Roads were built so that they were easily drained to prevent damage of the roads and flooding. The roads were cleaned often by designated maintenance workers.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Garrido|first1=Franciso|title=Rethinking Imperial Infrastructure:A Bottom- up Perspective on the Inca Road|journal=Journal of Anthropological Archaeology|date=September 2016|volume=43|pages=94\u2013109|doi=10.1016/j.jaa.2016.06.001|doi-access=free}}https://ac-els-cdn-com.libproxy.mst.edu/S0278416516300599/1-s2.0-S0278416516300599-main.pdf?_tid=a3b4c3be-aef6-11e7-80a7-00000aab0f02&acdnat=1507776179_8ef75bdf7e76a27dd4b488c65a746988</ref> Lodges for traveling nobles were also constructed alongside the roads. Rest stops called [[Tambo (Incan structure)|tambos]] were built close to roads with water supplies leading to each so that travelers and messengers could have a place to rest and clean water to drink. Military store houses were also built near the roads and kept food for when troops were traveling. Bridges were built across rivers that were too deep to cross, and large flat stones were placed along the sides of roads as markers to distinguish different sections of the roads.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book|title=Incamisana: Engineering an Inca Water Temple|last1=Wright|first1=Kenneth R.|last2=Gibaja Oviendo|first2=Arminda M.|last3=McEwan|first3=Gordon F.|last4=Miksad|first4=Richard W.|last5=Wright|first5=Ruth M.|publisher=American Society of Civil Engineers|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=}}https://ebookcentral-proquest-com.libproxy.mst.edu/lib/umr-ebooks/reader.action?docID=4534226</ref>\n\nThe Inca relied on and worshiped water heavily. A temple was built, the Incamisana, to worship water and the deities granting them water. The temple, as well as many other buildings constructed by the Inca, incorporated aesthetics, underground water conduits, and hydraulic systems. The Inca understood water was needed for agricultural production (used in terraces) and for domestic purposes. The civil engineers of the time for the Inca were tasked with laying out diversion and canal routes to a designated spot, finding what water source would give the desired flow rate, and what elevation the water source would need to be tapped from for gravity to work effectively.<ref name=\":2\" />\nSanitation was also well known by the Inca. The Inca had their own wastewater treatment systems and it is documented that they would collect the human waste to perform land application to help ensure successful harvest seasons.<ref>Bond, T., Roma, E., Foxon, K. M., Templeton, M. R., & Buckley, C. A. (2013). Ancient water and sanitation systems - applicability for the contemporary urban developing world. ''Water Science and Technology, 67''(5), 935-941. doi:<nowiki>http://dx.doi.org.libproxy.mst.edu/10.2166/wst.2013.628</nowiki></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080218042549/http://www.geocities.com/architecture_aztec_america/america_inca_1.htm Inca Architecture]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inca Society}}\n[[Category:Inca]]\n[[Category:South American society]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Pre-Columbian civilization}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2008}}\n{{Weasel|date=February 2010}}\n}}\n\n{{Inca civilization}}\n\nThe '''Inca society''' was the society of the Inca civilization in [[Peru]]. The [[Inca Empire]], which lasted from 1438 to 1533 AD, represented the height of this civilization. The Inca state was known as the [[Kingdom of Cusco]] before 1438. Over the course of the Inca Empire, the rulers used conquest and peaceful assimilation to incorporate in their empire a large portion of western South America, centred on the [[Andes|Andean]] mountain ranges. The empire proved relatively short-lived however: by 1533, [[Atahualpa]], the last [[Sapa Inca]] (emperor) of the Inca Empire, was killed on the orders of the [[conquistador]] [[Francisco Pizarro]], marking the beginning of Spanish rule. The last Inca stronghold, the [[Neo-Inca State]] in [[Vilcabamba, Peru|Vilcabamba]] was conquered by the Spanish in 1572.\n\n==Population==\n\nPopulation estimates for the Tawantinsuyu society range from as few as 4.1 million people to more than 37 million. Most estimates are between 6 and 14 million people. The reason for these various estimates is that, despite that the Inca kept excellent census records using their [[quipus]], knowledge of how to read them has been lost. Almost all of them were destroyed by the Spanish in the course of their conquest and rule.<ref>{{Cite book | last=McEwan | first=Gordon Francis | authorlink=Gordon Francis McEwan | title=The Incas: New Perspectives | year=2006 | publisher=W. W. Norton | location= | isbn=0-393-33301-9 | pages=93\u201396}} There is some debate about the size of the population.</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\nWomen and men had paralleled roles, but were separate in Inca society. They were equally valued for the part they played in their society despite their differing roles.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Powers|first=Karen Vieira|title=Andeans and Spaniards in the Contact Zone: A Gendered Collision|url=|journal=American Indian Quarterly|volume=24|issue=4|pages=511\u2013536|doi=10.1353/aiq.2000.0025|year=2000}}</ref> Marriage was no different.\n\nIncan women were typically married at the age of sixteen, while men married at the age of twenty. Age, however, was not as important as keeping track of the stage of life that a person was at, such as whether or not they were able to work or be married.<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Altroy|first1=Terence|title=The Incas|date=2015|publisher=Wiley Blackwell|location=West Sussex|isbn=9781444331158|page=295|edition=2nd}}</ref> Ranks played a role in a person's marriage status as well. Men of lower rank could only have one wife; people of ranks higher than the [[kuraka]] [[Polygyny|were allowed more]].<ref>{{cite book |author= |title=Incas: lords of gold and glory |publisher=Time-Life Books |location=New York |year=1992 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/incaslordsofgold00time/page/130 130] |isbn=0-8094-9870-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/incaslordsofgold00time/page/130 }}</ref> If a man had more than one wife, one served as the principal wife while the other(s) were considered secondary. Having more wives showed that the man had more labour showing that the household was wealthy. The death of the principal wife was sometimes met with suspicion that the husband played a role in her death. The man had to find a new principal wife before he was able to recover from the previous wife's death.<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Altroy|first1=Terence|title=The Incas|date=2015|publisher=Wiley Blackwell|location=West Sussex, UK|isbn=9781444331158|pages=305\u2013306|edition=2nd}}</ref> To prevent such suspicion and to increase the likelihood of a successful marriage, there were situations in which the couple could test how well the marriage would work out.\n\nTrial marriages were typical of Inca culture. In this type of marriage, the man and woman would agree to try out being married to one another for a few years. At the end of this time, the woman could go home to her parents if she wished, and her husband could also send her home if he did not think it would work out. However, once the marriage was made final, they could only divorce if the woman was childless. To make the marriage final, the provincial governor had to approve the union.<ref name=\"The Incas\">{{cite book|last1=D'Altroy|first1=Terence|title=The Incas|date=2015|publisher=Wiley Blackwell|location=West Sussex, UK|isbn=9781444331158|page=304|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nIn the Inca society, a wedding was a simple event.<ref name=\"The Incas\"/>  Instead, it was looked at more as a business-like agreement. Therefore, marriage was an economic agreement between two families. Parents on either side had to come to an agreement before the marriage took place and the couple could not be directly related to one another.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Silverblatt|first1=Irene|title=Andean Women in the Inca Empire|journal=Feminist Studies|date=October 1978|volume=4|issue=3|page=39|doi=10.2307/3177537|jstor=3177537}}</ref> Women would almost always marry men in the same social class as themselves. However, while it was very rare for them to marry a man with a higher social ranking, it was still possible for some young women. The only way for a young woman to alter her social ranking would be if a man of higher ranking took notice of her.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}\n\nOnce a woman was married, she was expected to collect food and cook, watch over the animals and the children, and to supply cloth to the government. Women of higher ranking also weaved, like those of lower ranks, but their work was used in special clothing for the higher ranks.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Silverblatt|first1=Irene|title=Andean Women in the Inca Empire|journal=Feminist Studios, Inc.|date=Oct 1978|volume=4|issue=3|page=42}}</ref> A man's role sometimes resembled those of a woman, but acted in conjunction with one another.<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Altroy|first1=Terence|title=The Incas|date=2015|publisher=Wiley Blackwell|location=West Sussex, UK|isbn=9781444331158|page=300}}</ref> A woman\u2019s household obligations would not change after she became pregnant. When she did find out she was pregnant she prayed and made offerings to an Inca god, Kanopa.Using marriage as an alliance strategy was also common among the Inca. Even before the Spaniards' arrival, the Inca used marriage as a way to claim themselves to power. After the [[Spanish conquest of the Inca Empire|Spaniards arrival]] the Inca allowed marriages between the Inca and Spaniards in order to gain power during a time of civil war.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Guengerich|first1=Sara Vicuna|title=Capac Women and the Politics of Marriage in Early Colonial Peru|journal=Colonial Latin America Review|date=2015|volume=24|issue=2|pages=147\u2013148|doi=10.1080/10609164.2015.1040275}}</ref>\n\n==Arts==\nThe Inca were a conquering society, and their expansionist assimilation of other cultures is evident in their artistic style.  The artistic style of the Inca utilized the vocabulary of many regions and cultures, but incorporated these themes into a standardized imperial style that could easily be replicated and spread throughout the empire.  The simple abstract geometric forms and highly stylised animal representation in ceramics, wood carvings, textiles and metalwork were all part of the Inca culture.  The motifs were not as revivalist as previous empires. No motifs of other societies were directly used with the exception of [[Huari culture|Huari]] and [[Tiwanaku]] arts.\n\n===Shipbuilding===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Totora titicaca.jpg|thumb|Reproduction of Inca ship sailing on Lake Titicaca in Bolivia]] -->\n\nFor fishing, trade, construction, transport and military purposes, the Inca built seagoing vessels called [[Balsa (ship)|''balsas'']] by weaving together [[totora (plant)|totora]] reeds. The largest of these vessels were 20 to 30 meters long, making them comparable in length to the Spanish ''[[caravel]]'' .{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} This method of constructing ships from woven reeds is an ancient Peruvian tradition which long predates the Inca. There are depictions of such vessels in [[Moche (culture)|Moche]] pottery dating back to 100 A.D.\n\n===Clothing===\n[[File:Tupa-inca-tunic.png|thumb|Inca tunic]]\n\nInca officials wore stylized [[tunic]]s that indicated their status. It contains an amalgamation of motifs used in the tunics of particular officeholders. For instance, the black and white [[checkerboard]] pattern topped with a pink triangle is believed to have been worn by soldiers of the army. Some of the motifs make reference to earlier cultures, such as the stepped diamonds of the [[Huari culture|Huari]] and the three-step stairstep motif of the [[Moche (culture)|Moche]].\n\nCloth was divided into three classes. ''Awaska'' was used for household use, and usually made from [[llama]] wool. Finer cloth, ''qunpi'', was divided into two classes: The first, woven by male ''qunpikamayuq'' (keepers of fine cloth) from [[alpaca]] wool, was collected as tribute from throughout the country and was used for trade. The other class of ''qunpi'' ranked highest. It was woven in the Acllawasi (acllahuasi) by \"aclla\" (female virgins of the sun god temple) from [[vicu\u00f1a]] wool and used solely for royal and religious use.  These had thread counts of 300 or more per inch, unsurpassed anywhere in the world, until the [[Industrial Revolution]] of the 19th century.\n\nAside from the tunic, a person of importance wore a ''[[llawt'u]]'', a series of cords wrapped around the head. To establish his importance, the Inca [[Atahualpa]] commissioned a ''llawt'u'' woven from vampire bat hair. The leader of each [[ayllu]], or extended family, had its own headdress.\n\nIn conquered regions, traditional clothing continued to be worn, but the finest weavers, such as those of [[Chan Chan]], were transferred to Cusco and kept there to weave ''qunpi''. (The [[Chimu|Chim\u00fa]] had previously transferred these same weavers to Chan Chan from [[Sican culture|Sican]].)\n\nThe Incan government controlled all clothing of their society.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} One would receive two outfits of clothing, one formal and one casual pair, and they would then proceed to wear those same outfits until they could literally be worn no longer. Since the government was in such strict control on their clothing, the Incas could not alter their clothing without the permission of the government.\n\n===Jewelry===\nThe wearing of [[jewellery]] was not uniform throughout the empire. Chim\u00fa [[artisan]]s, for example, continued to wear [[earrings]] after their integration into the empire, but in many other regions, usually, only local leaders wore them.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} Jewelry may have been common among the Inca people, however it did not hold as much value to them because labor was the main way people paid each other.<ref name=\"Karen Spalding\">{{cite book|last1=Spalding|first1=Karen|title=Huarochir\u00c3: An Andean Society Under Inca and Spanish Rule|date=1984|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=Stanford, California|isbn=0-8047-1516-5|pages=83\u201384|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kTPgOxyliqQC&pg=PA1&dq=inca+jewelry#v=onepage&q=inca%20jewelry&f=false|accessdate=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ceramics and metalwork===\n[[File:Recipiente Chim\u00fa-Inca caim\u00e1n (M. Am\u00e9rica, Madrid) 01.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Chim\u00fa]]-Inca ceramic from the [[Cultural periods of Peru|Late Horizon]].]]\n\nCeramics were for the most part utilitarian in nature, but also incorporated the imperialist style that was prevalent in the Inca textiles and metalwork.  In addition, the Inca played drums and on woodwind instruments including [[flute]]s, [[pan-pipe]]s and [[trumpet]]s made of shell and ceramics.\n\nThe Inca made beautiful objects of gold, silver, copper, bronze and [[tumbaga]] . But precious metals were in shorter supply than in earlier Peruvian cultures. The Inca metalworking style draws much of its inspiration from [[Chim\u00fa]] art and in fact the best metal workers of [[Chan Chan]] were transferred to Cusco when the Kingdom of [[Chimor]] was incorporated into the empire. Unlike the Chim\u00fa, the Inca do not seem to have regarded metals to be as precious as fine cloth. Nonetheless, the metalworks of the Incas were perhaps the most advanced in America. When the Spanish first encountered the Inca they were offered gifts of ''qunpi'' cloth.\n\nIncan ceramics are usually very distinct and easy to recognize. The shapes of the vessels are highly standardized. The most typical Incan pottery would have a spherical body with a cone shaped base. This spherical body usually includes two vertical side handles with a tall neck and flaring rim. The Incans often would place animal heads on their pottery as well usually near the top of the vessel. There were also several other popular styles for Incan ceramics which included a shallow dish with a single bird head and handle, a pedestal beaker, and a single or double handled bottle.\n\nIncans often decorated their ceramics with a multitude of images and colors. They usually decorated their pottery with bright colors of red, yellow, orange, black and white. Much like all other forms of Incan art, the pottery was often decorated with geometric shapes. The Incans would put diamonds, squares, checkers, triangles, circles and dots on almost all of their ceramic work. Other common themes were animals and insects like llamas, birds, jaguars, alpacas, bees, butterflies as well as block-like humans.\n\nAs part of a tax obligation to the commoners, mining was required in all the provinces. Even though the Inca Empire contained a lot of precious metals, the Incans did not value their metal as much as fine cloth.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} The Incans adopted much of their metal-working characteristics from the metalwork of [[Chimu]]. Because of their expertise in metalworking, after the fall of Chimu many metalworkers were taken back to the capital city of Cuzco to continue their metalworking for the emperor. Copper, tin, gold, and silver were all obtained from mines or washed from the river gravels. These metals would then be handed over to metallurgists. Because the Inca had a system that emphasized political and religious organization, there were many specialized artisans like metallurgists. There were also specialized weavers, cloth makers, pottery makers, and many more. Both copper and bronze would be used for basic farming tools or weapons. Some of the common bronze and copper pieces found in the Incan empire included sharp sticks for digging, club-heads, knives with curved blades, axes, chisels, needles and pins. All of these items would be forged by a metallurgist and then spread throughout the empire.\n\nThe Incans reserved their more precious metals for ornaments and decorations. Gold and silver were common themes throughout the palaces of Incan emperors. It was said that the walls and thrones were covered with gold and that the emperor dined on gold and silver service. These golden plated services would often be inlaid with llamas, butterflies or other creatures. Even beyond the gold and decoration of the emperor\u2019s palace were the ornaments that decorated all of the temples throughout the empire. The temples of the Incans were strewn with sacred and highly precious objects. Headdresses, crowns, ceremonial knives, cups, and a lot of ceremonial clothing were all inlaid with gold or silver.\n\nMany historians{{Who|date=February 2010}} believe that the choice of gold was to distinguish the more \u201csacred\u201d or \u201choly\u201d pieces from others.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} The commonality of gold has much to do with the Incan religion surrounding the sun. Because of the beautiful reflection that gold casts, it gave the appearance of containing the sun, making the precious metal even more valued in a sun-obsessed society. Gold was reserved for the highest class of Incan society which consisted of priests, lords and of course the Sapa Inca or emperor.\n\n==Politics==\n\nInca government is generally seen as an omnipotent emperor that ruled over a bureaucracy made up of local elites who had been recruited to serve in the state.<ref name=\":1z\">{{Cite book|title=The Incas|last=D'Altroy|first=Terence|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4443-3115-8|location=West Sussex, UK|pages=174}}</ref> This style of rule is often credited to Cuzco's success.<ref name=\":1z\" />\n\nThe Inca empire was adamant about expansion and did so through two imperialism strategies: territorial administration and indirect-hegemonic control. Territorial administration consisted of a complete take over of provinces by reorganizing the economy through increased agricultural production and control of exchange routes via the Incan road system. The territorial administration allowed the Inca empire to put in a great deal of effort to control a new territory in hopes to strengthen the empire by a flow of surplus goods back to the empire core from the overtaken province. Indirect-hegemonic control enabled the Incas to gain control over a province but would allow the local leaders to govern the province. The reason behind this strategy was to gain land and flow of surplus goods back to the empire core without spending a great deal of effort to overtake and govern.<ref name=\":3\">Distant Provinces in the Inka Empire : Toward a Deeper Understanding of Inka Imperialism, edited by Michael A. Malpass, and Sonia Alconini, University of Iowa Press, 2010. ProQuest Ebook Central, <nowiki>https://ebookcentral-.proquest.com/lib/umr-ebooks/detail.action?docID=843228</nowiki>.</ref>\n\nImperial rule was sustained through enforcement by Incan rulers and military troops on a random basis, as well as education of the provincial elite youth of the Incan way of life. Temples and shrines were also constructed in overtaken provinces to inflict Incan religion upon provincial peoples.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Education==\n{{Main|Inca education}}\n[[File:Quipu.png|thumb|Representation of an Incan quipu]]\n\nThe Inca used [[quipu]] or bunches of knotted strings, for accounting and census purposes.  Much of the information on the surviving quipus has been shown to be numeric data; some numbers seem to have been used as mnemonic labels, and the colour, spacing, and structure of the quipu carried information as well.  Since it isn't known how to interpret the coded or non-numeric data, the associated information is considered lost.\n\n==Religion==\n{{Main|Inca religion}}\n\nThe belief system of the Incas was polytheistic. Viracocha, the creator of the universe and Inti, the Sun God, were the most important gods. Viracocha was believed to have created humanity on an island in the middle of [[Lake Titicaca]]. Inti was devoutly loved so much that the Inca people called themselves \"Intip Churin\" which in the Inca language means \"the children of the sun.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe Inca took part in spiritual human sacrifices known as the [[Capacocha]]. These sacrifices were taken out onto mountains all throughout the Andes and placed alive into burial tombs where they were left with items such as figurines, coca leaves, food, alcoholic beverages, and pottery. These offerings were carried out on large mountains where ceremonial sites were constructed, and were believed to have been made for numerous events such as: important festivals, natural phenomenon, and efforts to please the mountain deities. The ''vilca camayos'' were the overseers of the offerings, in which they had decision on where the sacrifices were made and the amount of sacrifices made on each mountain. Mountain deities were worshiped because it was believed that they controlled things like rainfall, water flow and therefore, the abundance and fertility of crops.,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Reinhard|first1=Johan|title=Frozen Mummies of the Andes|date=September 2016|url=http://um9mh3ku7s.search.serialssolutions.com/?ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_enc=info%3Aofi%2Fenc%3AUTF-8&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fsummon.serialssolutions.com&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=FROZEN+MUMMIES+of+the+ANDES&rft.jtitle=Expedition&rft.au=Johan+Reinhard&rft.date=2016-10-01&rft.pub=University+of+Pennsylvania%2C+University+Museum&rft.issn=0014-4738&rft.volume=58&rft.issue=2&rft.spage=8&rft.externalDocID=4187432271&paramdict=en-US|accessdate=18 October 2017}}</ref><ref>[Reinhard, Johan and Constanza Ceruti. \"Sacred Mountains, Ceremonial Sites, and Human Sacrifice among the Incas.\" Archaeoastronomy, vol. 19, June 2005, pp. 1-43. EBSCOhost, libproxy.mst.edu/login?url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=aph&AN=22773113&site=ehost-live.]</ref>\n\n==Other practices==\nThe Inca practiced ''[[artificial cranial deformation|cranial deformation]]''. They achieved this by wrapping tight cloth straps around the heads of newborns in order to alter the shape of their still-soft skulls. These deformations did not result in brain damage. Researchers at the Field Museum believe that the practice was used to mark different ethnicities across the Inca Empire.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fieldmuseum.org/machupicchu/ongoing.html |title=Machu Picchu: Ongoing Investigations<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2006-05-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090317221142/http://www.fieldmuseum.org/machupicchu/ongoing.html |archive-date=2009-03-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Inca preserved bodies through mummification. Bodies were wrapped in the fetal position in cloth or leather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/peru/mummies/mworld2.html|title=NOVA Online {{!}} Ice Mummies of the Inca {{!}} Mummies of the World (2)|website=www.pbs.org|access-date=2017-09-29}}</ref> Rank determined how the Incas were buried. Common people were placed in an open cave or chullpa for possible visiting. Emperors organs were removed and placed in jars separate from their bodies. After preparation they were placed where they most occupied in life.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Incas : new perspectives|last=Francis.|first=McEwan, Gordon|date=2006|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781851095797|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|oclc=63189780}}</ref>\n\n== Agriculture ==\n{{Main|Inca cuisine}}\n[[File:Patates.jpg|left|thumb|Around 200 varieties of Peruvian potatoes were cultivated by the Incas and their predecessors]]\nIt is estimated that the Inca cultivated around seventy crop species.  The main crops were [[potato]]es, [[sweet potato]]es, [[maize]], [[Chile pepper|chili peppers]], [[cotton]], [[tomato]]es, [[peanut]]s, an edible root called [[oxalis tuberosa|oca]], and the [[pseudograin]]s [[quinoa]] and [[amaranth]]. The crops developed by the Inca and preceding cultures makes South America one of the historic centers of [[crop diversity]] (along with the [[Middle East]], [[India]], [[Mesoamerica]], [[Ethiopia]], and the [[Far East]]). Many of these crops were widely distributed by the Spanish and are now important crops worldwide. [[Salsa (sauce)|Salsa]] was originated by the [[Inca people]] using tomatoes, chili peppers, and other spices.\n\nIn the Incan settlement of Vitcos, pollen from maize and quinoa was found in several soil samples which date back as early as the Incan period.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Meseth|first=Enrique|display-authors=etal|date=July 2015|title=Reconstructing Agriculture in Vitcos Inca Settlement, Peru|url=|journal=Irrigation and Drainage|volume=64|issue=3|pages=340\u2013352|via=Database|doi=10.1002/ird.1891}}</ref>\n\nThe Inca cultivated food crops on dry Pacific coastlines, high on the slopes of the Andes, and in the lowland [[Amazon rainforest]]. In mountainous Andean environments, they made extensive use of [[Terrace (agriculture)|terraced]] fields which not only allowed them to put to use the mineral-rich mountain soil which other peoples left fallow, but also took advantage of micro-climates conducive to a variety of crops being cultivated throughout the year. A contributing factor for the ability of the Inca to expand their population and agriculture as quick as they did, was because of a small climate shift that allowed for slightly warmer temperatures and a small increase in annual precipitation.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Chepstow-Lusty|first=A. J.|last2=Frogley|first2=M. R.|last3=Bauer|first3=B. S.|last4=Leng|first4=M. J.|last5=Boessenkool|first5=K. P.|last6=Carcaillet|first6=C.|last7=Ali|first7=A. A.|last8=Gioda|first8=A.|date=2009-07-22|title=Putting the rise of the Inca Empire within a climatic and land management context|journal=Clim. Past|volume=5|issue=3|pages=375\u2013388|doi=10.5194/cp-5-375-2009|issn=1814-9332|doi-access=free}}</ref> This contributed to the Inca's ability to use terraced and irrigated fields in higher elevations, opening up vast amount of the Andes Mountains for Inca agriculture.<ref name=\":0\" /> Agricultural tools consisted mostly of simple [[digging stick]]s. {{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}\n\nThe Inca developed [[Qollqa]]s, a building made of \"adobe, field stone, clay mortar, plaster and pirca\" used for food storage.<ref name=\":1x\">{{Cite journal|last=Brandlin|first=Daniela|last2=Schexnayder|first2=Cliff|title=Lessons in Sustainability from the Inca Empire|journal=Practice Periodical on Structural Design and Construction|language=en|volume=18|issue=1|pages=52\u201355|doi=10.1061/(asce)sc.1943-5576.0000138|year=2013}}</ref> These granaries stored \"maize, quinoa, potatoes, potatoes, chica (maize beer), fruit, salt, fish, tubers, and grain\".<ref name=\":1x\" /> Qollqas allowed for the survival of food supplies in the cold climate of the Andes.<ref name=\":1x\" />\n[[File:Peruvian corn.jpg|thumb|Many varieties of Peruvian maize (corn) were well-known to the Incas for centuries]]\n\nThe Inca also raised [[llama]]s and [[alpaca]]s for their wool, meat, and to use them as pack animals and captured wild [[vicu\u00f1a]]s for their fine hair.\n\nThe [[Inca road system]] was key to farming success as it allowed distribution of foods over long distances. The Inca also constructed vast storehouses, which allowed them to live through [[El Ni\u00f1o]] years while some neighboring civilizations suffered.\n\nInca leaders kept records of what each ''ayllu'' in the empire produced, but did not tax them on their production. They instead used the ''mita'' for the support of the empire.\n\nThe Inca diet consisted primarily of fish and vegetables, supplemented less frequently with the meat of [[guinea pig|cuyes]] (guinea pigs) and camelids. In addition, they hunted various animals for meat, skins and feathers.  Maize was malted and used to make [[chicha]], a fermented alcoholic [[beverage]].\n<!--\n==Currency==\nInca society was based on a [[barter]] system. Workers got labor credit, which was work paid for in goods or food. It was well used in their day. It was a very good system for their needs\n\nW don't know this, we have yet to decipher their accounting system. But its very existence makes barter seem quaint; They may very well have had a credit based system. ...\n[[User:Zenyu|Zenyu]] 18:42, Dec 7, 2004 (UTC) -->\n\n'''\n\n== Economy ==\n\nAccording to Ferreira and Chamot:\n:\"''The social system of the Incas had an ancient Andean origin based on the ayllu, an extended family group with a common ancestor. The economic system was also based on ancient social structures and can be explained through several principles, namely reciprocity, redistribution, and vertical control.''\"\n\nThese authors also add:\n:\"''Redistribution, a practice employed by the state, ensured that all agricultural goods not exchanged by reciprocity were to be distributed in the different areas of the empire in the case of bad crops.''\"<ref>Darget-Chamot, Ferreira ''''''''Cultures and Customs of Peru''; '''Greenwood Press; Westport Ct/London; 2003; pp 13'''</ref>\n\nIn essence, the government of the Inca functioned as a safeguard against mass starvation.\n\nUnlike the Europeans, gold and silver were not used as a form of currency. Instead, clothing and food were distributed by the rulers in exchange for labor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/ancient/lost-inca-empire.html|title=The Lost Inca Empire \u2014 NOVA {{!}} PBS|website=www.pbs.org|access-date=2017-09-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Incan required tribute from those they conquered. Historical records show that agricultural production as well as cloth production increases after Incan conquest.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Costin|first=Cathy Lynne|date=May 1, 2016|title=Who Benefits? Structural Change and lived Experience in the Late Prehispanic Andes|journal=Archeological Papers of the American Anthropological Association|volume=27|pages=120\u2013142|doi=10.1111/apaa.12078}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\nThe \"Qhapaq \u00d1an\" (Inca Road) was largely used and constructed across the Inca Empire. Uses were not only for nobility to spread information and expand the empire, but was also used for soldiers, for transportation of goods, and for private usage. Not only were Incan roads expansive, but they were also well planned and maintained. The Incans made a standard design for the roads and carried out the standard throughout the empire. Roads were built so that they were easily drained to prevent damage of the roads and flooding. The roads were cleaned often by designated maintenance workers.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Garrido|first1=Franciso|title=Rethinking Imperial Infrastructure:A Bottom- up Perspective on the Inca Road|journal=Journal of Anthropological Archaeology|date=September 2016|volume=43|pages=94\u2013109|doi=10.1016/j.jaa.2016.06.001|doi-access=free}}https://ac-els-cdn-com.libproxy.mst.edu/S0278416516300599/1-s2.0-S0278416516300599-main.pdf?_tid=a3b4c3be-aef6-11e7-80a7-00000aab0f02&acdnat=1507776179_8ef75bdf7e76a27dd4b488c65a746988</ref> Lodges for traveling nobles were also constructed alongside the roads. Rest stops called [[Tambo (Incan structure)|tambos]] were built close to roads with water supplies leading to each so that travelers and messengers could have a place to rest and clean water to drink. Military store houses were also built near the roads and kept food for when troops were traveling. Bridges were built across rivers that were too deep to cross, and large flat stones were placed along the sides of roads as markers to distinguish different sections of the roads.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book|title=Incamisana: Engineering an Inca Water Temple|last1=Wright|first1=Kenneth R.|last2=Gibaja Oviendo|first2=Arminda M.|last3=McEwan|first3=Gordon F.|last4=Miksad|first4=Richard W.|last5=Wright|first5=Ruth M.|publisher=American Society of Civil Engineers|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=}}https://ebookcentral-proquest-com.libproxy.mst.edu/lib/umr-ebooks/reader.action?docID=4534226</ref>\n\nThe Inca relied on and worshiped water heavily. A temple was built, the Incamisana, to worship water and the deities granting them water. The temple, as well as many other buildings constructed by the Inca, incorporated aesthetics, underground water conduits, and hydraulic systems. The Inca understood water was needed for agricultural production (used in terraces) and for domestic purposes. The civil engineers of the time for the Inca were tasked with laying out diversion and canal routes to a designated spot, finding what water source would give the desired flow rate, and what elevation the water source would need to be tapped from for gravity to work effectively.<ref name=\":2\" />\nSanitation was also well known by the Inca. The Inca had their own wastewater treatment systems and it is documented that they would collect the human waste to perform land application to help ensure successful harvest seasons.<ref>Bond, T., Roma, E., Foxon, K. M., Templeton, M. R., & Buckley, C. A. (2013). Ancient water and sanitation systems - applicability for the contemporary urban developing world. ''Water Science and Technology, 67''(5), 935-941. doi:<nowiki>http://dx.doi.org.libproxy.mst.edu/10.2166/wst.2013.628</nowiki></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080218042549/http://www.geocities.com/architecture_aztec_america/america_inca_1.htm Inca Architecture]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inca Society}}\n[[Category:Inca]]\n[[Category:South American society]]\n", "name_user": "RicardoMontano2323", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inca_society"}
{"title_page": "Premiership of Jason Kenney", "text_new": "{{About|Jason Kenney's time as premier of Alberta and his policies|the membership of the ministry and cabinet|28th Canadian Ministry}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox administration\n| image = File:Jason Kenney - 2018 (41455191460) (cropped).jpg \n| name = Premiership of Jason Kenney \n| term_start = April 30, 2019\n| term_end = \n| premier = Jason Kenney\n| premier_link = Premier of Alberta\n| cabinet =  [[30th Alberta Legislature]]\n| party = [[United Conservative Party]]\n| election = [[2019 Alberta general election]]\n| appointer = [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]]\n| seat = [[Premier of Alberta]]\n| predecessor = [[Rachel Notley]]\n| successor =\n| seal = \n| seal_size = \n| seal_caption = \n| official_url =https://www.alberta.ca/premier.aspx\n}}\n\nThe '''premiership of Jason Kenney''' began on April 30, 2019 when [[Jason Kenney]] and his first [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]] were sworn in by [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]], [[Lois Mitchell]]. Kenney was invited to form the [[30th Alberta Legislature]] and became the [[List of premiers of Alberta|18th Premier of Alberta]], following the [[2019 Alberta general election]] where Kenney's  [[United Conservative Party]] (UCP) won a majority of seats in the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta|Alberta Legislature]] leading to the resignation of Premier [[Rachel Notley]].\n\nBy March 3, 2020 Kenney's approval rate among Albertans had dropped to 47 per cent from 60 per cent in September 2019.<ref name=\"CBC_20200303\">{{Cite web| title = Kenney's popularity drops below 50% in latest Angus Reid poll |work= CBC News|date=March 3, 2020| access-date = March 18, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/angus-reid-kenney-popularity-poll-1.5483820}}</ref> Reasons for the drop in popularity included the UCP's response to the [[2020 Canadian pipeline and railway protests]] which included the bill targeting those who disrupt critical infrastructure with severe penalties. Other concerns included aggressive cuts in the 2019 and 2020 budgets designed to balance the budget and support the oil and gas sector. Reductions to funding for post-secondary institutions and to municipalities and the freeze on spending on health and public schools also raised questions. The provincial government unilaterally changed the way doctors could bill the province and warned that there would be freezes or cuts to government employees in the spring of 2020. Concerns were raised about the cost of the Canadian Energy Centre and about the March 4 decision to \"fully or partially closing 20 provincial parks and seeking \"partnerships\" for 164 more.\" The bill that targeted those who disrupt critical infrastructure with severe penalties also raised concerns.<ref name=\"CBC_20200303\"/>\n\nBy April 7, 2020, a combination of interconnected unprecedented global events\u2014including the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2002 coronavirus pandemic]], the [[coronavirus recession]], the [[2020 stock market crash]], and the [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]] with the \"collapse in oil prices\" represent\u2014what Premier Kenney called\u2014\"the greatest challenge\" in Alberta's \"modern history, threatening its main industry and wreaking havoc on its finances.\"<ref name=\"NaPo_Bloomberg_Orland_20200407\">{{cite news |url=https://nationalpost.com/commodities/energy/alberta-premier-kenney-sees-negative-oil-prices-14-billion-deficit |title=Alberta Premier Kenney sees negative oil prices, $20-billion deficit in 'the greatest challenge of our generation' |work=National Post via Bloomberg News |first=Kevin |last=Orland |date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy April 19, as the collapse in the [[price of oil]] worsened, Alberta's benchmark crude oil\u2014[[Western Canadian Select]]\u2014descended to negative pricing.\n\n==Major events in the first year as Premier==\nThe UCP government moved quickly to repeal the Carbon Tax,<ref name=\"AB_assembly_20190620\"/><ref name=\"AL_20191024\"/> implemented lower corporate taxes with the goal lowering the tax to the lowest in Canada\u2014eight per cent by 2022-23,<ref name=\"Bill3_20190628\"/> to defer arbitration on public sector wages,<ref name=\"CP_CBC_20190620\"/> to commission inquiries into anti-Alberta energy campaigns,<ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI_FAQ\"/><ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI\"/> establish the [[Canadian Energy Centre]]\u2014a 'war room' to battle what the UCP considered to be anti-energy industry propaganda,<ref name=\"CBC_Heydari_20190607\"/> commissioned a report on Alberta's finances by [[Janice MacKinnon]]'s task force, that recommended freezes and cuts that would help to reach the UCP's goal of eliminating the deficit by 2023. The report's mandate did not include the impact of potential revenue if a provincial sales tax were introduced. It focused on slashing health care costs and various measures related to the public sector, including education.<ref name=\"macleans_Markusoff_20190903\"/>\n\n==2019 election==\n{{main|2019 Alberta general election}}\nKenney won the [[2017 United Conservative Party leadership election|United Conservative Party leadership election]] October 28, 2017. He previously represented [[Calgary Midnapore]]. In the [[2019 Alberta general election]] held on April 16, 2019, Kenney won with won 54.88% of the popular vote and 63 seats in the legislature. The [[30th Alberta Legislature|30th]] [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta|Alberta Legislature]] was constituted after the [[2019 Alberta general election|general election on April 16, 2019]].\n\n==Cabinet and Office of the Premier==\n{{main|Executive Council of Alberta}}\n\nOn April 30, the cabinet was sworn in by [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]], [[Lois Mitchell]]. Ministers in the newly-formed cabinet included [[Travis Toews]] who was appointed President of Treasury Board and Minister of Finance on April 30, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alberta.ca |title=Ministry of Treasury Board and Finance |work=Government of Alberta |access-date=October 24, 2019 }}</ref> [[Doug Schweitzer]] as Minister of Justice and Solicitor General,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alberta.ca/justice-and-solicitor-general.aspx |title=Ministry of Justice and Solicitor General |work=Government of Alberta |access-date=October 24, 2019 }}</ref> [[Jason Nixon]] as [[Alberta Environment and Parks|Minister of Environment and Parks]] ,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alberta.ca/environment-and-parks.aspx |title=Ministry of Environment and Parks |work=Government of Alberta |access-date=October 24, 2019 }}</ref> [[Sonya Savage]] as [[Alberta Energy|Minister of Energy]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alberta.ca/energy.aspx |title=Ministry of Energy |work=Government of Alberta |access-date=October 24, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\">{{Cite news| last = Varcoe| first = Chris| title = New Alberta energy minister steps into cabinet's hot seat | work = Calgary Herald| date = May 1, 2019 |access-date=October 24, 2019 |url=https://calgaryherald.com/opinion/columnists/varcoe-albertas-new-energy-minister-has-hands-full-on-day-1}}</ref> Nixon was appointed House Leader, and [[Doug Schweitzer]], [[Ric McIver]], and Savage were appointed as Deputy House Leaders on April 30, 2019.\n\n==30th Legislature - 1st Session (2019)==\n\nDuring the Spring Sitting of the 1st Session of the [[30th Alberta Legislature]], which spanned May through July, 2019, the Kenney government passed about thirteen pieces of legislation, including the Act to Repeal the Carbon Tax,<ref name=\"AB_assembly_20190620\"/><ref name=\"AL_20191024\">{{citation |url=https://www.assembly.ab.ca/pro/bills/20190521_1200_01_bsr.pdf |work=[[30th Alberta Legislature]] |title=Bill Status Report for the 30th Legislature|date= October 24, 2019 | access-date = October 27, 2019 }}</ref> the Alberta Corporate Tax Amendment,<ref name=\"Bill3_20190628\"/> and the [[Public Sector Wage Arbitration Deferral Act]].<ref name=\"CP_CBC_20190620\"/> Premier Kenney established a one-year $2.5 million Public Inquiry into Anti-Alberta Energy Campaigns<ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI_FAQ\">{{Cite web| title = FAQ |series= Public inquiry into anti-Alberta energy campaigns| access-date = September 12, 2019 | url = https://albertainquiry.ca/faq}}</ref><ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI\">{{Cite web| title = Public inquiry into anti-Alberta energy campaigns |series=Anti-Energy campaigns| access-date = September 12, 2019| url = https://albertainquiry.ca/}}</ref> and a Calgary-based $30 million 'war room' to \"fight misinformation related to oil and gas\".<ref name=\"CBC_Heydari_20190607\">{{Cite web| last = Heydari| first = Anis| title = Jason Kenney touts $30M 'war room' but provides few details| work = CBC News| access-date = October 27, 2019| date = June 7, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/jason-kenney-war-room-calgary-1.5167205}}</ref>\n\n===Carbon tax===\nAs promised in his election platform, Premier Kenney's first piece of legislation was Bill 1: [[An Act to Repeal the Carbon Tax]],<ref name=\"AB_assembly_20190620\">{{citation |url=http://www.assembly.ab.ca/pro/bills/20190521_1200_01_bsr.pdf |format=PDF | date = June 20, 2019| access-date = June 20, 2019 |work=Legislative Assembly of Alberta |title=Bill Status Report for the 30th Legislature - 1st Session (2019) |pages=2}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC_AB_20190605\">{{cite news |title=Alberta makes it official: Bill passed and proclaimed to kill carbon tax |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-carbon-tax-repealed-1.5162899 |accessdate=25 July 2019 |date=June 5, 2019}}</ref> which had been put into place in November 2015 during the premiership of Rachel Notley.<ref name=macleans_Tombe_2015>{{cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/economy/economicanalysis/heres-what-we-know-and-dont-know-about-albertas-carbon-tax/|title=Here's what we know\u2014and don't know\u2014about Alberta's carbon tax|work=Macleans|last=Tombe|first=Trevor|access-date=August 5, 2018|date=November 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923202306/https://www.macleans.ca/economy/economicanalysis/heres-what-we-know-and-dont-know-about-albertas-carbon-tax/|archive-date=September 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Premier Kenney was one of four provincial premiers that challenged the constitutionality of [[Carbon pricing in Canada|Canada's carbon tax]].<ref name=\"nationalobserver_Lorinc_20191010\">{{Cite news| date = October 19, 2019| first = John |last=Lorinc | title = The little-known colossus behind the Conservatives' anti-climate agenda| work = National Observer| access-date = October 28, 2019 | url = https://www.nationalobserver.com/2019/10/19/features/little-known-colossus-behind-conservatives-anti-climate-agenda}}</ref>  Kenney has loudly \"denounced\" carbon taxes and threatened \"more legal action\" after a Saskatchewan superior court dismissed the legal \"challenge of the constitutionality of the federal carbon tax.\"<ref name=\"nationalobserver_Lorinc_20191010\"/>  Both Ford and Kenney have increased their criticisms of carbon taxes saying they will \"either trigger a recession or sink the oil patch,\" according to an October 10, 2019 article in ''The National Observer''.<ref name=\"nationalobserver_Lorinc_20191010\"/>\n\nOn October 10, 2019 the UCP tabled Bill 19, the Technology Innovation and Emissions Reduction (TIER) legislation, which is a provincial carbon tax on industrial emitters. Industrial emitters will pay \"$30 per tonne of emissions\" with an estimated reduction in emissions of \"32 megatonnes in 2030.\" The funds collected will go towards \"deficit reduction and technological advancements with respect to climate change.\" There is no carbon tax on consumers.<ref name=\"thestar_Yousif_20191029\">{{cite news |title=Alberta's climate change plan puts $30 per tonne price on carbon for big emitters, in line with federal government |date=October 29, 2019 |access-date=November 1, 2019|first1=Nadine |last1=Yousif |first2=Kieran |last2=Leavitt |url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2019/10/29/alberta-tables-climate-change-plan-puts-30-per-tonne-price-on-carbon-for-big-emitters-in-line-with-federal-government.html |newspaper=The Star Edmonton}}</ref>\n\nPremier Kenney had said that Climate Leadership Plan introduced by Rachel Notley \"crippled the Alberta economy.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Rusnell_20191216\">{{Cite news| last1 = Rusnell| first1 = Charles| first2 = Jennie |last2=Russell|work=CBC News| date = December 16, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019| title = Kenney's claim that carbon tax damaged Alberta economy refuted in court documents | url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/kenney-s-claim-carbon-tax-damaged-alberta-economy-is-refuted-in-court-documents-1.5396454}}</ref> This claim was refuted by the November 15, 2019 Government of Alberta report, \"Economic Assessment of Climate Policy in Alberta,\"<ref name=AB_AEP_20191115>{{Cite report| title = Economic Assessment of Climate Policy in Alberta |isbn=978-1-4601-4622-4 | date = November 15, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019| url = https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/9b7ed960-ab4c-45ab-8d89-d2f5222111cb/resource/dafb5196-147f-464a-99e3-c107f67c3976/download/aep-economic-assessment-of-climate-policy-in-alberta-2019.pdf |pages=60}}</ref> which was submitted by the Kenney's government as a court document to the [[Alberta Court of Appeal]], as part of Alberta's constitutional challenge of the federal government's carbon tax. The Alberta government's \"own analysis\" revealed that Notley's carbon tax economic effect was \"an average reduction in annual growth of Alberta's gross domestic product (GDP) of only 0.05 per cent.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Rusnell_20191216\"/>\n\n===Public inquiry into anti-Alberta energy campaigns===\n\nOn July 4, 2019 Premier Kenney announced a one-year $2.5 million Public Inquiry into Anti-Alberta Energy Campaigns.<ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI_FAQ\"/><ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI\"/> The inquiry, which is led by the former board chair of the Calgary Economic Development\u2014a forensic accountant\u2014Steve Allan, \"has a mandate to investigate foreign-funded efforts.\"<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Clancy_20190909\">{{Cite news| date = September 9, 2019| first = Clare |last=Clancy | title = Public inquiry into international campaigns related to energy launches website |newspaper= Edmonton Journal| access-date = September 12, 2019| url = https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/public-inquiry-into-international-campaigns-related-to-energy-launches-website}}</ref> The inquiry will include interviews, research, and potentially, public hearings.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Clancy_20190909\"/> Kenney announced the creation of the public inquiry along with the \"Energy War Room\" in a release by the UCP party during his election campaign. Kenney cited \"the intrepid reporting of journalist Vivian Krause,\" who has spent ten years examining foreign funding of Canadian environmental non-profit organizations (ENGOs).<ref name=\"UCP_press_release\">{{Cite press release| title = Standing Up for Alberta, Fighting the Foreign-Funded Special Interests| work = [[United Conservative Party]] (UCP)| access-date = September 12, 2019| url = https://www.albertastrongandfree.ca/fighting-the-foreign-funded-special-interests/}}</ref> In the press release, Kenney said that the inquiry may follow up on investigations done in other jurisdictions, including \"the January 6, 2017 Backgrounder for the United States investigation, \"Assessing Russian Activities and Intentions in Recent US Elections\" that contained, \"clear evidence that the Kremlin is financing and choreographing anti-fracking propaganda in the United States.\" He could also include evidence from the March 1, 2018, [[House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology]] report, \"Russian Attempts to Influence U.S. Domestic Energy Markets by Exploiting Social Media\" from the House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology\", which states, \"the Kremlin manipulated various groups in an attempt to carry out its geopolitical agenda, particularly with respect to domestic energy policy.\" Premier Kenney says that \"foreign-funded efforts\" are undermining Alberta's oil and gas sector.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Clancy_20190909\" /><ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI\" /><ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI_FAQ\" /> The backgrounder said that RT ran \"anti-fracking programming, highlighting environmental issues and the impacts on public health.\"<ref name=\"DNI_Background_RU_20170106\">{{Cite report| access-date = September 12, 2019 |title=Background|series=Assessing Russian Activities and Intentions in Recent US Elections: The Analytic Process and Cyber Incident Attribution | url = https://www.dni.gov/files/documents/ICA_2017_01.pdf |date=January 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a talk at [[Manhattan Institute]] in September 12, 2018, \"The Real Fuel of the Future: Natural Gas\", Kenney said that there were \"domestic economic benefits from an expanded shale gas industry,\" but there was a \"potential American upset of the former hegemony in global gas trade.\"<ref name=\"manhattan_institute_20180912\">{{Cite web| title = The Real Fuel of the Future: Natural Gas| work = Manhattan Institute|access-date = September 12, 2019| date = September 12, 2018| url = https://www.manhattan-institute.org/html/real-fuel-future-natural-gas-11467.html}}</ref> In 2018 the media was \"preoccupied\" with [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian social-media meddling in the 2016 U.S. presidential election]]. In 2018 Russia attempted to \"sow discord in our domestic energy debates\".<ref name=\"manhattan_institute_20180912\"/> The March 1, 2018, [[House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology]] report, \"Russian Attempts to Influence U.S. Domestic Energy Markets by Exploiting Social Media\" from the House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology\" said that over \"4,000 social-media accounts linked to Russian entities were engaged in inflaming online debates over pipelines, fossil fuels, and climate change\".<ref name=\"US_20180301\">{{Cite web| last = House Committee on Science| title = Russian Attempts to Influence U.S. Domestic Energy Markets by Exploiting Social Media| access-date = September 12, 2019| date = March 1, 2018| url = https://www.hsdl.org/?abstract&did=}}</ref> Kenney said that these \"fake accounts advocated for 'the complete abandonment of specific fuel sources, such as fossil fuels, by touting exaggerated claims about alternative energy sources,' while sometimes both promoting and mocking climate change, all intended to \u201cgenerate further domestic [U.S.] controversy.\"<ref name=\"manhattan_institute_20180912\"/>\n\nIn September 2019, Vancouver-based [[Ecojustice Canada|Ecojustice]] issued a letter of warning of potential legal challenge to commissioner Allan asking for a response within 30 days.<ref name=\"citynews_Krugel_20190918\">{{Cite news| last = Krugel| first = Lauren| title = Alberta inquiry into oil and gas foes could face legal challenge from Ecojustice| work = The Canadian Press via City News| date = September 18, 2019 |url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2019/09/18/alberta-inquiry-into-oil-and-gas-foes-could-face-legal-challenge-from-ecojustice/ | access-date = October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of Calgary]]'s Martin Olszynski and Shaun Fluker from the Faculty of Law, raised concerns about the Alberta Inquiry \"from the perspective of the rule of law and procedural fairness.\"<ref name=\"ablawg_Koshan_20191217\">{{cite |first1=Jennifer |last1=Koshan |first2=Linda |last2=McKay-Panos |title=The Alberta Inquiry and Freedom of Expression |date=December 17, 2019 | access-date = December 21, 2019|work= ABlawg, Faculty of Law, [[University of Calgary]]|url=http://ablawg.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Blog_JK_LMK_Expression.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref> Their colleagues said that the Inquiry could unjustifiably violate the \"freedom of expression of the Canadian organizations it is aimed at as well as those associated with such organizations, including their members and supporters.\"<ref name=\"ablawg_Koshan_20191217\"/>\n\n===Energy war room===\n{{main|Canadian Energy Centre}}\nIn June 2019, Premier Kenney announced the creation of a Calgary-based $30 million 'war room' to \"fight misinformation related to oil and gas.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Heydari_20190607\"/> In an October 9, 2019 press release, Minister Savage announced the appointment of former journalist and lobbyist [[Tom Olsen]] as CEO and managing director of the war room which will be called the Canadian Energy Centre Limited (CECL).<ref>{{Cite press release| last = Alberta| first = Government of| title = Canadian Energy Centre: Minister Savage Statement| access-date = November 1, 2019| url = https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=64616F41F93C7-0B06-67EF-BFBE0FDF119A4D6A}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = Alberta's energy war room now called Canadian Energy Centre |work= CBC News| access-date = November 1, 2019| date = October 9, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-energy-war-room-tom-olsen-1.5315354}}</ref> \n\nThe Canadian Energy Centre Limited is a private corporation, which means that it is not subject to Alberta's Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act (FOIP Act).<ref name=\"CBC_Bellefontaine_20191010\">{{Cite news| last = Bellefontaine| first = Michelle| title = Incorporation of Alberta's energy war room means much of its operations remain secret |work=CBC News| access-date = November 1, 2019| date = October 10, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/canadian-energy-centre-freedom-of-information-rules-exemption-1.5317360}}</ref> Premier Kenney's press secretary Christine Myatt said that keeping CECL's internal operations secret is a \"tactical and/or strategic advantage to the very foreign-funded special interests the CEC is looking to counter.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bellefontaine_20191010\"/>\n\nCEC's board of directors is composed of Minister Savage, Minister of Justice and Solicitor General, [[Doug Schweitzer]], and [[Jason Nixon]], [[Alberta Environment and Parks|Minister of Environment and Parks]].<ref name=\"CBC_Bellefontaine_20191010\"/>\n\nThe [[Canadian Energy Centre]] (CEC) was launched on December 11 by Premier Kenney, Minister Savage and Olsen at a press conference at the [[Southern Alberta Institute of Technology]] (SAIT).<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\">{{Cite news| title = Logo a no go: Alberta energy war room to pull image belonging to U.S. company |first=Dean |last=Bennett| work =The Canadian Press via Medicine Hat News| access-date = December 21, 2019 |date=December 19, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/news/national-news/2019/12/19/logo-a-no-go-alberta-energy-war-room-to-pull-image-belonging-to-us-company/}}</ref> The CEC will \"highlight achievements in Alberta's oil and gas sector\" and will \"refute what it deems to be misinformation about the industry.\" Kenney said the centre will \"counter misinformation\" \"coming from some environmental groups and others seeking to landlock Alberta's oil and gas\".<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/> On December 11, Olsen described the centre as a place to tell the story of the oil and gas industry in Alberta, which includes rebutting its critics respectfully.<ref name=\"medicinehatnews_20191211_Olsen\">{{Cite news| title = Alberta premier says energy war room will be respectful as it takes on critics| work = Medicine Hat News| access-date = December 21, 2019 |date=December 11, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/news/national-news/2019/12/11/alberta-premier-says-energy-war-room-will-be-respectful-as-it-takes-on-critics/attachment/alberta-premier-says-energy-war-room-will-be-respectful-as-it-takes-on-critics/}}</ref><ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/> \n\nA December 14 ''Medicine Hat News'' opinion piece,<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_Appel_20191214\">{{Cite news| title = Opinion: Energy war room an expensive joke at best| work = Medicine Hat News |first=Jeremy |last=Appel| access-date = December 21, 2019 |date=December 14, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/commentary/opinions/2019/12/14/opinion-energy-war-room-an-expensive-joke-at-best/}}</ref> that was critical of the CEC, said that the centre was not \"subject to freedom-of-information searches and could be used to stifle legitimate dissent and commentary on the oil and gas industry.\" In his December 18 rebuttal, Olson, who is a former ''Calgary Herald'' journalist, said that \"oversight\" of the CEC is \"rigorous\" and that the centre is subject to the Fiscal Planning and Transparency Act, the Whistle Blowers Act and audits by Alberta's auditor general.<ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Olsen_20191218\">{{Cite news| title = Guest Column: Canadian Energy Centre seeks to bring measured tone| work = Medicine Hat News| access-date = December 21, 2019 |date=December 18, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/commentary/opinions/2019/12/18/guest-column-canadian-energy-centre-seeks-to-bring-measured-tone/}}</ref> Olsen said that \"campaigns to shut down new pipeline projects and damage the reputation of our oil and gas industry have received tens of millions of dollars from U.S. environmental foundations.\" This has resulted in the \"landlocking of Alberta energy\" which had resulted in the loss of jobs, \"tens of billions of dollars\" in capital, less money for public services, as well as \"lower value for their shareholders that include many of the country\u2019s biggest pension plans and investment funds.\"<ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Olsen_20191218\"/>\n\nThe CEC logo, which was unveiled at the launch, was also used in the December 11 promotional video, on the CEC's website, \"on the wall of its downtown Calgary office, and on signs\".<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/> By the evening of December 18, \"social media users\" on [[Twitter]] began to share side-by-side versions of the CEC logo and the \"trademarked symbol\" for [[Progress Software|Progress Software Corporation]], the [[Massachusetts]]-headquartered \"software giant\"\u2014[[Progress Software]],<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219\">{{Cite news| title = U.S. software giant checking on logo used by Alberta's energy war room|newspaper = Canadian Press via Medicine Hat News | access-date = December 21, 2019| date = December 19, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/news/national-news/2019/12/19/us-software-giant-checking-on-logo-used-by-albertas-energy-war-room/ |location=Edmonton}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC_News_20191221\">{{Cite news| title = Alberta energy 'war room' discovers its logo was lifted from American software company |first=Jordan |last=Omstead|work= CBC News| access-date = December 21, 2019 |date=December 19, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-energy-war-room-discovers-its-logo-was-lifted-from-american-software-company-1.5403077}}</ref> A December 19 [[Canadian Press]] report said that the icons were \"identical, stylized sharp-angled depictions of what appear to be radiating waves... the Progress one is emerald-green and the war room version is two shades of blue.\"<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/> According to a CP report, the [[Massachusetts]]-headquartered \"software giant\"\u2014[[Progress Software]] sent an email that morning saying that it was \"looking into whether Alberta\u2019s new energy war room has violated the company's trademarked logo.\"<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219\"/><ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/>\n\nIn a December 19 statement, the energy centre's CEO and managing director, [[Tom Olsen]], said that the logo was pulled and was to be replaced.<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/> Olsen said that the \"design debacle\" \"mistake\" was an \"unfortunate situation\".<ref name=\"CBC_News_20191221\"/> He said that the CEC was in \"discussions\" with the marketing agency\u2014Lead & Anchor \"to determine how it happened\".<ref name=\"CBC_News_20191221\"/> The CEC had selected Lead & Anchor over eight other contractors proposed to the CEC by the Calgary marketing agency, Communo.<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Braid_20191219\">{{Cite news| last = Braid| first = Don| date = December 19, 2019|newspaper = Calgary Herald| title = The first war room battle is over a logo | url = https://calgaryherald.com/opinion/columnists/braid-the-first-war-room-battle-is-over-a-logo}}</ref>\n\nSteven Lee, the founder of the [[Foundation for Environmental Stewardship]] (FES) became the first to be \"scrutinized by the centre\".<ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Weber_20191221\">{{Cite web| last = Weber| first = Bob| title = 'Intimidating:' Alberta's energy war room singles out climate campaigner| work = Medicine Hat News| access-date = December 21, 2019| date = December 21, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/news/national-news/2019/12/21/intimidating-albertas-energy-war-room-singles-out-climate-campaigner/}}</ref> Lee was criticized in a December 10 post entitled \"Alberta father irked by charity group that targets fossil fuel industry\" that was posted on the newly-launched CEC website.<ref name=\"CEC_20101210_Airdrie\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta father irked by charity group that targets fossil fuel industry| work = Canadian Energy Centre| access-date = December 21, 2019| date = December 10, 2019| url = https://www.canadianenergycentre.ca/alberta-father-irked-by-charity-group-that-targets-fossil-fuel-industry/}}</ref><ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Weber_20191221\"/> An irate parent was concerned about the presentation and the Three Percent Project handout given to his fifteen-year-old son at his [[Airdrie, Alberta]] school on December 5, 2019.<ref name=\"CEC_20101210_Airdrie\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta father irked by charity group that targets fossil fuel industry| work = Canadian Energy Centre| access-date = December 21, 2019| date = December 10, 2019| url = https://www.canadianenergycentre.ca/alberta-father-irked-by-charity-group-that-targets-fossil-fuel-industry/}}</ref><ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Weber_20191221\"/> Lee received a phone message from a caller saying, \"I'm a reporter with the Canadian Energy Centre. Our website is launching next week and we will be writing a story about the 3% Project, which has raised concerns among some parents who reached out to us following presentations at their children's schools.\"<ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Weber_20191221\"/> The 3% Project is a \"flagship project\" of FES, established by then-19-year-old Steve Lee in 2012.<ref name=\"3percentproject\">{{cite web |url=https://3percentproject.com/ |title=3% Project | access-date = December 21, 2019| date = nd |quote=\"Mobilizing a Generation on Sustainability Solutions: 3% Project is going to schools to provide real, employable skills to youth to help them create sustainability solutions locally.\"}}</ref>\n\n===Bargaining rights bill ===\nOn June 20, 2019, the [[Public Sector Wage Arbitration Deferral Act]] (Bill 9)\u2014informally known as the \"bargaining rights bill was passed into law. Bill 9 was introduced by Minister Toews in order to \"suspend and delay\" hearings related to wage arbitration for public sector workers until after the MacKinnon panel report was submitted.<ref name=\"CP_CBC_20190620\"/> which was passed into law on June 20, 2019.<ref name=\"CP_CBC_20190620\"/><ref name=\"Assembly_AB_20190620\">{{Cite web| title = Bills and Amendments- Legislative Assembly of Alberta|date=| access-date = June 20, 2019| url = https://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=bills_status&selectbill=009&legl=30&session=1}}</ref><ref name=\"AB_Hansard_201906_Bill9\">{{Citation |pages=933\u2013972 | date=June 18, 2019 |work=Alberta Hansard| first3 = Morinville-St| title = Legislative Assembly of Alberta The 30th Legislature | access-date = June 20, 2019 |issn= 0383-3623 |location=Edmonton, Alberta |url=http://www.assembly.ab.ca/ISYS/LADDAR_files/docs/hansards/han/legislature_30/session_1/20190618_1930_01_han.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref>{{rp|933\u2013972}}<ref name=\"CBC_Bellefontaine_20190618\">{{Cite web| first = Michelle |last=Bellefontaine |work=CBC News| title = Opposition accuses UCP of killing debate on controversial bill | access-date = June 18, 2019| date = June 18, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/opposition-accuses-ucp-of-killing-debate-on-controversial-bill-1.5180126}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC_Trynacity_20190614\">{{Cite web| date = June 14, 2019| first = Kim |last=Trynacity |work=CBC News| title = Wage deferral bill could be to the UCP what farm safety was to NDP | access-date = June 18, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/wage-deferral-bill-could-be-to-the-ucp-what-farm-safety-was-to-ndp-1.5176503}}</ref> is a bill, informally known as the \"bargaining rights bill\".<ref name=\"CP_CBC_20190620\">{{Cite web| last = Canadian Press| title = Bargaining rights bill passes after all-night session in Alberta legislature| work = CBC News| access-date = October 27, 2019| date = June 20, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-finance-union-wage-arbitration-hearings-toews-1.5182706}}</ref>  The bill affected Alberta's 180,000 public service employees represented by unions in 24 collective agreements.<ref name=\"CBC_Trynacity_20190614\"/>\n\n===Corporate tax lowered===\nThe Alberta government has set a goal of balancing the budget by 2022-2023.<ref name=\"ABGOV_20190613\">{{Cite web| title = Public sector wage arbitration deferral | date = June 13, 2019| access-date = June 18, 2019| url = https://www.alberta.ca/public-sector-wage-arbitration-deferral.aspx |work=Government of Alberta}}</ref><ref name=\"CTVNews_20190613\">{{Cite web| title = Opposition says new legislation could see province not honour public sector contracts| work = Calgary| access-date = June 18, 2019| date = June 13, 2019| url = https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/opposition-says-new-legislation-could-see-province-not-honour-public-sector-contracts-1.4464658}}</ref> As part of Premier Kenney's \"main strategy to lure investment to the province, stimulate job growth, and resurrect the oilpatch\" promised during his electoral campaign in their April 2019 campaign platform \"Alberta Strong and Free,\"<ref name=\"UCP_Platform_201904\">{{Cite report| publisher = [[United Conservative Party]] (UCP)| pages = 114| title = Alberta Strong and Free Platform| date = April 2019 |access-date=October 27, 2019 |url=https://www.albertastrongandfree.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Alberta-Strong-and-Free-Platform-1.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20191026\">{{Cite news| last = Bakx| first = Kyle| title = Why Husky is getting a tax cut in Alberta and spending big bucks elsewhere| work = CBC News|access-date=October 27, 2019 |date=October 26, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/husky-kenney-sask-nfld-alta-alberta-1.5335823}}</ref> on June 28, 2019, the Job Creation Tax Cut (Alberta Corporate Tax Amendment) Act (Bill 3), introduced by Minister Toews, came into law.<ref name=\"Bill3_20190628\">{{Cite web|title=Bill3: Job Creation Tax Cut| department = Bills and Amendments |work=Legislative Assembly of Alberta|access-date=October 24, 2019 |date=June 28, 2019| url = http://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=bills_status&selectbill=003&legl=30&session=1 |series=30th Legislature, 1st Session (2019)}}</ref> Bill 3 included further reductions in Alberta's corporate tax rate in four stages to lower the \"corporate tax rate for all businesses, from 12 to eight per cent by 2022-23\".<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_French_20190601\">{{Cite web| last = French| first = Janet| title = Economists skeptical of jobs promised by corporate tax cuts| work = Edmonton Journal|access-date=October 24, 2019| date = June 1, 2019 |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/economists-skeptical-of-jobs-promised-by-corporate-tax-cuts}}</ref> The first cut from 12 to 11 per cent\" came into effect on July 1. The second cut of 10 per cent will come into effect on January 2020; a third decrease of nine per cent on January 1, 2021, and a fourth cut of eight per cent cut that come into effect on January 1, 2022.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_French_20190601\"/> Toews repeated the campaign pledge when he announced Bill 13, saying that the \"cuts should create at least 55,000 jobs in Alberta\". As well the Alberta's revised tax rates \u2014will increase the province's \"international competitiveness\" as they will be lower than those of 44 out of 50 American states, according to Toews.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_French_20190601\"/> According to an October 26, 2019 ''CBC News'' article, when Bill 3 \"came into effect on July 1, it gave Alberta the lowest corporate tax rate in Canada.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20191026\"/> Bill 3 \"formalizes\" one of the UCP's election promises.<ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20191026\"/> Several economists were cited by the UCP in their April 2019 Alberta Strong and Free Platform, including [[Jack Mintz]], [[Bev Dahlby]], and [[Aaron Stokes]] of [[Stokes Economics]].<ref name=\"UCP_Platform_201904\"/>{{rp|108}}<ref name=\"Stokes_20190329\">{{citation |title=Stokes Economics Review of UCP Balanced Budget Plan submitted to Jason Kenney, Leader of the United Conservative Party of Alberta |date=March 29, 2019 |first=Aaron |last=Stokes }}</ref> Mintx said that the tax cuts would \"lead to the creation of at least 55,000 full-time private sector jobs\". Dahlby estimated that the cuts would \"generate a $12.7 billion increase in nominal GDP\", a \"6.5% increase in per capita real GDP\", and a \"$1.2 billion in additional government revenues by 2023-24.\"<ref name=\"UCP_Platform_201904\"/>{{rp|20}} The Stokes analysis predicted the \"cut will result in $1 billion less net revenue for the province by 2022-23.\"<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_French_20190601\"/><ref name=\"UCP_Platform_201904\"/> On March 4, 2019, the UCP had announced their intention to cut corporate taxes by one third with a prediction of adding $13 billion to Alberta's economy.<ref name=\"UCP_TaxCuts_20190304\">{{Cite web| work = United Conservative Party |title=UCP Unveils Job Creation Tax Cut |quote=\"One Third Cut to Business Taxes Would Create at Least 55,000 Jobs, Grow Alberta Economy by $13 billion\"|access-date=October 24, 2019 |date=March 4, 2019| url = https://unitedconservative.ca/Article?name=UCPNews_Mar42019&}}</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 2021 the UCP's corporation tax will drop to nine per cent on New Year\u2019s Day 2021 and eight per cent in 2022, which would represent the \"lowest rate in Canada by a 30 per cent margin\".<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Hudes_20200228\"/>\n\nThe UCP's Job Creation Tax Cut was intended to lead to the \"creation of at least 55,000 new jobs, according to economist Jack Mintz.<ref name=\"UCP_TaxCuts_20190304\"/> Since 2009, the unemployment rate in Alberta hit its lowest point\u20144.3 per cent\u2014in September 2013 and its highest\u20149.1 per cent\u2014in November 2016.<ref name=\"economicdashboard\">{{Cite web| title = Unemployment Rate| access-date = December 17, 2019| url = https://economicdashboard.alberta.ca/Unemployment}}</ref> Alberta had experienced boom years in the energy sector starting in 2010,<ref name=\"CBC_Tombe_20190731\">{{Cite news| date = July 31, 2019| first = Trevor |last=Tombe |work=CBC News| title = Why earnings in Alberta have been stagnant for years | access-date = September 9, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/alberta-wages-recession-tombe-1.5229086}}</ref> but this boom was followed by a \"long and deep\" recession that lasted from 2014 to 2017\u2014driven by both low commodity pricing globally and controversial political policies from both the Provincial and Federal Government.<ref name=\"CBC_Tombe_20190731\">{{Cite news| date = July 31, 2019| first = Trevor |last=Tombe |work=CBC News| title = Why earnings in Alberta have been stagnant for years | access-date = September 9, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/alberta-wages-recession-tombe-1.5229086}}</ref> When the UCP government were elected in the spring of 2019, Alberta's economy was still in recovery.<ref name=\"CBC_Tombe_20190731\"/> Overall, by July 2019, about 35,000 jobs had been lost in mining, oil and gas alone.<ref name=\"CBC_Tombe_20190731\"/> Since 2014, sectors that offered high-wage employment of $30 and above, saw about 100,000 jobs disappear\u2014\"construction (down more than 45,000 jobs), mining, oil and gas (down nearly 35,000), and professional services (down 18,000),\" according to the economist, Trevor Tombe.<ref name=\"CBC_Tombe_20190731\"/>In 2013, oil tax revenues brought in 9.58 billion, or 21% of the total Provincial budget,<ref name=\"AlbertaBudget2013\">{{cite web | url=https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/7714457c-7527-443a-a7db-dd8c1c8ead86/resource/5604f999-fa33-4f77-bff4-1b8a189979e1/download/goa-2013-14-annual-report-complete.pdf |title=Alberta 2013-2014 Budget }}</ref> whereas in 2018 it had fallen to just 5.43 billion, or 11% of the Provincial budget.<ref name=\"AlbertaBudget2018\">{{cite web | url=https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/3d732c88-68b0-4328-9e52-5d3273527204/resource/2b82a075-f8c2-4586-a2d8-3ce8528a24e1/download/Budget-2019-Fiscal-Plan-2019-23.pdf#revenue |title=Alberta 2018-2019 Budget}}</ref> In 2013, the energy industry had provided 7.7% of all jobs in Alberta.<ref name=\"economic_results_AB2015\">{{cite web | url=http://www.albertacanada.com/business/overview/economic-results.aspx | title=Economic results | publisher=Government of Alberta | date=October 25, 2015 | accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref>  In 2017, 140,300 jobs representing 6.1% of total employment of 2,286,900 in Alberta in 2017 was due to the energy industry.<ref name=\"GovAB_2018\">{{Cite journal| pages = 10 |url=https://work.alberta.ca/documents/industry-profile-mining-oil-and-gas-extraction.pdf |date=2017 |journal=Alberta Government |title=Industry Profiles 2018 Mining and Oil and Gas Extraction Industry}}</ref> The unemployment rate in Alberta peaked in November 2016 at 9.1%.<ref name=\"economicdashboard\"/> The unemployment rate in the spring of 2019 in Alberta was 6.7% with 21,000 jobs added in April.<ref name=\"StatsCan\">{{Cite web| last = Government Of Canada| first = Statistics Canada| title = Regional unemployment rates used by the Employment Insurance program, three-month moving average, seasonally adjusted| access-date = September 5, 2019| date = May 10, 2019| url = https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/daily-quotidien/190510/t012a-eng.htm}}</ref> By July 2019, the seasonally adjusted unemployment rate had increased to 7.0% and remained at about that level since then.<ref name=\"economicdashboard\"/> By August 2019, the employment number in Alberta was 2,344,000, following the loss of 14,000 full-time jobs in July, which represented  the \"largest decline\" in Canada according to Statistics Canada.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Wyton_20190909\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta economy sheds 14,000 full-time jobs in July |newspaper= Edmonton Journal| access-date = September 6, 2019 |first=Moira |last=Wyton |date=August 9, 2019 | url = https://edmontonjournal.com/news/local-news/alberta-economy-sheds-14000-full-time-jobs-in-july}}</ref> According to Statistics Canada, in November, Alberta lost 18,000 jobs and the unemployment rate was 7.2%,<ref name=\"thinkhq_20191216\"/> \"with declines occurring in a number of industries, led by wholesale and retail trade. On a year-over-year basis, total employment in the province was little changed.\"<ref name=\"GC_SC_20191206\">{{Cite report | work = [[Statistics Canada]], Government of Canada| series = The Daily |title=Labour Force Survey, November 2019| | date = December 6, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019| url = https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/daily-quotidien/191206/dq191206a-eng.htm}}</ref> As UCP popularity declined considerably by December 2019, the polling agency, ThinkHQ Public Affairs Inc., said that \"governments tend to get more blame for the economy when times are tough than they do credit when times are good.\"<ref name=\"thinkhq_20191216\"/>\n\n===Blue Ribbon Panel on Alberta's Finances===\n\nIn August 2019, [[Janice MacKinnon]]'s task force submitted the report commissioned by Premier Kenney, \"Report and Recommendations: Blue Ribbon Panel on Alberta's Finances\".<ref name=\"MacKinnon_201908\">{{Cite report| last = MacKinnon| first = Janice| title = Report and Recommendations: Blue Ribbon Panel on Alberta's Finances |url=https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/081ba74d-95c8-43ab-9097-cef17a9fb59c/resource/257f040a-2645-49e7-b40b-462e4b5c059c/download/blue-ribbon-panel-report.pdf |access-date=November 1, 2019|date=August 2019 |pages=82}}</ref> According to ''[[Maclean's]]'', Premier Kenney had \"mandated\" that the panel \"figure out how to balance the provincial books without raising taxes.\"<ref name=\"macleans_Markusoff_20190903\">{{Cite news| last = Markusoff| first = Jason| title = Jason Kenney's convenient blueprint to fix half of Alberta's fiscal house| work = [[Maclean's]]| date = September 3, 2019 |access-date=November 1, 2019|url=https://www.macleans.ca/economy/jason-kenneys-convenient-blueprint-to-fix-half-of-albertas-fiscal-house/}}</ref> McKinnon, who was Saskatchewan's finance minister, found that \"Alberta spends more per person on its public sector, and compensates its teachers, doctors and other workers more generously, than other major provinces.\"<ref name=\"macleans_Markusoff_20190903\"/> The panel recommended that the post-secondary tuition freeze be lifted, and suggested \"various measures to slash health-care costs and government-wide program reviews.\"<ref name=\"macleans_Markusoff_20190903\"/>\n\n===2019 Budget===\n{{main|Alberta provincial budget, 2019}}\n \nOn October 24, 2019 Minister Toews announced the UCP's first [[Alberta provincial budget, 2019|provincial budget]]. ''[[The National Post]]'' said that it fulfilled their \"promise of slight austerity\" with \"cuts to spending programs and the elimination of hundreds of bureaucracy jobs\".<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> ''The Post'' said that these and the corporate tax cuts \"were the key planks of a four-year plan to bring the budget into balance.\"<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\">{{Cite news| last = Dawson| first = Tyler| title = Jason Kenney\u2019s conservatives deliver the tougher budget they warned Albertans was necessary| work = National Post|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/jason-kenneys-conservatives-deliver-the-tougher-budget-they-warned-albertans-was-necessary|access-date=October 27, 2019 | date=October 24, 2019}}</ref> The goal is to reduce government spending by $4-billion over four years.<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> The 2019-20 budget will \"run a deficit of $8.7 billion\" which is approximately \"$2-billion higher than in 2018-19.\"<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> ''The Post'' said that the changes in post-secondary education were \"significant\" with a 12-per-cent funding cut.<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> and a reduction in \"government grants to post-secondary institutions\".<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> Together that represents a $1.9 billion in cuts in post-secondary education.<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> Post-secondary institutions will be allowed to increase tuition.<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> The Alberta government has set a goal of balancing the budget by 2022-2023.<ref name=\"ABGOV_20190613\"/><ref name=\"CTVNews_20190613\"/>\n\nThe budget decision to de-index disability benefits met with outrage, according to ''The Star''. Many people were \"vocal about their disdain surrounding the UCP\u2019s decision to reverse the [[Assured Income for the Severely Handicapped|Assured Income for the Severely Handicapped]] (AISH)\u2019s tie to inflation\", including [[Arlene Dickinson]], formerly with the [[Dragon Den\u2019s]].<ref name=\"thestar_Yousif_20191025\">{{cite news |title=UCP\u2019s new budget met with outrage over the untying of disability benefits to inflation |date=October 25, 2019 |access-date=November 1, 2019|first1=Nadine |last1=Yousif |url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2019/10/25/ucps-new-budget-met-with-outrage-over-the-untying-of-disability-benefits-to-inflation.html |newspaper=The Star Edmonton}}</ref>\n\nOn October 28, the Minister Toews introduced Bill 20, an omnibus bill which included a clause through which the government of Alberta could withdraw the $1.53-billion grant it had promised for Calgary's [[Green Line (Calgary)|Green Line]] \"with just 90 days' notice and without cause.\"<ref name=\"CBC_20191102\">{{Cite news| title = Largest project in Calgary's history under threat from provincial changes, says Nenshi| work = CBC News| access-date = November 2, 2019| date = November 2, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/green-line-threat-termination-clause-1.5344181}}</ref> \n\nMinister Toews introduced a second omnibus bill, Bill 21, on October 28, as part of his budget that allows the provincial government to \"cancel its master agreement with doctors if the two sides can't negotiate a new deal.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bennett_20191031\">{{Cite news| last = Bennett| first = Dean| title = Alberta doctors call proposed new pay plan cynical and heavy-handed |work= CBC News| access-date = November 2, 2019| date = October 31, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-doctors-criticize-proposed-new-pay-plan-1.5342010}}</ref> In an October 30 open letter to all members of the [[Alberta Medical Association]], Dr. Christine Molnar, AMA director, said that the \"bill effectively gives government the power of pre-approval to cancel any physician services agreement without recourse. This is a violation of the sanctity of contracts.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bennett_20191031\"/> The bill would also give the government control over where new doctors can work starting in March 2022, in order to provide better service to rural areas.<ref name=\"CBC_Bennett_20191031\"/> \n\nAccording to an October 31, 2019 ''CBC News'' article, the UCP is \"working off\" August 2019, [[Janice MacKinnon]]'s August 2019 \"Report and Recommendations: Blue Ribbon Panel on Alberta's Finances\".<ref name=\"CBC_Bennett_20191031\"/>\n\nOn December 3, 2019, [[Moody's Investors Service|Moody's]] downgraded Alberta's credit rating from Aa2 stable from Aa1 negative.<ref name=\"CBC_Rieger_20191204\">{{Cite news| last = Rieger| first = Sarah| title = Moody's downgrades Alberta's credit rating, citing continued dependence on oil |work= CBC News| access-date = December 5, 2019| date = December 4, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/moody-s-alberta-credit-rating-1.5383294}}</ref> According to [[Mount Royal University]]'s political science professor, Duane Bratt, factors influencing the downgrade include the UCP's budget plan that led to an increase in the deficit and concerns about labour unrest with thousands of public sector jobs set to be eliminated.<ref name=\"CBC_Rieger_20191204\"/> Moody's report said that Alberta's economy's \"structural weakness\" lies in its concentration and dependency on [[non-renewable resource]]s (NNRs) combined with a \"lack of sufficient pipeline capacity to transport oil efficiently,\" \"no near-term expectation of a significant rebound in oil-related investments,\"<ref name=\"CBC_Rieger_20191204\"/> and \"revenue pressures related to UCP cuts to corporate tax rates.\"<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Wyton_20191204\">{{Cite web| last = Wyton| first = Moira| title = Finance minister \u2018disappointed\u2019 by decline in Alberta\u2019s credit rating| work = Edmonton Journal| access-date = December 5, 2019| date = December 4, 2019| url = https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/finance-minister-disappointed-by-decline-in-albertas-credit-rating}}</ref> Minister Toews blamed the downgrade on the NDP's tenure, during which the province had also experienced a credit rating downgrade, from its very high credit rating of AAA to Aa1.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Wyton_20191204\"/> Premier Kenney said in an interview that \" financial institutions \u2014 and this apparently includes Moody\u2019s \u2014 are buying into the political agenda emanating from Europe, which is trying to stigmatize development of hydrocarbon energy.\"<ref name=\"globalnews_Toy_20191204\">{{Cite web| last = Toy| first = Adam| title = Financial institutions like Moody\u2019s 'buying into' European political agenda: Kenney| work = Global News| access-date = December 5, 2019| date = December 4, 2019| url = https://globalnews.ca/news/6255402/kenney-danielle-smith-interview-moodys/}}</ref>\n\n==2020 Budget==\nMinister Toews tabled the UCP's second provincial budget on February 27, 2020. Toews said that the $CDN56.8 billion budget is based on an \"anticipated 38 per cent increase in energy royalties.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Hudes_20200228\">{{Cite news| last = Hudes| first = Sammy| title = Alberta budget banks on critical revenue boosts despite market 'volatility,' rising debt| work = Calgary Herald| date = February 28, 2020 |access-date=March 2, 2020 |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/politics/alberta-budget-banks-on-critical-revenue-boosts-despite-market-volatility-rising-debt}}</ref> The increased energy royalties depends heavily on the success of the UCP's corporate tax rate cuts to spur revenue growth through an infusion of capital from private investment and the resulting expansion in both \"oil production and pipeline capacity.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Hudes_20200228\"/> The only other revenue streams in this budget are \"a vaping tax and the extension of a tourism levy on short-term rentals.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Hudes_20200228\"/> David Taras, a [[political scientist]] from [[Mount Royal University]] said that this budget signaled that the UCP was \"not blinking\"\u2014They are \"sticking with [their game plan] the \"policy of cuts and deficit reduction in the face of what appears to be a province that's bleeding jobs.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Hudes_20200228\"/> \n\nThe budget included a proposed 10-year strategy intended to increase tourism spending to $20 billion by 2030, which a Ministry of Economic Development, Trade and Tourism spokesperson said was \"ambitious but reasonable\". \"Only $45 million of the overall ministry budget is [currently] dedicated to tourism\" and millions were cut from the tourism budget in this and previous budgets.<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Smith_20200228\">{{Cite news| last = Smith| first = Alanna | title = Critics say tourism goals set by the province are 'audacious'| work = Calgary herald| date = February 28, 2020 |access-date=March 2, 2020 |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/critics-say-tourism-goals-set-by-the-province-are-audacious}}</ref> The Tourism Industry Association of Alberta chair said that this \"audacious\" plan does not \"reflect\" the \"conversations\" held during the \"pre-budget planning sessions\" the government had with \"hundreds of industry professionals\" in Calgary and Edmonton to \"discuss recommendations with the government on how to boost the tourism industry.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Smith_20200228\"/> Province-wide, the budget cut $53 million from 2020 through 2023, from affordable housing maintenance.<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Nenshi_20200228\">{{Cite news |access-date=March 2, 2020 | work = Calgary Herald| date = February 28, 2020|url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/politics/budget-2020-plans-bow-river-flood-mitigation-no-changes-to-municipal-funding-cuts| last = | first = | title = Nenshi criticizes cut to affordable housing maintenance}}</ref>\n\nThe budget increases homeowners' education property taxes by 3.1 per cent in 2020-2021, which the government predicts will add revenue of \"$102 million to a total of $2.6 billion.\"<ref name=\"globalnews_Gilligan_20200228\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta Budget 2020: breaking down the biggest impacts to Calgary| work = Global News|first=Melissa |last=Gilligan |access-date=March 2, 2020 |date=February 28, 2020 | url = https://globalnews.ca/news/6608148/alberta-budget-2020-calgary-impacts/}}</ref>\n\nOperational funding of $8.2 billion for kindergarten to Grade 12 education will remain at 2019 levels, in spite of population growth and inflation.<ref name=\"globalnews_Gilligan_20200228\"/> \n\nThe  $20.6 billion budgeted for health received the same criticism from the Opposition party.<ref name=\"globalnews_Gilligan_20200228\"/> \n\nIn their February 28, 2020 report, Moody's Investors Service said that the 2020 budget was credit neutral.<ref name=\"moodys_20200228\">{{Cite web| title = Research: Moody's - Alberta\u2019s 2020 budget is credit neutral for the province |work=Moody's|access-date=March 2, 2020 |date=February 28, 2020 || url = https://www.moodys.com/research/Moodys-Albertas-2020-budget-is-credit-neutral-for-the-province--PBC_1216903 |location=Toronto}}</ref> According to Moody's, the UCP fiscal plan is subject to \"significant uncertainties, driven by weak resource sector investments and pipeline projects which are subject to regulatory, political, and other types of delays, much of which is beyond the control of the government.\"\n\nBy April 7, 2020, a combination of interconnected unprecedented global events\u2014including the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2002 coronavirus pandemic]], the [[coronavirus recession]], the [[2020 stock market crash]], and the [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]] and the resulting \"collapse in oil prices\", represent, what Premier Kenney described as \"the greatest challenge\" in Alberta's \"modern history, threatening its main industry and wreaking havoc on its finances.\"<ref name=\"NaPo_Bloomberg_Orland_20200407\">{{cite news |url=https://nationalpost.com/commodities/energy/alberta-premier-kenney-sees-negative-oil-prices-14-billion-deficit |title=Alberta Premier Kenney sees negative oil prices, $20-billion deficit in 'the greatest challenge of our generation' |work=National Post via Bloomberg News |first=Kevin |last=Orland |date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Ministry of Energy ==\n\n[[Sonya Savage]], whose background in energy and the environment includes major projects, such as the [[Enbridge Northern Gateway Pipelines]] and with her work as an executive of [[Canadian Energy Pipeline Association]] (CEPA), was appointed [[Alberta Energy|Minister of Energy]] on April 30, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alberta.ca/energy.aspx |title=Ministry of Energy |work=Government of Alberta |access-date=October 24, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\">{{Cite news| last = Varcoe| first = Chris| title = New Alberta energy minister steps into cabinet's hot seat | work = Calgary Herald| date = May 1, 2019 |access-date=October 24, 2019 |url=https://calgaryherald.com/opinion/columnists/varcoe-albertas-new-energy-minister-has-hands-full-on-day-1}}</ref> She is tasked with overhauling the [[Alberta Energy Regulator]] (AER)\u2014one of the UCP's campaign promises with the aim of implementing \"shorter timelines for project approvals.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/>  On April 30, the UCP proclaimed Bill 12  which gives \"Alberta the power to restrict oil and gas exports to British Columbia.<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/> According to the ''Calgary Herald'', this \"could provoke a quick court challenge\" the Premier of British Columbia, [[John Horgan]].<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/> On April 30, Premier Kenney \"pragmatically backed away\" from the campaign promise to \"remove the 100-megatonne cap on oilsands emissions.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/> According to the ''Calgary Herald'', Bill C-48 regarding an \"oil tanker ban off the northern coast of British Columbia\" threatened the proposed [[Enbridge Northern Gateway Pipelines]] project that Savage had worked on.<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/> She was also involved in \"CEPA's examination of Bill C-69, Ottawa\u2019s overhaul of how major energy projects \u2014 including oil and gas pipelines \u2014 are reviewed by the federal government.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/>\n\nIn February 2019, the previous government signed a [[crude-by-rail]] program agreement with two railway companies\u2014and the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] (CPR) [[Canadian National Railway]] (CNR) with a goal of reducing the [[Western Canadian Select]] price discount that has been exacerbated by the \"lack of pipeline capacity\". Through the four-year, $3.7-billion agreement the \"province would have purchased and shipped 120,000 barrels of crude a day.\"<ref name=\"G&M_Graney_20191027\">{{Cite news| last =Graney| first =  Emma | title = Alberta nears deal to unload crude-by-rail contracts to private sector| work = The Globe and Mail via the Canadian Press|access-date=October 28, 2019 | date=October 27, 2019| url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/article-alberta-in-talks-to-offload-crude-by-rail-contract-to-private-sector/}}</ref> The NDP had estimated that the program would have generated \"revenue of $6-billion\", according to ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''. The Kenney government cancelled the agreement shortly after taking office because the \"financial risks were too high\".<ref name=\"G&M_Graney_20191027\"/> By the end of October 2019 Minister Savage was in ongoing negotiations with the railways related to the \"number and complexity of the contracts.\"<ref name=\"G&M_Graney_20191027\"/> In November, 2019 Premier Kenney visited Texas in a four day trip to create more investment in Alberta's oil and gas industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-what-jason-kenney-and-albertans-can-learn-from-texas/|title=What Jason Kenney and Albertans can learn from Texas|last=Fawcett|first=Max|date=December 1, 2019|website=The Globe and Mail|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''article said, \"A single talisman has defined Jason Kenney\u2019s time as premier of Alberta: oil. A single talisman has defined Jason Kenney's time as premier of Alberta: oil.\"<ref name=\"theglobeandmail_Korol_20200331\">{{Cite news| title = Globe editorial: Why Jason Kenney\u2019s $7.5-billion oil pipeline investment is a risky bet |work= Reuters and The Globe and Mail|first=Todd |last=Korol| access-date =April 7, 2020| url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/editorials/article-why-jason-kenneys-75-billion-oil-pipeline-investment-is-a-risky-bet/ |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>  Kenney campaigned on supporting the oil and gas industries and expanding the pipeline system. By 2018, \"chronic pipeline bottlenecks\" and as a result \"industry and governments millions of dollars a day in lost revenue.\" Following the December 2 announcement of mandatory oil production cut backs in Alberta, the price of WCS rose to c.US$26.65 a barrel.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Canadian Crude Price Spike Won't Last| work = OilPrice.com| accessdate = 2018-12-30| url = https://oilprice.com/Energy/Oil-Prices/Canadian-Crude-Price-Spike-Wont-Last.html}}</ref> The differential between [[Western Canadian Select]]\u2014the benchmark price for Alberta heavy crude\u2014and [[West Texas Intermediate]] (WTI)\u2014which had averaged at US$17 for the decade from 2008 to 2018\u2014widened to a record of around US$50,<ref name=\"theglobeandmail_20181127\">{{Cite news| title = Why Alberta's latest oil-price plunge is unprecedented| access-date = 28 December 2018| url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/industry-news/energy-and-resources/article-why-albertas-latest-oil-price-plunge-is-unprecedented/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |first=Matt |last=Lundy |date=27 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NEB_2020\"/> and the price of WCS plummeted to US$5.90.<ref name=\"economicdashboard_AB_20191223\">{{Cite web| title = Economic Dashboard - Oil Prices| access-date = December 23, 2019| url = https://economicdashboard.alberta.ca/OilPrice}}</ref>  In response, the NDP government under then-Premier [[Rachel Notley]], had set temporary mandatory production limits which resulted in the price of WCS rose to c.US$26.65 a barrel.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Canadian Crude Price Spike Won't Last| work = OilPrice.com| accessdate = 2018-12-30| url = https://oilprice.com/Energy/Oil-Prices/Canadian-Crude-Price-Spike-Wont-Last.html}}</ref> \n\nOn March 24, 2020, as the price of oil plunged more than 5 percent, federal Finance Minister [[Bill Morneau]] announced a program to help the oil industry which would include a \"backstop for banks that lend to the energy sector.\"<ref name=\"G&M_Jones_20200327\">{{Cite news|first=Jeffrey |last=Jones| title = With oil at a record low, government must think about curtailment |work=The Globe and Mail| access-date = April 7, 2020 |date=March 27, 2020| url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/article-with-oil-at-a-record-low-government-must-think-about-curtailment/}}</ref>\n\nBy March 31, 2020, the \"federal government had already bought Trans Mountain\" and was \"committed to getting it built\" and Enbridge's Line 3 was making progress.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail_Korol_20200331\"/> In what Kenney described as a \"bold move to retake control of our province's economic destiny\", the province agreed to help finance the construction of [[TC Energy]]'s [[Keystone Pipeline|Keystone XL oil sands pipeline]] in southern Aberta, Montana, South Dakota and Nebraska with \"agreements for the transport of 575,000 barrels of oil daily\".<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\">{{Cite news| title = Disputed Canada-US Oil Pipeline Work to Start in April |location=[[Billings, Montana]] |work=[[Associated Press|AP]] via [[The New York Times]] |date=March 31, 2020| access-date = April 7, 2020| url = https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/31/world/bc-cn-canada-keystone-xl-pipeline.html}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that \"[d]espite plunging oil prices\" in March\", Kenney said the \"province's resource-dependent economy could not afford for Keystone XL to be delayed until after the coronavirus pandemic and a global economic downturn have passed.\"<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/> Alberta \"has agreed to invest approximately $1.1 billion US as equity in the project, which substantially covers planned construction costs through the end of 2020. The remaining $6.9 billion US is expected to be funded through a combination of a $4.2-billion project-level credit facility to be fully guaranteed by the Alberta government and a $2.7-billion investment by TC Energy.\"<ref name=\"CBC_CP_20200331\">{{Cite news| date = March 31, 2020| work = The Canadian Press via CBC| title = TC Energy to start work on Keystone XL pipeline after $1.1B US Alberta investment| access-date = April 7, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/tc-energy-keystone-xl-pipeline-1.5515850}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/> Kenney has said that the Keystone XL will create \"1,400 direct and 5,400 indirect jobs in Alberta during construction and will reap an estimated $30 billion in tax and royalty revenues for both Alberta and Canada over the next twenty years.<ref name=\"CBC_CP_20200331\"/> \n\nTC Energy \"expects to buy back the Alberta government's investment and refinance the $4.2 billion loan\" when the 1,200-mile (1,930-kilometer) pipeline is operational starting in 2023.<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/> Keystone XL will add up to 830,000 bpd from Western Canada to [[Steele City, Nebraska]]. From there it connects to \"other pipelines that feed oil refineries on the U.S. Gulf Coast.\"<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/> According to the [[Canadian Energy Regulator]], in 2018, Alberta produced 3.91 million bpd of crude oil, which represents 82 per cent of the total production in Canada.<ref name=\"NEB_2020\">{{Cite report| last = Government of Canada| work = [[Canadian Energy Regulator]] formerly National Energy Board| series = Provincial and Territorial Energy Profiles |title=Alberta| access-date = April 7, 2020| url = https://www.cer-rec.gc.ca/nrg/ntgrtd/mrkt/nrgsstmprfls/ab-eng.html}}</ref> \n\nAccording to a March 31, 2020 article in ''[[The New York Times]]'', because of Kenney, [[Russ Girling]], TC Energy CEO, announced that construction of its $8-billion US Keystone XL oil sands pipeline's Canada-United States border crossing, in rural northeast [[Montana]], will begin in April in spite of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/> Concerns were raised by the office of the Montana's Governor, [[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Steve Bullock]] about the added strain on \"rural health resources during the coronavirus pandemic\", with the arrival of a hundred or more pipeline construction workers in rural Montana. At the time of the announcement northeastern Montana had only one confirmed COVID-19 case.<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/>\n\n==Ministry of Education==\n\nIn November 2019, the Calgary Board of Education (CBE) announced it would be cutting the positions of hundreds of teachers following the UCP 2019 cuts to the education funding in the UCP's fall budget,<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> In response, Alberta\u2019s Education Minister Adriana LaGrange said she would launch an \"independent financial audit\" as well as a \"governance review\" of the CBE. LaGrange said that the CBE had used taxpayer dollars recklessly. She said that the \"audit and governance review will give government a path forward on helping the CBE prioritize the classroom and find efficiencies elsewhere in its operations.\"<ref name=\"globalnews_Gilligan_201911120\">{{Cite news| title = Calgary Board of Education to cut 300 temporary teachers amid $32M shortfall |location=Calgary|first= Melissa |last=Gilligan |date=November 20, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019| url = https://globalnews.ca/news/6193545/cbe-cuts-300-temporary-teachers/}}</ref> In early December LaGrange \"provided a \"one-time exception\" on the annual $15 million \"maintenance renewal funding\" to the Alberta Board of Education. This allows school boards to use the funds to reverse the layoffs of 317 temporary teachers.<ref name=\"globalnews_Croteau_20191209\">{{Cite news| title = Calgary Board of Education reverses teacher layoffs while Catholic board hikes school bus fees|first=Jill |last=Croteau | work = Global News| date = December 9, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019| url = https://globalnews.ca/news/6274118/calgary-board-education-school-teacher-layoffs-reverse-bus-fees/}}</ref>\n\n==Ministry of Environment and Parks ==\n{{main|Ministry of Environment and Parks}}\n\nOn March 3, 2020, the [[Ministry of Environment and Parks|Minister of Environment and Parks]], [[Jason Nixon]] said  that the province could not \"continue to spend $86 million of Albertans' tax dollars\" on the \"province's parks, recreation areas and other protected areas\"\u2014areas that bring in only $36 million.<ref name=\"CP_20200304\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta government plans to close 20 parks, hand over 164 others to third parties| work = The Canadian Press via Kimberley Daily Bulletin| access-date = March 18, 2020| date = March 4, 2020| url = https://www.kimberleybulletin.com/news/alberta-government-plans-to-close-20-parks-hand-over-164-others-to-third-parties/}}</ref> An Alberta Parks March 5 statement entitled, \"Optimizing Alberta Parks\", listed changes that would come into effect in 2020 as part of a cost-saving initiative.<ref name=\"albertaparks_20200315\">{{cite press release |title=Optimizing Alberta Parks |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318205752/https://albertaparks.ca/news-events/ |archivedate=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |date=March 5, 2020 |url=https://albertaparks.ca/news-events/}}</ref> <ref name=\"calgaryherald_Corbella_20200305\"/> The UCP government would \"fully or partially close\" \"20 provincial parks\" and was \"planning to hand over 164 others to third-party managers\".<ref name=\"albertaparks_20200315\"/><ref name=\"CP_20200304\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta government plans to close 20 parks, hand over 164 others to third parties| work = The Canadian Press via Kimberley Daily Bulletin| access-date = March 18, 2020| date = March 4, 2020| url = https://www.kimberleybulletin.com/news/alberta-government-plans-to-close-20-parks-hand-over-164-others-to-third-parties/}}</ref> The ''Canadian Press'' said that this represents \"more than one-third of all the province's parks, recreation areas and other protected areas.\"<ref name=\"CP_20200304\"/> The statement included the possibly of selling Crown land.<ref name=\"globalnews_Weber_20200317\">{{Cite news| title = Alberta to sell native grassland despite government promises no Crown land would be sold| work = Global News via the Canadian Press|first=Bob |last=Weber|date=March 17, 2020| access-date = March 18, 2020| url = https://globalnews.ca/news/6689873/alberta-crown-land-for-sale/}}</ref> \n\nIn response to concerns, Nixon said in a March 5 ''Calgary Herald'' interview, \"We are not selling any Crown or public land \u2014 period.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Corbella_20200305\">{{Cite news| title = Alberta Parks are not for sale \u2014 not one square centimetre |newspaper= Calgary Herald| access-date = March 18, 2020| url = https://calgaryherald.com/opinion/columnists/corbella-alberta-parks-are-not-for-sale-not-one-centimeter/ |author=Licia Corbella |date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> According to a March 17 ''Global News'' article, the province listed a 65-hectare plot of land east of [[Taber, Alberta|Taber]] in a March 31 auction with a starting bid of $440,000.<ref name=\"globalnews_Weber_20200317\"/>\n\n==Ministry for Economic Development, Trade and Tourism==\n\nBy April 7, 2020, the Minister of Economic Development, Trade and Tourism [[Tanya Fir]], said that the technology sector would be \"a key part of diversifying Alberta's economy.\" Fir is reviewing recommendations in a report by a Innovation Capital Working Group, a working group of \"tech sector, academic and business leaders\" created by the province in December 2019, to \"develop ways\" to support and grow Alberta's tech sector.<ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20200407\">{{Cite news| date = April 7, 2020| first = Kyle |last=Bakx| title = Why Alberta's devotion to oil is making tech companies want to leave the province |work= CBC News| access-date = April 7, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/tech-alberta-kxl-keystone-1.5523929}}</ref><ref name=\"calgaryherald_Stephenson_20200403\">{{Cite web| title = COVID crisis endangers future of Alberta's tech sector, advocates warn| work = Calgary Herald| access-date = April 7, 2020|first=Amanda |last=Stephenson | url = https://calgaryherald.com/business/local-business/covid-crisis-endangers-future-of-albertas-tech-sector-advocates-warn}}</ref> The UCP eliminated The Interactive Digital Media Tax Credit,  the Capital Investment Tax Credit, and the Alberta Investor Tax Credit, which had provided a \"30 per cent tax credit to investors who put money into specific industries such as clean technology and digital animation.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20200407\"/> Trent Johnsen, a veteran member of Alberta's tech sector, who has been involved with Innovate Calgary among others, said that Alberta was \"betting exclusively on oil and gas. What is Alberta doing to become a successful player in the 21st century of the new economy?\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20200407\"/> \n\n==Public response to Kenney's premiership==\n\nA March 3  CBC article listed the reasons for Kenney's drop in the polls to 47 per cent in March from 60 per cent in September 2019.<ref name=\"CBC_20200303\">{{Cite web| title = Kenney's popularity drops below 50% in latest Angus Reid poll |work= CBC News|date=March 3, 2020| access-date = March 18, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/angus-reid-kenney-popularity-poll-1.5483820}}</ref> This included the blockades as well as the UCP's \"aggressive approach to bolster the province's oil and gas sector and balance the budget through cuts\". Other controversial actions taken by the UCP include, \"cutting funding for post-secondary institutions while lifting the tuition cap\"; \"reducing funding to municipalities; \"imposing unilateral changes to the way doctors bill the province; making clear it wants freezes or cuts to government employees' pay when collective agreements come up for negotiation this spring; spending $30 million per year on a war room now called the Canadian Energy Centre; making its first bill of the new sitting one that targets those who disrupt critical infrastructure with severe penalties; and \"fully or partially closing 20 provincial parks and seeking \"partnerships\" for 164 more.\"<ref name=\"CBC_20200303\"/>\n\n==Response to coronavirus pandemic==\nIn response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alberta]], Premier Kenny declared a state of emergency on March 17, which gives the province or the provincial health authority the right to \"acquire or use property, require a qualified person to help out, authorize the conscription of people needed or authorize the entry into buildings or onto land without a warrant\" under the Public Health Act. Although the order may lapse after 30 days, it can be renewed.<ref name=\"thestar_Boyd_20200317\">{{Cite news| title = Ontario, Alberta and B.C. have declared states of emergency. Here's how that helps |first=Alex |last=Boyd| work = The Star |location=Toronto|date=March 17, 2020 |access-date=March 17, 2020| url = https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/17/alberta-joins-ontario-declares-public-emergency-due-to-coronavirus.html}}</ref> Ontario and British Columbia also declared a state of emergency as the number of cases increased.<ref name=\"thestar_Boyd_20200317\"/> By March 17, there were 23 new cases representing the \"largest day-over-day increase yet in the province\" resulting in total of 97 people in Alberta with the virus.<ref name=\"CTV_Romero_20200317\">{{Cite news| last = Romero| first = Diego| title = Alberta confirms 23 new cases of COVID-19, bringing total to 97| work = Edmonton| access-date = March 17, 2020| date =March 2020| url = https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/alberta-confirms-23-new-cases-of-covid-19-bringing-total-to-97-1.4856621}}</ref> Confirmed cases across the province include 20 in the Calgary zone, 20 in the Edmonton zone, 3 in the Central zone, 1 in the South zone, and 3 in the North zone.<ref name=\"AB_20200317\">{{Cite web| title = COVID-19 info for Albertans| access-date = March 17, 2020 |date=March 17, 2020| url = https://www.alberta.ca/coronavirus-info-for-albertans.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==Polling results==\n\nIn the February 24 to February 28 Angus Reid Institute poll, Kenney's approval rate among Albertans had dropped to 47 per cent from 54 per cent in December 2019<ref name=\"CBC_20200303\"/> and 60 per cent in September 2019.<ref name=\"NaPo_20191130\">{{Cite news| title = Can anything stop Jason Kenney? Alberta premier rides high approval rating as his party gathers for convention |work= National Post| access-date = December 5, 2019| date = November 30, 2019| url = https://nationalpost.com/news/can-anything-stop-jason-kenney |first=Tyler |last=Dawson |location=Edmonton}}</ref> In September he was one of the top-three most-popular premiers in Canada with only Permier Moe of Saskatchewan and Quebec's Fran\u00e7ois Legault winning higher approval ratings by a small margin.<ref name=\"NaPo_20191130\"/>\n\nAccording to a ThinkHQ Public Affairs Inc. poll released on December 16, 2019, Albertans who disapprove of the performance of the UCP government were in the majority at 53 percent,<ref name=\"CBC_20191216\">{{Cite news| date = December 16, 2019| work = CBC News| title = Public approval of UCP government slides 12 points, poll suggests|access-date=December 17, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/ucp-thinkhq-poll-kenney-approval-alberta-honeymoon-end-1.5397567}}</ref> which reflects a \"considerable slide in public approval\" since October.<ref name=\"thinkhq_20191216\">{{Cite web| title = UCP Honeymoon Comes to an End in Alberta: Driven by heightened concerns about jobs, the economy and belt-tightening |work=ThinkHQ Public Affairs Inc. |first=Marc |last=Henry| date = December 16, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019 |location=Calgary| url = https://thinkhq.ca/ucp-honeymoon-comes-to-an-end-in-alberta-driven-by-heightened-concerns-about-jobs-the-economy-and-belt-tightening/}}</ref> Of the respondents who voted for the UCP in spring, 21 per cent disapproved of Kenney by December 16.<ref name=\"CBC_20191216\"/> In ThinkHQ's poll the opposition to the UCP was \"considerably more intense than support\"\u201438 per cent said they strongly disapproved with only 16 per cent strong approving. Reasons for the slide in popularity by December 2019, included growing concerns about both employment and the economy with \"many voters\" concerned with the \"unexpected consequences related to budget-tightening by the new Kenney government.\"<ref name=\"thinkhq_20191216\"/>\n\n==List of premiers==\n{{main|List of premiers of Alberta}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Alberta Energy Regulator]]\n*[[Alberta Geological Survey]]\n*[[Alberta Health Services]]\n*[[Alberta Human Rights Commission]]\n*[[Alberta Municipal Government Board]]\n*[[Alberta Oil Sands Technology and Research Authority]]\n*[[Alberta Parks]]\n*[[Economy of Alberta]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.premier.gov.ab.ca/ Premier of Alberta Official Site]\n\n{{Alberta Assemblies}}\n{{Topics on Alberta}}\n{{Politics of Canadian provinces}}\n{{Alberta politics}}\n\n[[Category:Premiers of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Premierships]]\n[[Category:Politics of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Alberta Legislature]]\n[[Category:Alberta provincial legislation]]\n[[Category:2019 in Alberta]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|Jason Kenney's time as premier of Alberta and his policies|the membership of the ministry and cabinet|28th Canadian Ministry}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox administration\n| image = File:Jason Kenney - 2018 (41455191460) (cropped).jpg \n| name = Premiership of Jason Kenney \n| term_start = April 30, 2019\n| term_end = \n| premier = Jason Kenney\n| premier_link = Premier of Alberta\n| cabinet =  [[30th Alberta Legislature]]\n| party = [[United Conservative Party]]\n| election = [[2019 Alberta general election]]\n| appointer = [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]]\n| seat = [[Premier of Alberta]]\n| predecessor = [[Rachel Notley]]\n| successor =\n| seal = \n| seal_size = \n| seal_caption = \n| official_url =https://www.alberta.ca/premier.aspx\n}}\n\nThe '''premiership of Jason Kenney''' began on April 30, 2019 when [[Jason Kenney]] and his first [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]] were sworn in by [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]], [[Lois Mitchell]]. Kenney was invited to form the [[30th Alberta Legislature]] and became the [[List of premiers of Alberta|18th Premier of Alberta]], following the [[2019 Alberta general election]] where Kenney's  [[United Conservative Party]] (UCP) won a majority of seats in the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta|Alberta Legislature]] leading to the resignation of Premier [[Rachel Notley]].\n\nBy March 3, 2020 Kenney's approval rate among Albertans had dropped to 47 per cent from 60 per cent in September 2019.<ref name=\"CBC_20200303\">{{Cite web| title = Kenney's popularity drops below 50% in latest Angus Reid poll |work= CBC News|date=March 3, 2020| access-date = March 18, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/angus-reid-kenney-popularity-poll-1.5483820}}</ref> Reasons for the drop in popularity included the UCP's response to the [[2020 Canadian pipeline and railway protests]] which included the bill targeting those who disrupt critical infrastructure with severe penalties. Other concerns included aggressive cuts in the 2019 and 2020 budgets designed to balance the budget and support the oil and gas sector. Reductions to funding for post-secondary institutions and to municipalities and the freeze on spending on health and public schools also raised questions. The provincial government unilaterally changed the way doctors could bill the province and warned that there would be freezes or cuts to government employees in the spring of 2020. Concerns were raised about the cost of the Canadian Energy Centre and about the March 4 decision to \"fully or partially closing 20 provincial parks and seeking \"partnerships\" for 164 more.\" The bill that targeted those who disrupt critical infrastructure with severe penalties also raised concerns.<ref name=\"CBC_20200303\"/>\n\nBy April 7, 2020, a combination of interconnected unprecedented global events\u2014including the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2002 coronavirus pandemic]], the [[coronavirus recession]], the [[2020 stock market crash]], and the [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]] with the \"collapse in oil prices\" represent\u2014what Premier Kenney called\u2014\"the greatest challenge\" in Alberta's \"modern history, threatening its main industry and wreaking havoc on its finances.\"<ref name=\"NaPo_Bloomberg_Orland_20200407\">{{cite news |url=https://nationalpost.com/commodities/energy/alberta-premier-kenney-sees-negative-oil-prices-14-billion-deficit |title=Alberta Premier Kenney sees negative oil prices, $20-billion deficit in 'the greatest challenge of our generation' |work=National Post via Bloomberg News |first=Kevin |last=Orland |date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy April 19, as the collapse in the [[price of oil]] worsened, Alberta's benchmark crude oil\u2014[[Western Canadian Select]]\u2014descended to negative pricing.\n\n==Major events in the first year as Premier==\nThe UCP government moved quickly to repeal the Carbon Tax,<ref name=\"AB_assembly_20190620\"/><ref name=\"AL_20191024\"/> implemented lower corporate taxes with the goal lowering the tax to the lowest in Canada\u2014eight per cent by 2022-23,<ref name=\"Bill3_20190628\"/> to defer arbitration on public sector wages,<ref name=\"CP_CBC_20190620\"/> to commission inquiries into anti-Alberta energy campaigns,<ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI_FAQ\"/><ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI\"/> establish the [[Canadian Energy Centre]]\u2014a 'war room' to battle what the UCP considered to be anti-energy industry propaganda,<ref name=\"CBC_Heydari_20190607\"/> commissioned a report on Alberta's finances by [[Janice MacKinnon]]'s task force, that recommended freezes and cuts that would help to reach the UCP's goal of eliminating the deficit by 2023. The report's mandate did not include the impact of potential revenue if a provincial sales tax were introduced. It focused on slashing health care costs and various measures related to the public sector, including education.<ref name=\"macleans_Markusoff_20190903\"/>\n\n==2019 election==\n{{main|2019 Alberta general election}}\nKenney won the [[2017 United Conservative Party leadership election|United Conservative Party leadership election]] October 28, 2017. He previously represented [[Calgary Midnapore]]. In the [[2019 Alberta general election]] held on April 16, 2019, Kenney won with won 54.88% of the popular vote and 63 seats in the legislature. The [[30th Alberta Legislature|30th]] [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta|Alberta Legislature]] was constituted after the [[2019 Alberta general election|general election on April 16, 2019]].\n\n==Cabinet and Office of the Premier==\n{{main|Executive Council of Alberta}}\n\nOn April 30, the cabinet was sworn in by [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]], [[Lois Mitchell]]. Ministers in the newly-formed cabinet included [[Travis Toews]] who was appointed President of Treasury Board and Minister of Finance on April 30, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alberta.ca |title=Ministry of Treasury Board and Finance |work=Government of Alberta |access-date=October 24, 2019 }}</ref> [[Doug Schweitzer]] as Minister of Justice and Solicitor General,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alberta.ca/justice-and-solicitor-general.aspx |title=Ministry of Justice and Solicitor General |work=Government of Alberta |access-date=October 24, 2019 }}</ref> [[Jason Nixon]] as [[Alberta Environment and Parks|Minister of Environment and Parks]] ,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alberta.ca/environment-and-parks.aspx |title=Ministry of Environment and Parks |work=Government of Alberta |access-date=October 24, 2019 }}</ref> [[Sonya Savage]] as [[Alberta Energy|Minister of Energy]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alberta.ca/energy.aspx |title=Ministry of Energy |work=Government of Alberta |access-date=October 24, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\">{{Cite news| last = Varcoe| first = Chris| title = New Alberta energy minister steps into cabinet's hot seat | work = Calgary Herald| date = May 1, 2019 |access-date=October 24, 2019 |url=https://calgaryherald.com/opinion/columnists/varcoe-albertas-new-energy-minister-has-hands-full-on-day-1}}</ref> Nixon was appointed House Leader, and [[Doug Schweitzer]], [[Ric McIver]], and Savage were appointed as Deputy House Leaders on April 30, 2019.\n\n==30th Legislature - 1st Session (2019)==\n\nDuring the Spring Sitting of the 1st Session of the [[30th Alberta Legislature]], which spanned May through July, 2019, the Kenney government passed about thirteen pieces of legislation, including the Act to Repeal the Carbon Tax,<ref name=\"AB_assembly_20190620\"/><ref name=\"AL_20191024\">{{citation |url=https://www.assembly.ab.ca/pro/bills/20190521_1200_01_bsr.pdf |work=[[30th Alberta Legislature]] |title=Bill Status Report for the 30th Legislature|date= October 24, 2019 | access-date = October 27, 2019 }}</ref> the Alberta Corporate Tax Amendment,<ref name=\"Bill3_20190628\"/> and the [[Public Sector Wage Arbitration Deferral Act]].<ref name=\"CP_CBC_20190620\"/> Premier Kenney established a one-year $2.5 million Public Inquiry into Anti-Alberta Energy Campaigns<ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI_FAQ\">{{Cite web| title = FAQ |series= Public inquiry into anti-Alberta energy campaigns| access-date = September 12, 2019 | url = https://albertainquiry.ca/faq}}</ref><ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI\">{{Cite web| title = Public inquiry into anti-Alberta energy campaigns |series=Anti-Energy campaigns| access-date = September 12, 2019| url = https://albertainquiry.ca/}}</ref> and a Calgary-based $30 million 'war room' to \"fight misinformation related to oil and gas\".<ref name=\"CBC_Heydari_20190607\">{{Cite web| last = Heydari| first = Anis| title = Jason Kenney touts $30M 'war room' but provides few details| work = CBC News| access-date = October 27, 2019| date = June 7, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/jason-kenney-war-room-calgary-1.5167205}}</ref>\n\n===Carbon tax===\nAs promised in his election platform, Premier Kenney's first piece of legislation was Bill 1: [[An Act to Repeal the Carbon Tax]],<ref name=\"AB_assembly_20190620\">{{citation |url=http://www.assembly.ab.ca/pro/bills/20190521_1200_01_bsr.pdf |format=PDF | date = June 20, 2019| access-date = June 20, 2019 |work=Legislative Assembly of Alberta |title=Bill Status Report for the 30th Legislature - 1st Session (2019) |pages=2}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC_AB_20190605\">{{cite news |title=Alberta makes it official: Bill passed and proclaimed to kill carbon tax |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-carbon-tax-repealed-1.5162899 |accessdate=25 July 2019 |date=June 5, 2019}}</ref> which had been put into place in November 2015 during the premiership of Rachel Notley.<ref name=macleans_Tombe_2015>{{cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/economy/economicanalysis/heres-what-we-know-and-dont-know-about-albertas-carbon-tax/|title=Here's what we know\u2014and don't know\u2014about Alberta's carbon tax|work=Macleans|last=Tombe|first=Trevor|access-date=August 5, 2018|date=November 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923202306/https://www.macleans.ca/economy/economicanalysis/heres-what-we-know-and-dont-know-about-albertas-carbon-tax/|archive-date=September 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Premier Kenney was one of four provincial premiers that challenged the constitutionality of [[Carbon pricing in Canada|Canada's carbon tax]].<ref name=\"nationalobserver_Lorinc_20191010\">{{Cite news| date = October 19, 2019| first = John |last=Lorinc | title = The little-known colossus behind the Conservatives' anti-climate agenda| work = National Observer| access-date = October 28, 2019 | url = https://www.nationalobserver.com/2019/10/19/features/little-known-colossus-behind-conservatives-anti-climate-agenda}}</ref>  Kenney has loudly \"denounced\" carbon taxes and threatened \"more legal action\" after a Saskatchewan superior court dismissed the legal \"challenge of the constitutionality of the federal carbon tax.\"<ref name=\"nationalobserver_Lorinc_20191010\"/>  Both Ford and Kenney have increased their criticisms of carbon taxes saying they will \"either trigger a recession or sink the oil patch,\" according to an October 10, 2019 article in ''The National Observer''.<ref name=\"nationalobserver_Lorinc_20191010\"/>\n\nOn October 10, 2019 the UCP tabled Bill 19, the Technology Innovation and Emissions Reduction (TIER) legislation, which is a provincial carbon tax on industrial emitters. Industrial emitters will pay \"$30 per tonne of emissions\" with an estimated reduction in emissions of \"32 megatonnes in 2030.\" The funds collected will go towards \"deficit reduction and technological advancements with respect to climate change.\" There is no carbon tax on consumers.<ref name=\"thestar_Yousif_20191029\">{{cite news |title=Alberta's climate change plan puts $30 per tonne price on carbon for big emitters, in line with federal government |date=October 29, 2019 |access-date=November 1, 2019|first1=Nadine |last1=Yousif |first2=Kieran |last2=Leavitt |url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2019/10/29/alberta-tables-climate-change-plan-puts-30-per-tonne-price-on-carbon-for-big-emitters-in-line-with-federal-government.html |newspaper=The Star Edmonton}}</ref>\n\nPremier Kenney had said that Climate Leadership Plan introduced by Rachel Notley \"crippled the Alberta economy.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Rusnell_20191216\">{{Cite news| last1 = Rusnell| first1 = Charles| first2 = Jennie |last2=Russell|work=CBC News| date = December 16, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019| title = Kenney's claim that carbon tax damaged Alberta economy refuted in court documents | url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/kenney-s-claim-carbon-tax-damaged-alberta-economy-is-refuted-in-court-documents-1.5396454}}</ref> This claim was refuted by the November 15, 2019 Government of Alberta report, \"Economic Assessment of Climate Policy in Alberta,\"<ref name=AB_AEP_20191115>{{Cite report| title = Economic Assessment of Climate Policy in Alberta |isbn=978-1-4601-4622-4 | date = November 15, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019| url = https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/9b7ed960-ab4c-45ab-8d89-d2f5222111cb/resource/dafb5196-147f-464a-99e3-c107f67c3976/download/aep-economic-assessment-of-climate-policy-in-alberta-2019.pdf |pages=60}}</ref> which was submitted by the Kenney's government as a court document to the [[Alberta Court of Appeal]], as part of Alberta's constitutional challenge of the federal government's carbon tax. The Alberta government's \"own analysis\" revealed that Notley's carbon tax economic effect was \"an average reduction in annual growth of Alberta's gross domestic product (GDP) of only 0.05 per cent.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Rusnell_20191216\"/>\n\n===Public inquiry into anti-Alberta energy campaigns===\n\nOn July 4, 2019 Premier Kenney announced a one-year $2.5 million Public Inquiry into Anti-Alberta Energy Campaigns.<ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI_FAQ\"/><ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI\"/> The inquiry, which is led by the former board chair of the Calgary Economic Development\u2014a forensic accountant\u2014Steve Allan, \"has a mandate to investigate foreign-funded efforts.\"<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Clancy_20190909\">{{Cite news| date = September 9, 2019| first = Clare |last=Clancy | title = Public inquiry into international campaigns related to energy launches website |newspaper= Edmonton Journal| access-date = September 12, 2019| url = https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/public-inquiry-into-international-campaigns-related-to-energy-launches-website}}</ref> The inquiry will include interviews, research, and potentially, public hearings.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Clancy_20190909\"/> Kenney announced the creation of the public inquiry along with the \"Energy War Room\" in a release by the UCP party during his election campaign. Kenney cited \"the intrepid reporting of journalist Vivian Krause,\" who has spent ten years examining foreign funding of Canadian environmental non-profit organizations (ENGOs).<ref name=\"UCP_press_release\">{{Cite press release| title = Standing Up for Alberta, Fighting the Foreign-Funded Special Interests| work = [[United Conservative Party]] (UCP)| access-date = September 12, 2019| url = https://www.albertastrongandfree.ca/fighting-the-foreign-funded-special-interests/}}</ref> In the press release, Kenney said that the inquiry may follow up on investigations done in other jurisdictions, including \"the January 6, 2017 Backgrounder for the United States investigation, \"Assessing Russian Activities and Intentions in Recent US Elections\" that contained, \"clear evidence that the Kremlin is financing and choreographing anti-fracking propaganda in the United States.\" He could also include evidence from the March 1, 2018, [[House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology]] report, \"Russian Attempts to Influence U.S. Domestic Energy Markets by Exploiting Social Media\" from the House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology\", which states, \"the Kremlin manipulated various groups in an attempt to carry out its geopolitical agenda, particularly with respect to domestic energy policy.\" Premier Kenney says that \"foreign-funded efforts\" are undermining Alberta's oil and gas sector.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Clancy_20190909\" /><ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI\" /><ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI_FAQ\" /> The backgrounder said that RT ran \"anti-fracking programming, highlighting environmental issues and the impacts on public health.\"<ref name=\"DNI_Background_RU_20170106\">{{Cite report| access-date = September 12, 2019 |title=Background|series=Assessing Russian Activities and Intentions in Recent US Elections: The Analytic Process and Cyber Incident Attribution | url = https://www.dni.gov/files/documents/ICA_2017_01.pdf |date=January 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a talk at [[Manhattan Institute]] in September 12, 2018, \"The Real Fuel of the Future: Natural Gas\", Kenney said that there were \"domestic economic benefits from an expanded shale gas industry,\" but there was a \"potential American upset of the former hegemony in global gas trade.\"<ref name=\"manhattan_institute_20180912\">{{Cite web| title = The Real Fuel of the Future: Natural Gas| work = Manhattan Institute|access-date = September 12, 2019| date = September 12, 2018| url = https://www.manhattan-institute.org/html/real-fuel-future-natural-gas-11467.html}}</ref> In 2018 the media was \"preoccupied\" with [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian social-media meddling in the 2016 U.S. presidential election]]. In 2018 Russia attempted to \"sow discord in our domestic energy debates\".<ref name=\"manhattan_institute_20180912\"/> The March 1, 2018, [[House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology]] report, \"Russian Attempts to Influence U.S. Domestic Energy Markets by Exploiting Social Media\" from the House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology\" said that over \"4,000 social-media accounts linked to Russian entities were engaged in inflaming online debates over pipelines, fossil fuels, and climate change\".<ref name=\"US_20180301\">{{Cite web| last = House Committee on Science| title = Russian Attempts to Influence U.S. Domestic Energy Markets by Exploiting Social Media| access-date = September 12, 2019| date = March 1, 2018| url = https://www.hsdl.org/?abstract&did=}}</ref> Kenney said that these \"fake accounts advocated for 'the complete abandonment of specific fuel sources, such as fossil fuels, by touting exaggerated claims about alternative energy sources,' while sometimes both promoting and mocking climate change, all intended to \u201cgenerate further domestic [U.S.] controversy.\"<ref name=\"manhattan_institute_20180912\"/>\n\nIn September 2019, Vancouver-based [[Ecojustice Canada|Ecojustice]] issued a letter of warning of potential legal challenge to commissioner Allan asking for a response within 30 days.<ref name=\"citynews_Krugel_20190918\">{{Cite news| last = Krugel| first = Lauren| title = Alberta inquiry into oil and gas foes could face legal challenge from Ecojustice| work = The Canadian Press via City News| date = September 18, 2019 |url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2019/09/18/alberta-inquiry-into-oil-and-gas-foes-could-face-legal-challenge-from-ecojustice/ | access-date = October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of Calgary]]'s Martin Olszynski and Shaun Fluker from the Faculty of Law, raised concerns about the Alberta Inquiry \"from the perspective of the rule of law and procedural fairness.\"<ref name=\"ablawg_Koshan_20191217\">{{cite |first1=Jennifer |last1=Koshan |first2=Linda |last2=McKay-Panos |title=The Alberta Inquiry and Freedom of Expression |date=December 17, 2019 | access-date = December 21, 2019|work= ABlawg, Faculty of Law, [[University of Calgary]]|url=http://ablawg.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Blog_JK_LMK_Expression.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref> Their colleagues said that the Inquiry could unjustifiably violate the \"freedom of expression of the Canadian organizations it is aimed at as well as those associated with such organizations, including their members and supporters.\"<ref name=\"ablawg_Koshan_20191217\"/>\n\n===Energy war room===\n{{main|Canadian Energy Centre}}\nIn June 2019, Premier Kenney announced the creation of a Calgary-based $30 million 'war room' to \"fight misinformation related to oil and gas.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Heydari_20190607\"/> In an October 9, 2019 press release, Minister Savage announced the appointment of former journalist and lobbyist [[Tom Olsen]] as CEO and managing director of the war room which will be called the Canadian Energy Centre Limited (CECL).<ref>{{Cite press release| last = Alberta| first = Government of| title = Canadian Energy Centre: Minister Savage Statement| access-date = November 1, 2019| url = https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=64616F41F93C7-0B06-67EF-BFBE0FDF119A4D6A}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = Alberta's energy war room now called Canadian Energy Centre |work= CBC News| access-date = November 1, 2019| date = October 9, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-energy-war-room-tom-olsen-1.5315354}}</ref> \n\nThe Canadian Energy Centre Limited is a private corporation, which means that it is not subject to Alberta's Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act (FOIP Act).<ref name=\"CBC_Bellefontaine_20191010\">{{Cite news| last = Bellefontaine| first = Michelle| title = Incorporation of Alberta's energy war room means much of its operations remain secret |work=CBC News| access-date = November 1, 2019| date = October 10, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/canadian-energy-centre-freedom-of-information-rules-exemption-1.5317360}}</ref> Premier Kenney's press secretary Christine Myatt said that keeping CECL's internal operations secret is a \"tactical and/or strategic advantage to the very foreign-funded special interests the CEC is looking to counter.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bellefontaine_20191010\"/>\n\nCEC's board of directors is composed of Minister Savage, Minister of Justice and Solicitor General, [[Doug Schweitzer]], and [[Jason Nixon]], [[Alberta Environment and Parks|Minister of Environment and Parks]].<ref name=\"CBC_Bellefontaine_20191010\"/>\n\nThe [[Canadian Energy Centre]] (CEC) was launched on December 11 by Premier Kenney, Minister Savage and Olsen at a press conference at the [[Southern Alberta Institute of Technology]] (SAIT).<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\">{{Cite news| title = Logo a no go: Alberta energy war room to pull image belonging to U.S. company |first=Dean |last=Bennett| work =The Canadian Press via Medicine Hat News| access-date = December 21, 2019 |date=December 19, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/news/national-news/2019/12/19/logo-a-no-go-alberta-energy-war-room-to-pull-image-belonging-to-us-company/}}</ref> The CEC will \"highlight achievements in Alberta's oil and gas sector\" and will \"refute what it deems to be misinformation about the industry.\" Kenney said the centre will \"counter misinformation\" \"coming from some environmental groups and others seeking to landlock Alberta's oil and gas\".<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/> On December 11, Olsen described the centre as a place to tell the story of the oil and gas industry in Alberta, which includes rebutting its critics respectfully.<ref name=\"medicinehatnews_20191211_Olsen\">{{Cite news| title = Alberta premier says energy war room will be respectful as it takes on critics| work = Medicine Hat News| access-date = December 21, 2019 |date=December 11, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/news/national-news/2019/12/11/alberta-premier-says-energy-war-room-will-be-respectful-as-it-takes-on-critics/attachment/alberta-premier-says-energy-war-room-will-be-respectful-as-it-takes-on-critics/}}</ref><ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/> \n\nA December 14 ''Medicine Hat News'' opinion piece,<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_Appel_20191214\">{{Cite news| title = Opinion: Energy war room an expensive joke at best| work = Medicine Hat News |first=Jeremy |last=Appel| access-date = December 21, 2019 |date=December 14, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/commentary/opinions/2019/12/14/opinion-energy-war-room-an-expensive-joke-at-best/}}</ref> that was critical of the CEC, said that the centre was not \"subject to freedom-of-information searches and could be used to stifle legitimate dissent and commentary on the oil and gas industry.\" In his December 18 rebuttal, Olson, who is a former ''Calgary Herald'' journalist, said that \"oversight\" of the CEC is \"rigorous\" and that the centre is subject to the Fiscal Planning and Transparency Act, the Whistle Blowers Act and audits by Alberta's auditor general.<ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Olsen_20191218\">{{Cite news| title = Guest Column: Canadian Energy Centre seeks to bring measured tone| work = Medicine Hat News| access-date = December 21, 2019 |date=December 18, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/commentary/opinions/2019/12/18/guest-column-canadian-energy-centre-seeks-to-bring-measured-tone/}}</ref> Olsen said that \"campaigns to shut down new pipeline projects and damage the reputation of our oil and gas industry have received tens of millions of dollars from U.S. environmental foundations.\" This has resulted in the \"landlocking of Alberta energy\" which had resulted in the loss of jobs, \"tens of billions of dollars\" in capital, less money for public services, as well as \"lower value for their shareholders that include many of the country\u2019s biggest pension plans and investment funds.\"<ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Olsen_20191218\"/>\n\nThe CEC logo, which was unveiled at the launch, was also used in the December 11 promotional video, on the CEC's website, \"on the wall of its downtown Calgary office, and on signs\".<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/> By the evening of December 18, \"social media users\" on [[Twitter]] began to share side-by-side versions of the CEC logo and the \"trademarked symbol\" for [[Progress Software|Progress Software Corporation]], the [[Massachusetts]]-headquartered \"software giant\"\u2014[[Progress Software]],<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219\">{{Cite news| title = U.S. software giant checking on logo used by Alberta's energy war room|newspaper = Canadian Press via Medicine Hat News | access-date = December 21, 2019| date = December 19, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/news/national-news/2019/12/19/us-software-giant-checking-on-logo-used-by-albertas-energy-war-room/ |location=Edmonton}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC_News_20191221\">{{Cite news| title = Alberta energy 'war room' discovers its logo was lifted from American software company |first=Jordan |last=Omstead|work= CBC News| access-date = December 21, 2019 |date=December 19, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-energy-war-room-discovers-its-logo-was-lifted-from-american-software-company-1.5403077}}</ref> A December 19 [[Canadian Press]] report said that the icons were \"identical, stylized sharp-angled depictions of what appear to be radiating waves... the Progress one is emerald-green and the war room version is two shades of blue.\"<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/> According to a CP report, the [[Massachusetts]]-headquartered \"software giant\"\u2014[[Progress Software]] sent an email that morning saying that it was \"looking into whether Alberta\u2019s new energy war room has violated the company's trademarked logo.\"<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219\"/><ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/>\n\nIn a December 19 statement, the energy centre's CEO and managing director, [[Tom Olsen]], said that the logo was pulled and was to be replaced.<ref name=\"CP_medicinehatnews_20191219a\"/> Olsen said that the \"design debacle\" \"mistake\" was an \"unfortunate situation\".<ref name=\"CBC_News_20191221\"/> He said that the CEC was in \"discussions\" with the marketing agency\u2014Lead & Anchor \"to determine how it happened\".<ref name=\"CBC_News_20191221\"/> The CEC had selected Lead & Anchor over eight other contractors proposed to the CEC by the Calgary marketing agency, Communo.<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Braid_20191219\">{{Cite news| last = Braid| first = Don| date = December 19, 2019|newspaper = Calgary Herald| title = The first war room battle is over a logo | url = https://calgaryherald.com/opinion/columnists/braid-the-first-war-room-battle-is-over-a-logo}}</ref>\n\nSteven Lee, the founder of the [[Foundation for Environmental Stewardship]] (FES) became the first to be \"scrutinized by the centre\".<ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Weber_20191221\">{{Cite web| last = Weber| first = Bob| title = 'Intimidating:' Alberta's energy war room singles out climate campaigner| work = Medicine Hat News| access-date = December 21, 2019| date = December 21, 2019| url = https://medicinehatnews.com/news/national-news/2019/12/21/intimidating-albertas-energy-war-room-singles-out-climate-campaigner/}}</ref> Lee was criticized in a December 10 post entitled \"Alberta father irked by charity group that targets fossil fuel industry\" that was posted on the newly-launched CEC website.<ref name=\"CEC_20101210_Airdrie\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta father irked by charity group that targets fossil fuel industry| work = Canadian Energy Centre| access-date = December 21, 2019| date = December 10, 2019| url = https://www.canadianenergycentre.ca/alberta-father-irked-by-charity-group-that-targets-fossil-fuel-industry/}}</ref><ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Weber_20191221\"/> An irate parent was concerned about the presentation and the Three Percent Project handout given to his fifteen-year-old son at his [[Airdrie, Alberta]] school on December 5, 2019.<ref name=\"CEC_20101210_Airdrie\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta father irked by charity group that targets fossil fuel industry| work = Canadian Energy Centre| access-date = December 21, 2019| date = December 10, 2019| url = https://www.canadianenergycentre.ca/alberta-father-irked-by-charity-group-that-targets-fossil-fuel-industry/}}</ref><ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Weber_20191221\"/> Lee received a phone message from a caller saying, \"I'm a reporter with the Canadian Energy Centre. Our website is launching next week and we will be writing a story about the 3% Project, which has raised concerns among some parents who reached out to us following presentations at their children's schools.\"<ref name=\"medicinehatnews_Weber_20191221\"/> The 3% Project is a \"flagship project\" of FES, established by then-19-year-old Steve Lee in 2012.<ref name=\"3percentproject\">{{cite web |url=https://3percentproject.com/ |title=3% Project | access-date = December 21, 2019| date = nd |quote=\"Mobilizing a Generation on Sustainability Solutions: 3% Project is going to schools to provide real, employable skills to youth to help them create sustainability solutions locally.\"}}</ref>\n\n===Bargaining rights bill ===\nOn June 20, 2019, the [[Public Sector Wage Arbitration Deferral Act]] (Bill 9)\u2014informally known as the \"bargaining rights bill was passed into law. Bill 9 was introduced by Minister Toews in order to \"suspend and delay\" hearings related to wage arbitration for public sector workers until after the MacKinnon panel report was submitted.<ref name=\"CP_CBC_20190620\"/> which was passed into law on June 20, 2019.<ref name=\"CP_CBC_20190620\"/><ref name=\"Assembly_AB_20190620\">{{Cite web| title = Bills and Amendments- Legislative Assembly of Alberta|date=| access-date = June 20, 2019| url = https://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=bills_status&selectbill=009&legl=30&session=1}}</ref><ref name=\"AB_Hansard_201906_Bill9\">{{Citation |pages=933\u2013972 | date=June 18, 2019 |work=Alberta Hansard| first3 = Morinville-St| title = Legislative Assembly of Alberta The 30th Legislature | access-date = June 20, 2019 |issn= 0383-3623 |location=Edmonton, Alberta |url=http://www.assembly.ab.ca/ISYS/LADDAR_files/docs/hansards/han/legislature_30/session_1/20190618_1930_01_han.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref>{{rp|933\u2013972}}<ref name=\"CBC_Bellefontaine_20190618\">{{Cite web| first = Michelle |last=Bellefontaine |work=CBC News| title = Opposition accuses UCP of killing debate on controversial bill | access-date = June 18, 2019| date = June 18, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/opposition-accuses-ucp-of-killing-debate-on-controversial-bill-1.5180126}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC_Trynacity_20190614\">{{Cite web| date = June 14, 2019| first = Kim |last=Trynacity |work=CBC News| title = Wage deferral bill could be to the UCP what farm safety was to NDP | access-date = June 18, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/wage-deferral-bill-could-be-to-the-ucp-what-farm-safety-was-to-ndp-1.5176503}}</ref> is a bill, informally known as the \"bargaining rights bill\".<ref name=\"CP_CBC_20190620\">{{Cite web| last = Canadian Press| title = Bargaining rights bill passes after all-night session in Alberta legislature| work = CBC News| access-date = October 27, 2019| date = June 20, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-finance-union-wage-arbitration-hearings-toews-1.5182706}}</ref>  The bill affected Alberta's 180,000 public service employees represented by unions in 24 collective agreements,<ref name=\"CBC_Trynacity_20190614\"/>\n\n===Corporate tax lowered===\nThe Alberta government has set a goal of balancing the budget by 2022-2023.<ref name=\"ABGOV_20190613\">{{Cite web| title = Public sector wage arbitration deferral | date = June 13, 2019| access-date = June 18, 2019| url = https://www.alberta.ca/public-sector-wage-arbitration-deferral.aspx |work=Government of Alberta}}</ref><ref name=\"CTVNews_20190613\">{{Cite web| title = Opposition says new legislation could see province not honour public sector contracts| work = Calgary| access-date = June 18, 2019| date = June 13, 2019| url = https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/opposition-says-new-legislation-could-see-province-not-honour-public-sector-contracts-1.4464658}}</ref> As part of Premier Kenney's \"main strategy to lure investment to the province, stimulate job growth, and resurrect the oilpatch\" promised during his electoral campaign in their April 2019 campaign platform \"Alberta Strong and Free,\"<ref name=\"UCP_Platform_201904\">{{Cite report| publisher = [[United Conservative Party]] (UCP)| pages = 114| title = Alberta Strong and Free Platform| date = April 2019 |access-date=October 27, 2019 |url=https://www.albertastrongandfree.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Alberta-Strong-and-Free-Platform-1.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20191026\">{{Cite news| last = Bakx| first = Kyle| title = Why Husky is getting a tax cut in Alberta and spending big bucks elsewhere| work = CBC News|access-date=October 27, 2019 |date=October 26, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/husky-kenney-sask-nfld-alta-alberta-1.5335823}}</ref> on June 28, 2019, the Job Creation Tax Cut (Alberta Corporate Tax Amendment) Act (Bill 3), introduced by Minister Toews, came into law.<ref name=\"Bill3_20190628\">{{Cite web|title=Bill3: Job Creation Tax Cut| department = Bills and Amendments |work=Legislative Assembly of Alberta|access-date=October 24, 2019 |date=June 28, 2019| url = http://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=bills_status&selectbill=003&legl=30&session=1 |series=30th Legislature, 1st Session (2019)}}</ref> Bill 3 included further reductions in Alberta's corporate tax rate in four stages to lower the \"corporate tax rate for all businesses, from 12 to eight per cent by 2022-23\".<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_French_20190601\">{{Cite web| last = French| first = Janet| title = Economists skeptical of jobs promised by corporate tax cuts| work = Edmonton Journal|access-date=October 24, 2019| date = June 1, 2019 |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/economists-skeptical-of-jobs-promised-by-corporate-tax-cuts}}</ref> The first cut from 12 to 11 per cent\" came into effect on July 1. The second cut of 10 per cent will come into effect on January 2020; a third decrease of nine per cent on January 1, 2021, and a fourth cut of eight per cent cut that come into effect on January 1, 2022.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_French_20190601\"/> Toews repeated the campaign pledge when he announced Bill 13, saying that the \"cuts should create at least 55,000 jobs in Alberta\". As well the Alberta's revised tax rates \u2014will increase the province's \"international competitiveness\" as they will be lower than those of 44 out of 50 American states, according to Toews.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_French_20190601\"/> According to an October 26, 2019 ''CBC News'' article, when Bill 3 \"came into effect on July 1, it gave Alberta the lowest corporate tax rate in Canada.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20191026\"/> Bill 3 \"formalizes\" one of the UCP's election promises.<ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20191026\"/> Several economists were cited by the UCP in their April 2019 Alberta Strong and Free Platform, including [[Jack Mintz]], [[Bev Dahlby]], and [[Aaron Stokes]] of [[Stokes Economics]].<ref name=\"UCP_Platform_201904\"/>{{rp|108}}<ref name=\"Stokes_20190329\">{{citation |title=Stokes Economics Review of UCP Balanced Budget Plan submitted to Jason Kenney, Leader of the United Conservative Party of Alberta |date=March 29, 2019 |first=Aaron |last=Stokes }}</ref> Mintx said that the tax cuts would \"lead to the creation of at least 55,000 full-time private sector jobs\". Dahlby estimated that the cuts would \"generate a $12.7 billion increase in nominal GDP\", a \"6.5% increase in per capita real GDP\", and a \"$1.2 billion in additional government revenues by 2023-24.\"<ref name=\"UCP_Platform_201904\"/>{{rp|20}} The Stokes analysis predicted the \"cut will result in $1 billion less net revenue for the province by 2022-23.\"<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_French_20190601\"/><ref name=\"UCP_Platform_201904\"/> On March 4, 2019, the UCP had announced their intention to cut corporate taxes by one third with a prediction of adding $13 billion to Alberta's economy.<ref name=\"UCP_TaxCuts_20190304\">{{Cite web| work = United Conservative Party |title=UCP Unveils Job Creation Tax Cut |quote=\"One Third Cut to Business Taxes Would Create at Least 55,000 Jobs, Grow Alberta Economy by $13 billion\"|access-date=October 24, 2019 |date=March 4, 2019| url = https://unitedconservative.ca/Article?name=UCPNews_Mar42019&}}</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 2021 the UCP's corporation tax will drop to nine per cent on New Year\u2019s Day 2021 and eight per cent in 2022, which would represent the \"lowest rate in Canada by a 30 per cent margin\".<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Hudes_20200228\"/>\n\nThe UCP's Job Creation Tax Cut was intended to lead to the \"creation of at least 55,000 new jobs, according to economist Jack Mintz.<ref name=\"UCP_TaxCuts_20190304\"/> Since 2009, the unemployment rate in Alberta hit its lowest point\u20144.3 per cent\u2014in September 2013 and its highest\u20149.1 per cent\u2014in November 2016.<ref name=\"economicdashboard\">{{Cite web| title = Unemployment Rate| access-date = December 17, 2019| url = https://economicdashboard.alberta.ca/Unemployment}}</ref> Alberta had experienced boom years in the energy sector starting in 2010,<ref name=\"CBC_Tombe_20190731\">{{Cite news| date = July 31, 2019| first = Trevor |last=Tombe |work=CBC News| title = Why earnings in Alberta have been stagnant for years | access-date = September 9, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/alberta-wages-recession-tombe-1.5229086}}</ref> but this boom was followed by a \"long and deep\" recession that lasted from 2014 to 2017\u2014driven by both low commodity pricing globally and controversial political policies from both the Provincial and Federal Government.<ref name=\"CBC_Tombe_20190731\">{{Cite news| date = July 31, 2019| first = Trevor |last=Tombe |work=CBC News| title = Why earnings in Alberta have been stagnant for years | access-date = September 9, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/alberta-wages-recession-tombe-1.5229086}}</ref> When the UCP government were elected in the spring of 2019, Alberta's economy was still in recovery.<ref name=\"CBC_Tombe_20190731\"/> Overall, by July 2019, about 35,000 jobs had been lost in mining, oil and gas alone.<ref name=\"CBC_Tombe_20190731\"/> Since 2014, sectors that offered high-wage employment of $30 and above, saw about 100,000 jobs disappear\u2014\"construction (down more than 45,000 jobs), mining, oil and gas (down nearly 35,000), and professional services (down 18,000),\" according to the economist, Trevor Tombe.<ref name=\"CBC_Tombe_20190731\"/>In 2013, oil tax revenues brought in 9.58 billion, or 21% of the total Provincial budget,<ref name=\"AlbertaBudget2013\">{{cite web | url=https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/7714457c-7527-443a-a7db-dd8c1c8ead86/resource/5604f999-fa33-4f77-bff4-1b8a189979e1/download/goa-2013-14-annual-report-complete.pdf |title=Alberta 2013-2014 Budget }}</ref> whereas in 2018 it had fallen to just 5.43 billion, or 11% of the Provincial budget.<ref name=\"AlbertaBudget2018\">{{cite web | url=https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/3d732c88-68b0-4328-9e52-5d3273527204/resource/2b82a075-f8c2-4586-a2d8-3ce8528a24e1/download/Budget-2019-Fiscal-Plan-2019-23.pdf#revenue |title=Alberta 2018-2019 Budget}}</ref> In 2013, the energy industry had provided 7.7% of all jobs in Alberta.<ref name=\"economic_results_AB2015\">{{cite web | url=http://www.albertacanada.com/business/overview/economic-results.aspx | title=Economic results | publisher=Government of Alberta | date=October 25, 2015 | accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref>  In 2017, 140,300 jobs representing 6.1% of total employment of 2,286,900 in Alberta in 2017 was due to the energy industry.<ref name=\"GovAB_2018\">{{Cite journal| pages = 10 |url=https://work.alberta.ca/documents/industry-profile-mining-oil-and-gas-extraction.pdf |date=2017 |journal=Alberta Government |title=Industry Profiles 2018 Mining and Oil and Gas Extraction Industry}}</ref> The unemployment rate in Alberta peaked in November 2016 at 9.1%.<ref name=\"economicdashboard\"/> The unemployment rate in the spring of 2019 in Alberta was 6.7% with 21,000 jobs added in April.<ref name=\"StatsCan\">{{Cite web| last = Government Of Canada| first = Statistics Canada| title = Regional unemployment rates used by the Employment Insurance program, three-month moving average, seasonally adjusted| access-date = September 5, 2019| date = May 10, 2019| url = https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/daily-quotidien/190510/t012a-eng.htm}}</ref> By July 2019, the seasonally adjusted unemployment rate had increased to 7.0% and remained at about that level since then.<ref name=\"economicdashboard\"/> By August 2019, the employment number in Alberta was 2,344,000, following the loss of 14,000 full-time jobs in July, which represented  the \"largest decline\" in Canada according to Statistics Canada.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Wyton_20190909\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta economy sheds 14,000 full-time jobs in July |newspaper= Edmonton Journal| access-date = September 6, 2019 |first=Moira |last=Wyton |date=August 9, 2019 | url = https://edmontonjournal.com/news/local-news/alberta-economy-sheds-14000-full-time-jobs-in-july}}</ref> According to Statistics Canada, in November, Alberta lost 18,000 jobs and the unemployment rate was 7.2%,<ref name=\"thinkhq_20191216\"/> \"with declines occurring in a number of industries, led by wholesale and retail trade. On a year-over-year basis, total employment in the province was little changed.\"<ref name=\"GC_SC_20191206\">{{Cite report | work = [[Statistics Canada]], Government of Canada| series = The Daily |title=Labour Force Survey, November 2019| | date = December 6, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019| url = https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/daily-quotidien/191206/dq191206a-eng.htm}}</ref> As UCP popularity declined considerably by December 2019, the polling agency, ThinkHQ Public Affairs Inc., said that \"governments tend to get more blame for the economy when times are tough than they do credit when times are good.\"<ref name=\"thinkhq_20191216\"/>\n\n===Blue Ribbon Panel on Alberta's Finances===\n\nIn August 2019, [[Janice MacKinnon]]'s task force submitted the report commissioned by Premier Kenney, \"Report and Recommendations: Blue Ribbon Panel on Alberta's Finances\".<ref name=\"MacKinnon_201908\">{{Cite report| last = MacKinnon| first = Janice| title = Report and Recommendations: Blue Ribbon Panel on Alberta's Finances |url=https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/081ba74d-95c8-43ab-9097-cef17a9fb59c/resource/257f040a-2645-49e7-b40b-462e4b5c059c/download/blue-ribbon-panel-report.pdf |access-date=November 1, 2019|date=August 2019 |pages=82}}</ref> According to ''[[Maclean's]]'', Premier Kenney had \"mandated\" that the panel \"figure out how to balance the provincial books without raising taxes.\"<ref name=\"macleans_Markusoff_20190903\">{{Cite news| last = Markusoff| first = Jason| title = Jason Kenney's convenient blueprint to fix half of Alberta's fiscal house| work = [[Maclean's]]| date = September 3, 2019 |access-date=November 1, 2019|url=https://www.macleans.ca/economy/jason-kenneys-convenient-blueprint-to-fix-half-of-albertas-fiscal-house/}}</ref> McKinnon, who was Saskatchewan's finance minister, found that \"Alberta spends more per person on its public sector, and compensates its teachers, doctors and other workers more generously, than other major provinces.\"<ref name=\"macleans_Markusoff_20190903\"/> The panel recommended that the post-secondary tuition freeze be lifted, and suggested \"various measures to slash health-care costs and government-wide program reviews.\"<ref name=\"macleans_Markusoff_20190903\"/>\n\n===2019 Budget===\n{{main|Alberta provincial budget, 2019}}\n \nOn October 24, 2019 Minister Toews announced the UCP's first [[Alberta provincial budget, 2019|provincial budget]]. ''[[The National Post]]'' said that it fulfilled their \"promise of slight austerity\" with \"cuts to spending programs and the elimination of hundreds of bureaucracy jobs\".<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> ''The Post'' said that these and the corporate tax cuts \"were the key planks of a four-year plan to bring the budget into balance.\"<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\">{{Cite news| last = Dawson| first = Tyler| title = Jason Kenney\u2019s conservatives deliver the tougher budget they warned Albertans was necessary| work = National Post|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/jason-kenneys-conservatives-deliver-the-tougher-budget-they-warned-albertans-was-necessary|access-date=October 27, 2019 | date=October 24, 2019}}</ref> The goal is to reduce government spending by $4-billion over four years.<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> The 2019-20 budget will \"run a deficit of $8.7 billion\" which is approximately \"$2-billion higher than in 2018-19.\"<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> ''The Post'' said that the changes in post-secondary education were \"significant\" with a 12-per-cent funding cut.<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> and a reduction in \"government grants to post-secondary institutions\".<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> Together that represents a $1.9 billion in cuts in post-secondary education.<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> Post-secondary institutions will be allowed to increase tuition.<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> The Alberta government has set a goal of balancing the budget by 2022-2023.<ref name=\"ABGOV_20190613\"/><ref name=\"CTVNews_20190613\"/>\n\nThe budget decision to de-index disability benefits met with outrage, according to ''The Star''. Many people were \"vocal about their disdain surrounding the UCP\u2019s decision to reverse the [[Assured Income for the Severely Handicapped|Assured Income for the Severely Handicapped]] (AISH)\u2019s tie to inflation\", including [[Arlene Dickinson]], formerly with the [[Dragon Den\u2019s]].<ref name=\"thestar_Yousif_20191025\">{{cite news |title=UCP\u2019s new budget met with outrage over the untying of disability benefits to inflation |date=October 25, 2019 |access-date=November 1, 2019|first1=Nadine |last1=Yousif |url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2019/10/25/ucps-new-budget-met-with-outrage-over-the-untying-of-disability-benefits-to-inflation.html |newspaper=The Star Edmonton}}</ref>\n\nOn October 28, the Minister Toews introduced Bill 20, an omnibus bill which included a clause through which the government of Alberta could withdraw the $1.53-billion grant it had promised for Calgary's [[Green Line (Calgary)|Green Line]] \"with just 90 days' notice and without cause.\"<ref name=\"CBC_20191102\">{{Cite news| title = Largest project in Calgary's history under threat from provincial changes, says Nenshi| work = CBC News| access-date = November 2, 2019| date = November 2, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/green-line-threat-termination-clause-1.5344181}}</ref> \n\nMinister Toews introduced a second omnibus bill, Bill 21, on October 28, as part of his budget that allows the provincial government to \"cancel its master agreement with doctors if the two sides can't negotiate a new deal.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bennett_20191031\">{{Cite news| last = Bennett| first = Dean| title = Alberta doctors call proposed new pay plan cynical and heavy-handed |work= CBC News| access-date = November 2, 2019| date = October 31, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-doctors-criticize-proposed-new-pay-plan-1.5342010}}</ref> In an October 30 open letter to all members of the [[Alberta Medical Association]], Dr. Christine Molnar, AMA director, said that the \"bill effectively gives government the power of pre-approval to cancel any physician services agreement without recourse. This is a violation of the sanctity of contracts.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bennett_20191031\"/> The bill would also give the government control over where new doctors can work starting in March 2022, in order to provide better service to rural areas.<ref name=\"CBC_Bennett_20191031\"/> \n\nAccording to an October 31, 2019 ''CBC News'' article, the UCP is \"working off\" August 2019, [[Janice MacKinnon]]'s August 2019 \"Report and Recommendations: Blue Ribbon Panel on Alberta's Finances\".<ref name=\"CBC_Bennett_20191031\"/>\n\nOn December 3, 2019, [[Moody's Investors Service|Moody's]] downgraded Alberta's credit rating from Aa2 stable from Aa1 negative.<ref name=\"CBC_Rieger_20191204\">{{Cite news| last = Rieger| first = Sarah| title = Moody's downgrades Alberta's credit rating, citing continued dependence on oil |work= CBC News| access-date = December 5, 2019| date = December 4, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/moody-s-alberta-credit-rating-1.5383294}}</ref> According to [[Mount Royal University]]'s political science professor, Duane Bratt, factors influencing the downgrade include the UCP's budget plan that led to an increase in the deficit and concerns about labour unrest with thousands of public sector jobs set to be eliminated.<ref name=\"CBC_Rieger_20191204\"/> Moody's report said that Alberta's economy's \"structural weakness\" lies in its concentration and dependency on [[non-renewable resource]]s (NNRs) combined with a \"lack of sufficient pipeline capacity to transport oil efficiently,\" \"no near-term expectation of a significant rebound in oil-related investments,\"<ref name=\"CBC_Rieger_20191204\"/> and \"revenue pressures related to UCP cuts to corporate tax rates.\"<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Wyton_20191204\">{{Cite web| last = Wyton| first = Moira| title = Finance minister \u2018disappointed\u2019 by decline in Alberta\u2019s credit rating| work = Edmonton Journal| access-date = December 5, 2019| date = December 4, 2019| url = https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/finance-minister-disappointed-by-decline-in-albertas-credit-rating}}</ref> Minister Toews blamed the downgrade on the NDP's tenure, during which the province had also experienced a credit rating downgrade, from its very high credit rating of AAA to Aa1.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Wyton_20191204\"/> Premier Kenney said in an interview that \" financial institutions \u2014 and this apparently includes Moody\u2019s \u2014 are buying into the political agenda emanating from Europe, which is trying to stigmatize development of hydrocarbon energy.\"<ref name=\"globalnews_Toy_20191204\">{{Cite web| last = Toy| first = Adam| title = Financial institutions like Moody\u2019s 'buying into' European political agenda: Kenney| work = Global News| access-date = December 5, 2019| date = December 4, 2019| url = https://globalnews.ca/news/6255402/kenney-danielle-smith-interview-moodys/}}</ref>\n\n==2020 Budget==\nMinister Toews tabled the UCP's second provincial budget on February 27, 2020. Toews said that the $CDN56.8 billion budget is based on an \"anticipated 38 per cent increase in energy royalties.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Hudes_20200228\">{{Cite news| last = Hudes| first = Sammy| title = Alberta budget banks on critical revenue boosts despite market 'volatility,' rising debt| work = Calgary Herald| date = February 28, 2020 |access-date=March 2, 2020 |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/politics/alberta-budget-banks-on-critical-revenue-boosts-despite-market-volatility-rising-debt}}</ref> The increased energy royalties depends heavily on the success of the UCP's corporate tax rate cuts to spur revenue growth through an infusion of capital from private investment and the resulting expansion in both \"oil production and pipeline capacity.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Hudes_20200228\"/> The only other revenue streams in this budget are \"a vaping tax and the extension of a tourism levy on short-term rentals.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Hudes_20200228\"/> David Taras, a [[political scientist]] from [[Mount Royal University]] said that this budget signaled that the UCP was \"not blinking\"\u2014They are \"sticking with [their game plan] the \"policy of cuts and deficit reduction in the face of what appears to be a province that's bleeding jobs.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Hudes_20200228\"/> \n\nThe budget included a proposed 10-year strategy intended to increase tourism spending to $20 billion by 2030, which a Ministry of Economic Development, Trade and Tourism spokesperson said was \"ambitious but reasonable\". \"Only $45 million of the overall ministry budget is [currently] dedicated to tourism\" and millions were cut from the tourism budget in this and previous budgets.<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Smith_20200228\">{{Cite news| last = Smith| first = Alanna | title = Critics say tourism goals set by the province are 'audacious'| work = Calgary herald| date = February 28, 2020 |access-date=March 2, 2020 |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/critics-say-tourism-goals-set-by-the-province-are-audacious}}</ref> The Tourism Industry Association of Alberta chair said that this \"audacious\" plan does not \"reflect\" the \"conversations\" held during the \"pre-budget planning sessions\" the government had with \"hundreds of industry professionals\" in Calgary and Edmonton to \"discuss recommendations with the government on how to boost the tourism industry.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Smith_20200228\"/> Province-wide, the budget cut $53 million from 2020 through 2023, from affordable housing maintenance.<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Nenshi_20200228\">{{Cite news |access-date=March 2, 2020 | work = Calgary Herald| date = February 28, 2020|url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/politics/budget-2020-plans-bow-river-flood-mitigation-no-changes-to-municipal-funding-cuts| last = | first = | title = Nenshi criticizes cut to affordable housing maintenance}}</ref>\n\nThe budget increases homeowners' education property taxes by 3.1 per cent in 2020-2021, which the government predicts will add revenue of \"$102 million to a total of $2.6 billion.\"<ref name=\"globalnews_Gilligan_20200228\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta Budget 2020: breaking down the biggest impacts to Calgary| work = Global News|first=Melissa |last=Gilligan |access-date=March 2, 2020 |date=February 28, 2020 | url = https://globalnews.ca/news/6608148/alberta-budget-2020-calgary-impacts/}}</ref>\n\nOperational funding of $8.2 billion for kindergarten to Grade 12 education will remain at 2019 levels, in spite of population growth and inflation.<ref name=\"globalnews_Gilligan_20200228\"/> \n\nThe  $20.6 billion budgeted for health received the same criticism from the Opposition party.<ref name=\"globalnews_Gilligan_20200228\"/> \n\nIn their February 28, 2020 report, Moody's Investors Service said that the 2020 budget was credit neutral.<ref name=\"moodys_20200228\">{{Cite web| title = Research: Moody's - Alberta\u2019s 2020 budget is credit neutral for the province |work=Moody's|access-date=March 2, 2020 |date=February 28, 2020 || url = https://www.moodys.com/research/Moodys-Albertas-2020-budget-is-credit-neutral-for-the-province--PBC_1216903 |location=Toronto}}</ref> According to Moody's, the UCP fiscal plan is subject to \"significant uncertainties, driven by weak resource sector investments and pipeline projects which are subject to regulatory, political, and other types of delays, much of which is beyond the control of the government.\"\n\nBy April 7, 2020, a combination of interconnected unprecedented global events\u2014including the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2002 coronavirus pandemic]], the [[coronavirus recession]], the [[2020 stock market crash]], and the [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]] and the resulting \"collapse in oil prices\", represent, what Premier Kenney described as \"the greatest challenge\" in Alberta's \"modern history, threatening its main industry and wreaking havoc on its finances.\"<ref name=\"NaPo_Bloomberg_Orland_20200407\">{{cite news |url=https://nationalpost.com/commodities/energy/alberta-premier-kenney-sees-negative-oil-prices-14-billion-deficit |title=Alberta Premier Kenney sees negative oil prices, $20-billion deficit in 'the greatest challenge of our generation' |work=National Post via Bloomberg News |first=Kevin |last=Orland |date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Ministry of Energy ==\n\n[[Sonya Savage]], whose background in energy and the environment includes major projects, such as the [[Enbridge Northern Gateway Pipelines]] and with her work as an executive of [[Canadian Energy Pipeline Association]] (CEPA), was appointed [[Alberta Energy|Minister of Energy]] on April 30, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alberta.ca/energy.aspx |title=Ministry of Energy |work=Government of Alberta |access-date=October 24, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\">{{Cite news| last = Varcoe| first = Chris| title = New Alberta energy minister steps into cabinet's hot seat | work = Calgary Herald| date = May 1, 2019 |access-date=October 24, 2019 |url=https://calgaryherald.com/opinion/columnists/varcoe-albertas-new-energy-minister-has-hands-full-on-day-1}}</ref> She is tasked with overhauling the [[Alberta Energy Regulator]] (AER)\u2014one of the UCP's campaign promises with the aim of implementing \"shorter timelines for project approvals.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/>  On April 30, the UCP proclaimed Bill 12  which gives \"Alberta the power to restrict oil and gas exports to British Columbia.<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/> According to the ''Calgary Herald'', this \"could provoke a quick court challenge\" the Premier of British Columbia, [[John Horgan]].<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/> On April 30, Premier Kenney \"pragmatically backed away\" from the campaign promise to \"remove the 100-megatonne cap on oilsands emissions.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/> According to the ''Calgary Herald'', Bill C-48 regarding an \"oil tanker ban off the northern coast of British Columbia\" threatened the proposed [[Enbridge Northern Gateway Pipelines]] project that Savage had worked on.<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/> She was also involved in \"CEPA's examination of Bill C-69, Ottawa\u2019s overhaul of how major energy projects \u2014 including oil and gas pipelines \u2014 are reviewed by the federal government.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_varcoe_20191024\"/>\n\nIn February 2019, the previous government signed a [[crude-by-rail]] program agreement with two railway companies\u2014and the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] (CPR) [[Canadian National Railway]] (CNR) with a goal of reducing the [[Western Canadian Select]] price discount that has been exacerbated by the \"lack of pipeline capacity\". Through the four-year, $3.7-billion agreement the \"province would have purchased and shipped 120,000 barrels of crude a day.\"<ref name=\"G&M_Graney_20191027\">{{Cite news| last =Graney| first =  Emma | title = Alberta nears deal to unload crude-by-rail contracts to private sector| work = The Globe and Mail via the Canadian Press|access-date=October 28, 2019 | date=October 27, 2019| url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/article-alberta-in-talks-to-offload-crude-by-rail-contract-to-private-sector/}}</ref> The NDP had estimated that the program would have generated \"revenue of $6-billion\", according to ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''. The Kenney government cancelled the agreement shortly after taking office because the \"financial risks were too high\".<ref name=\"G&M_Graney_20191027\"/> By the end of October 2019 Minister Savage was in ongoing negotiations with the railways related to the \"number and complexity of the contracts.\"<ref name=\"G&M_Graney_20191027\"/> In November, 2019 Premier Kenney visited Texas in a four day trip to create more investment in Alberta's oil and gas industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-what-jason-kenney-and-albertans-can-learn-from-texas/|title=What Jason Kenney and Albertans can learn from Texas|last=Fawcett|first=Max|date=December 1, 2019|website=The Globe and Mail|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''article said, \"A single talisman has defined Jason Kenney\u2019s time as premier of Alberta: oil. A single talisman has defined Jason Kenney's time as premier of Alberta: oil.\"<ref name=\"theglobeandmail_Korol_20200331\">{{Cite news| title = Globe editorial: Why Jason Kenney\u2019s $7.5-billion oil pipeline investment is a risky bet |work= Reuters and The Globe and Mail|first=Todd |last=Korol| access-date =April 7, 2020| url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/editorials/article-why-jason-kenneys-75-billion-oil-pipeline-investment-is-a-risky-bet/ |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>  Kenney campaigned on supporting the oil and gas industries and expanding the pipeline system. By 2018, \"chronic pipeline bottlenecks\" and as a result \"industry and governments millions of dollars a day in lost revenue.\" Following the December 2 announcement of mandatory oil production cut backs in Alberta, the price of WCS rose to c.US$26.65 a barrel.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Canadian Crude Price Spike Won't Last| work = OilPrice.com| accessdate = 2018-12-30| url = https://oilprice.com/Energy/Oil-Prices/Canadian-Crude-Price-Spike-Wont-Last.html}}</ref> The differential between [[Western Canadian Select]]\u2014the benchmark price for Alberta heavy crude\u2014and [[West Texas Intermediate]] (WTI)\u2014which had averaged at US$17 for the decade from 2008 to 2018\u2014widened to a record of around US$50,<ref name=\"theglobeandmail_20181127\">{{Cite news| title = Why Alberta's latest oil-price plunge is unprecedented| access-date = 28 December 2018| url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/industry-news/energy-and-resources/article-why-albertas-latest-oil-price-plunge-is-unprecedented/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |first=Matt |last=Lundy |date=27 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NEB_2020\"/> and the price of WCS plummeted to US$5.90.<ref name=\"economicdashboard_AB_20191223\">{{Cite web| title = Economic Dashboard - Oil Prices| access-date = December 23, 2019| url = https://economicdashboard.alberta.ca/OilPrice}}</ref>  In response, the NDP government under then-Premier [[Rachel Notley]], had set temporary mandatory production limits which resulted in the price of WCS rose to c.US$26.65 a barrel.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Canadian Crude Price Spike Won't Last| work = OilPrice.com| accessdate = 2018-12-30| url = https://oilprice.com/Energy/Oil-Prices/Canadian-Crude-Price-Spike-Wont-Last.html}}</ref> \n\nOn March 24, 2020, as the price of oil plunged more than 5 percent, federal Finance Minister [[Bill Morneau]] announced a program to help the oil industry which would include a \"backstop for banks that lend to the energy sector.\"<ref name=\"G&M_Jones_20200327\">{{Cite news|first=Jeffrey |last=Jones| title = With oil at a record low, government must think about curtailment |work=The Globe and Mail| access-date = April 7, 2020 |date=March 27, 2020| url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/article-with-oil-at-a-record-low-government-must-think-about-curtailment/}}</ref>\n\nBy March 31, 2020, the \"federal government had already bought Trans Mountain\" and was \"committed to getting it built\" and Enbridge's Line 3 was making progress.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail_Korol_20200331\"/> In what Kenney described as a \"bold move to retake control of our province's economic destiny\", the province agreed to help finance the construction of [[TC Energy]]'s [[Keystone Pipeline|Keystone XL oil sands pipeline]] in southern Aberta, Montana, South Dakota and Nebraska with \"agreements for the transport of 575,000 barrels of oil daily\".<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\">{{Cite news| title = Disputed Canada-US Oil Pipeline Work to Start in April |location=[[Billings, Montana]] |work=[[Associated Press|AP]] via [[The New York Times]] |date=March 31, 2020| access-date = April 7, 2020| url = https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/31/world/bc-cn-canada-keystone-xl-pipeline.html}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that \"[d]espite plunging oil prices\" in March\", Kenney said the \"province's resource-dependent economy could not afford for Keystone XL to be delayed until after the coronavirus pandemic and a global economic downturn have passed.\"<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/> Alberta \"has agreed to invest approximately $1.1 billion US as equity in the project, which substantially covers planned construction costs through the end of 2020. The remaining $6.9 billion US is expected to be funded through a combination of a $4.2-billion project-level credit facility to be fully guaranteed by the Alberta government and a $2.7-billion investment by TC Energy.\"<ref name=\"CBC_CP_20200331\">{{Cite news| date = March 31, 2020| work = The Canadian Press via CBC| title = TC Energy to start work on Keystone XL pipeline after $1.1B US Alberta investment| access-date = April 7, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/tc-energy-keystone-xl-pipeline-1.5515850}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/> Kenney has said that the Keystone XL will create \"1,400 direct and 5,400 indirect jobs in Alberta during construction and will reap an estimated $30 billion in tax and royalty revenues for both Alberta and Canada over the next twenty years.<ref name=\"CBC_CP_20200331\"/> \n\nTC Energy \"expects to buy back the Alberta government's investment and refinance the $4.2 billion loan\" when the 1,200-mile (1,930-kilometer) pipeline is operational starting in 2023.<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/> Keystone XL will add up to 830,000 bpd from Western Canada to [[Steele City, Nebraska]]. From there it connects to \"other pipelines that feed oil refineries on the U.S. Gulf Coast.\"<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/> According to the [[Canadian Energy Regulator]], in 2018, Alberta produced 3.91 million bpd of crude oil, which represents 82 per cent of the total production in Canada.<ref name=\"NEB_2020\">{{Cite report| last = Government of Canada| work = [[Canadian Energy Regulator]] formerly National Energy Board| series = Provincial and Territorial Energy Profiles |title=Alberta| access-date = April 7, 2020| url = https://www.cer-rec.gc.ca/nrg/ntgrtd/mrkt/nrgsstmprfls/ab-eng.html}}</ref> \n\nAccording to a March 31, 2020 article in ''[[The New York Times]]'', because of Kenney, [[Russ Girling]], TC Energy CEO, announced that construction of its $8-billion US Keystone XL oil sands pipeline's Canada-United States border crossing, in rural northeast [[Montana]], will begin in April in spite of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/> Concerns were raised by the office of the Montana's Governor, [[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Steve Bullock]] about the added strain on \"rural health resources during the coronavirus pandemic\", with the arrival of a hundred or more pipeline construction workers in rural Montana. At the time of the announcement northeastern Montana had only one confirmed COVID-19 case.<ref name=\"NYT_AP_20200331\"/>\n\n==Ministry of Education==\n\nIn November 2019, the Calgary Board of Education (CBE) announced it would be cutting the positions of hundreds of teachers following the UCP 2019 cuts to the education funding in the UCP's fall budget,<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> In response, Alberta\u2019s Education Minister Adriana LaGrange said she would launch an \"independent financial audit\" as well as a \"governance review\" of the CBE. LaGrange said that the CBE had used taxpayer dollars recklessly. She said that the \"audit and governance review will give government a path forward on helping the CBE prioritize the classroom and find efficiencies elsewhere in its operations.\"<ref name=\"globalnews_Gilligan_201911120\">{{Cite news| title = Calgary Board of Education to cut 300 temporary teachers amid $32M shortfall |location=Calgary|first= Melissa |last=Gilligan |date=November 20, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019| url = https://globalnews.ca/news/6193545/cbe-cuts-300-temporary-teachers/}}</ref> In early December LaGrange \"provided a \"one-time exception\" on the annual $15 million \"maintenance renewal funding\" to the Alberta Board of Education. This allows school boards to use the funds to reverse the layoffs of 317 temporary teachers.<ref name=\"globalnews_Croteau_20191209\">{{Cite news| title = Calgary Board of Education reverses teacher layoffs while Catholic board hikes school bus fees|first=Jill |last=Croteau | work = Global News| date = December 9, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019| url = https://globalnews.ca/news/6274118/calgary-board-education-school-teacher-layoffs-reverse-bus-fees/}}</ref>\n\n==Ministry of Environment and Parks ==\n{{main|Ministry of Environment and Parks}}\n\nOn March 3, 2020, the [[Ministry of Environment and Parks|Minister of Environment and Parks]], [[Jason Nixon]] said  that the province could not \"continue to spend $86 million of Albertans' tax dollars\" on the \"province's parks, recreation areas and other protected areas\"\u2014areas that bring in only $36 million.<ref name=\"CP_20200304\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta government plans to close 20 parks, hand over 164 others to third parties| work = The Canadian Press via Kimberley Daily Bulletin| access-date = March 18, 2020| date = March 4, 2020| url = https://www.kimberleybulletin.com/news/alberta-government-plans-to-close-20-parks-hand-over-164-others-to-third-parties/}}</ref> An Alberta Parks March 5 statement entitled, \"Optimizing Alberta Parks\", listed changes that would come into effect in 2020 as part of a cost-saving initiative.<ref name=\"albertaparks_20200315\">{{cite press release |title=Optimizing Alberta Parks |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318205752/https://albertaparks.ca/news-events/ |archivedate=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |date=March 5, 2020 |url=https://albertaparks.ca/news-events/}}</ref> <ref name=\"calgaryherald_Corbella_20200305\"/> The UCP government would \"fully or partially close\" \"20 provincial parks\" and was \"planning to hand over 164 others to third-party managers\".<ref name=\"albertaparks_20200315\"/><ref name=\"CP_20200304\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta government plans to close 20 parks, hand over 164 others to third parties| work = The Canadian Press via Kimberley Daily Bulletin| access-date = March 18, 2020| date = March 4, 2020| url = https://www.kimberleybulletin.com/news/alberta-government-plans-to-close-20-parks-hand-over-164-others-to-third-parties/}}</ref> The ''Canadian Press'' said that this represents \"more than one-third of all the province's parks, recreation areas and other protected areas.\"<ref name=\"CP_20200304\"/> The statement included the possibly of selling Crown land.<ref name=\"globalnews_Weber_20200317\">{{Cite news| title = Alberta to sell native grassland despite government promises no Crown land would be sold| work = Global News via the Canadian Press|first=Bob |last=Weber|date=March 17, 2020| access-date = March 18, 2020| url = https://globalnews.ca/news/6689873/alberta-crown-land-for-sale/}}</ref> \n\nIn response to concerns, Nixon said in a March 5 ''Calgary Herald'' interview, \"We are not selling any Crown or public land \u2014 period.\"<ref name=\"calgaryherald_Corbella_20200305\">{{Cite news| title = Alberta Parks are not for sale \u2014 not one square centimetre |newspaper= Calgary Herald| access-date = March 18, 2020| url = https://calgaryherald.com/opinion/columnists/corbella-alberta-parks-are-not-for-sale-not-one-centimeter/ |author=Licia Corbella |date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> According to a March 17 ''Global News'' article, the province listed a 65-hectare plot of land east of [[Taber, Alberta|Taber]] in a March 31 auction with a starting bid of $440,000.<ref name=\"globalnews_Weber_20200317\"/>\n\n==Ministry for Economic Development, Trade and Tourism==\n\nBy April 7, 2020, the Minister of Economic Development, Trade and Tourism [[Tanya Fir]], said that the technology sector would be \"a key part of diversifying Alberta's economy.\" Fir is reviewing recommendations in a report by a Innovation Capital Working Group, a working group of \"tech sector, academic and business leaders\" created by the province in December 2019, to \"develop ways\" to support and grow Alberta's tech sector.<ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20200407\">{{Cite news| date = April 7, 2020| first = Kyle |last=Bakx| title = Why Alberta's devotion to oil is making tech companies want to leave the province |work= CBC News| access-date = April 7, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/tech-alberta-kxl-keystone-1.5523929}}</ref><ref name=\"calgaryherald_Stephenson_20200403\">{{Cite web| title = COVID crisis endangers future of Alberta's tech sector, advocates warn| work = Calgary Herald| access-date = April 7, 2020|first=Amanda |last=Stephenson | url = https://calgaryherald.com/business/local-business/covid-crisis-endangers-future-of-albertas-tech-sector-advocates-warn}}</ref> The UCP eliminated The Interactive Digital Media Tax Credit,  the Capital Investment Tax Credit, and the Alberta Investor Tax Credit, which had provided a \"30 per cent tax credit to investors who put money into specific industries such as clean technology and digital animation.\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20200407\"/> Trent Johnsen, a veteran member of Alberta's tech sector, who has been involved with Innovate Calgary among others, said that Alberta was \"betting exclusively on oil and gas. What is Alberta doing to become a successful player in the 21st century of the new economy?\"<ref name=\"CBC_Bakx_20200407\"/> \n\n==Public response to Kenney's premiership==\n\nA March 3  CBC article listed the reasons for Kenney's drop in the polls to 47 per cent in March from 60 per cent in September 2019.<ref name=\"CBC_20200303\">{{Cite web| title = Kenney's popularity drops below 50% in latest Angus Reid poll |work= CBC News|date=March 3, 2020| access-date = March 18, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/angus-reid-kenney-popularity-poll-1.5483820}}</ref> This included the blockades as well as the UCP's \"aggressive approach to bolster the province's oil and gas sector and balance the budget through cuts\". Other controversial actions taken by the UCP include, \"cutting funding for post-secondary institutions while lifting the tuition cap\"; \"reducing funding to municipalities; \"imposing unilateral changes to the way doctors bill the province; making clear it wants freezes or cuts to government employees' pay when collective agreements come up for negotiation this spring; spending $30 million per year on a war room now called the Canadian Energy Centre; making its first bill of the new sitting one that targets those who disrupt critical infrastructure with severe penalties; and \"fully or partially closing 20 provincial parks and seeking \"partnerships\" for 164 more.\"<ref name=\"CBC_20200303\"/>\n\n==Response to coronavirus pandemic==\nIn response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alberta]], Premier Kenny declared a state of emergency on March 17, which gives the province or the provincial health authority the right to \"acquire or use property, require a qualified person to help out, authorize the conscription of people needed or authorize the entry into buildings or onto land without a warrant\" under the Public Health Act. Although the order may lapse after 30 days, it can be renewed.<ref name=\"thestar_Boyd_20200317\">{{Cite news| title = Ontario, Alberta and B.C. have declared states of emergency. Here's how that helps |first=Alex |last=Boyd| work = The Star |location=Toronto|date=March 17, 2020 |access-date=March 17, 2020| url = https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/17/alberta-joins-ontario-declares-public-emergency-due-to-coronavirus.html}}</ref> Ontario and British Columbia also declared a state of emergency as the number of cases increased.<ref name=\"thestar_Boyd_20200317\"/> By March 17, there were 23 new cases representing the \"largest day-over-day increase yet in the province\" resulting in total of 97 people in Alberta with the virus.<ref name=\"CTV_Romero_20200317\">{{Cite news| last = Romero| first = Diego| title = Alberta confirms 23 new cases of COVID-19, bringing total to 97| work = Edmonton| access-date = March 17, 2020| date =March 2020| url = https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/alberta-confirms-23-new-cases-of-covid-19-bringing-total-to-97-1.4856621}}</ref> Confirmed cases across the province include 20 in the Calgary zone, 20 in the Edmonton zone, 3 in the Central zone, 1 in the South zone, and 3 in the North zone.<ref name=\"AB_20200317\">{{Cite web| title = COVID-19 info for Albertans| access-date = March 17, 2020 |date=March 17, 2020| url = https://www.alberta.ca/coronavirus-info-for-albertans.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==Polling results==\n\nIn the February 24 to February 28 Angus Reid Institute poll, Kenney's approval rate among Albertans had dropped to 47 per cent from 54 per cent in December 2019<ref name=\"CBC_20200303\"/> and 60 per cent in September 2019.<ref name=\"NaPo_20191130\">{{Cite news| title = Can anything stop Jason Kenney? Alberta premier rides high approval rating as his party gathers for convention |work= National Post| access-date = December 5, 2019| date = November 30, 2019| url = https://nationalpost.com/news/can-anything-stop-jason-kenney |first=Tyler |last=Dawson |location=Edmonton}}</ref> In September he was one of the top-three most-popular premiers in Canada with only Permier Moe of Saskatchewan and Quebec's Fran\u00e7ois Legault winning higher approval ratings by a small margin.<ref name=\"NaPo_20191130\"/>\n\nAccording to a ThinkHQ Public Affairs Inc. poll released on December 16, 2019, Albertans who disapprove of the performance of the UCP government were in the majority at 53 percent,<ref name=\"CBC_20191216\">{{Cite news| date = December 16, 2019| work = CBC News| title = Public approval of UCP government slides 12 points, poll suggests|access-date=December 17, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/ucp-thinkhq-poll-kenney-approval-alberta-honeymoon-end-1.5397567}}</ref> which reflects a \"considerable slide in public approval\" since October.<ref name=\"thinkhq_20191216\">{{Cite web| title = UCP Honeymoon Comes to an End in Alberta: Driven by heightened concerns about jobs, the economy and belt-tightening |work=ThinkHQ Public Affairs Inc. |first=Marc |last=Henry| date = December 16, 2019|access-date=December 17, 2019 |location=Calgary| url = https://thinkhq.ca/ucp-honeymoon-comes-to-an-end-in-alberta-driven-by-heightened-concerns-about-jobs-the-economy-and-belt-tightening/}}</ref> Of the respondents who voted for the UCP in spring, 21 per cent disapproved of Kenney by December 16.<ref name=\"CBC_20191216\"/> In ThinkHQ's poll the opposition to the UCP was \"considerably more intense than support\"\u201438 per cent said they strongly disapproved with only 16 per cent strong approving. Reasons for the slide in popularity by December 2019, included growing concerns about both employment and the economy with \"many voters\" concerned with the \"unexpected consequences related to budget-tightening by the new Kenney government.\"<ref name=\"thinkhq_20191216\"/>\n\n==List of premiers==\n{{main|List of premiers of Alberta}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Alberta Energy Regulator]]\n*[[Alberta Geological Survey]]\n*[[Alberta Health Services]]\n*[[Alberta Human Rights Commission]]\n*[[Alberta Municipal Government Board]]\n*[[Alberta Oil Sands Technology and Research Authority]]\n*[[Alberta Parks]]\n*[[Economy of Alberta]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.premier.gov.ab.ca/ Premier of Alberta Official Site]\n\n{{Alberta Assemblies}}\n{{Topics on Alberta}}\n{{Politics of Canadian provinces}}\n{{Alberta politics}}\n\n[[Category:Premiers of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Premierships]]\n[[Category:Politics of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Alberta Legislature]]\n[[Category:Alberta provincial legislation]]\n[[Category:2019 in Alberta]]\n", "name_user": "Oceanflynn", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBargaining rights bill:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Premiership_of_Jason_Kenney"}
{"title_page": "Nogizaka46", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese girl group}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Nogizaka46\n| image               = Nogizaka46 at Japan Expo 2014 (1).jpg\n| caption             = Nogizaka46 at Japan Expo 2014\n| landscape           = yes\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Tokyo]], Japan\n| genre               = [[J-Pop]]\n| years_active        = 2011\u2013present\n| label               = [[Sony Music Entertainment Japan|Sony Records/N46Div]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Sakamichi Series]]\n| website             = {{URL|https://www.nogizaka46.com/}}\n| current_members     = \n| past_members        = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Nogizaka46'''|\u4e43\u6728\u574246|extra=Nogizaka Forty-six}} is a [[Japanese idol|Japanese female idol]] group produced by [[Yasushi Akimoto]], created as the {{nihongo|official rival|\u516c\u5f0f\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30eb|k\u014dshiki raibaru}} of the group [[AKB48]]. They are the first group from the [[Sakamichi Series]], which also includes sister groups [[Keyakizaka46]], [[Yoshimotozaka46]], and [[Hinatazaka46]].\n\nThe group's musical catalogue includes twenty-five singles and five compilation albums. Starting with their third single, each of Nogizaka46's single releases have reached the top position on the weekly Oricon chart, and each single since \"[[Influencer (song)|Influencer]]\" has sold at least one million copies. The group has also created radio shows, theater productions, television programs, and films, including ''[[NogiBingo!]]'', ''[[Hatsumori Bemars]]'', ''Nogizaka Under Construction'', ''[[Asahinagu (film)|Asahinagu]]'', and a series of documentary films about the group.\n\nNogizaka46 has twice won the Grand Prix at the annual [[Japan Record Awards]], with consecutive wins for \"Influencer\" in 2017 and \"[[Synchronicity (song)|Synchronicity]]\" in 2018. The group has sold nearly 18 million CDs in Japan.\n\n==History==\n\n===2011\u20132012: Formation and early chart success===\nThe formation of Nogizaka46 was first announced on June 29, 2011, when it became the first group to be labelled as the \"official rival\" to the group [[AKB48]], rather than a sister group like [[NMB48]] or [[SKE48]]. The group was named after the location of the [[Sony Music Japan]] offices near [[Nogizaka Station]]. Producer Yasushi Akimoto said that the number \"46\" was chosen as a direct challenge to AKB48, implying that Nogizaka46 would succeed with fewer members.<ref name=\"oricon20110629\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/confidence/89336/full/|title=\"AKB48\u516c\u5f0f\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30eb\"\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u7d50\u6210 \u4e00\u822c\u516c\u52df\u3067\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc\u6c7a\u5b9a|work=ORICON STYLE|publisher=Oricon ME|accessdate=22 August 2011| language=ja|date=29 June 2011}}</ref> In contrast to AKB48 and its sister groups, the image of Nogizaka46 is based on the Japanese people's perception of conservatively-dressed private all-girls high school students in France, which carries the connotations of elegance and refinement.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ueda|first=Yutaka|date=March 2016|title=Image Strategy of Nogizaka46: How Do Young People Perceive It?|url=http://repository.seikei.ac.jp/dspace/bitstream/10928/865/1/ippankenkyuhoukoku-49-5_1-18.pdf|journal=Bulletin of Seikei University|volume=49|pages=2|via=}}</ref>\n\nOverall, 38,934 people applied to join Nogizaka46. Final auditions for the group were held from 20\u201321 August 2011, with 56 finalists competing for 36 available places, and 16 members joining as \"senbatsu\" members specially selected for performances and media appearances.<ref name=\"oricon20110822\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2000936/full/|script-title=ja:AKB48\"\u516c\u5f0f\"\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30eb\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u300136\u4eba\u6c7a\u5b9a \u6bce\u65e5\u304c\u7dcf\u9078\u6319?!|trans-title=AKB48 Official rival Nogizaka46, 36 members were selected|accessdate=2016-03-05|date=2011-08-22|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref> On October 2, 2011, the group launched its first television variety show, titled {{nihongo|''Nogizakatte, Doko?''|\u4e43\u6728\u5742\u3063\u3066\u3001\u3069\u3053?| Lit: Where is Nogizaka?}} and hosted by the comedy duo [[Bananaman (comedy duo)|Bananaman]].<ref name=\"oricon20110822\" /><ref name=\"tower20110912\">{{cite web|url=http://tower.jp/article/news/2011/09/12/n13|title=\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u306eTV\u30ec\u30ae\u30e5\u30e9\u30fc\u756a\u7d44\u300c\u4e43\u6728\u5742\u3063\u3066\u3001\u3069\u3053?\u300d\u304c10\u6708\u306b\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30c8|publisher=TOWER RECORDS ONLINE|accessdate=13 September 2011|language=ja|date=12 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2012, Nogizaka46 released their debut single \"[[Guruguru Curtain]]\". It ranked second on the [[Oricon]] chart and sold 136,309 copies in the first week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/js/w/2012-03-05/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120408135015/http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/js/w/2012-03-05/|script-title=ja:2012\u5e7402\u670820\u65e5\uff5e2012\u5e7402\u670826\u65e5\u306eCD\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u9031\u9593\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0|date=2012-03-05|archivedate=2012-04-08|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=|language=ja}}</ref> Their second single, \"[[Oide Shampoo]]\", was released on May 2 of the same year, and became their first number one song on the Oricon weekly chart, with sales of 156,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2011204/full/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u3011\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001AKB\u6307\u539f\u3068\u306e\u540c\u9580\u5bfe\u6c7a\u5236\u3059 \u4eca\u5e74\u521d\u306e\u65b0\u4eba\u9996\u4f4d|date=2012-05-08|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref> The choreography for \"Oide Shampoo\" caused a brief controversy, as critics disapproved of the members lifting their skirts over their faces during one part of the performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/20120421/ido12042105030000-n1.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423192852/http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/20120421/ido12042105030000-n1.html|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u3081\u304f\u308a\"\u5c01\u5370\"\u3072\u3089\u3072\u3089\"\u89e3\u7981\"|archivedate=2012-04-23|date=21 April 2012|accessdate=7 November 2015|publisher=[[Sankei Sports|Sankei Digital Inc.]]|language=ja}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, Nogizaka46 took part in Yubi Matsuri, an idol festival produced by [[Rino Sashihara]], performing before 8,000 people at [[Nippon Budokan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/71786|script-title=ja:\u6307\u539f\u8389\u4e43\u300c\u3086\u3073\u796d\u308a\u300d\u3067\u8c6a\u83ef\u30b3\u30e9\u30dc\u7248\u300c\u30d8\u30d3\u30ed\u30c6\u300d\u5b9f\u73fe|publisher=[[Natalie (website)|Natalie]]|date=26 June 2012|accessdate=20 November 2012|language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mynavi.jp/news/2012/11/02/182/|title=\u6307\u539f\u8389\u4e43\u30d7\u30ed\u30c7\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9\u300c\u7b2c\u4e00\u56de\u3086\u3073\u796d\u308a\u300d\u3001DVD&Blu-ray\u3067\u306e\u767a\u58f2\u304c\u6c7a\u5b9a!|publisher=My Navi|date=2 November 2012|accessdate=20 November 2012|language=ja}}</ref> They debuted their first musical theater production, titled ''16 nin no Principal'', at Shibuya Parco Theater in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/75143|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u300c16\u4eba\u306e\u30d7\u30ea\u30f3\u30b7\u30d1\u30eb\u300d\u516c\u6f14\u3001\u672c\u65e5\u304b\u3089\u4e88\u7d04\u958b\u59cb|date=2012-08-22|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=Natasha,Inc|language=ja}}</ref> By the end of 2012, Nogizaka46 reached number one on the Oricon yearly chart in the newcomers sales category, with annual sales of 870 million yen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2019912/full/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u5e74\u9593\u3011\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u65b0\u4eba\u30bb\u30fc\u30eb\u30b91\u4f4d AKB\u95a2\u9023\u30b0\u30eb\u30fc\u30d7\u521d|date=2012-12-21|accessdate=2016-10-20|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132015: Second generation and national exposure===\nNogizaka46 held their first anniversary concert at [[Makuhari Messe]] in [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]] in February 2013, performing for 9,000 fans.<ref name=\"natalie20130223\">{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/85424|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc1\u5468\u5e74\u3067\u5168\u66f2\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\uff06\u65b0\u66f2\u3082\u521d\u62ab\u9732|date=2013-02-23|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=Natasha,Inc|language=ja}}</ref> From December 2012 to April 2013, an audition for the second generation of Nogizaka46 members was held, with 14 new members chosen out of 16,302 applicants.<ref name=\"modelpress20160904\">{{cite web|url=http://mdpr.jp/news/detail/1611889|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u65b0\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc12\u4eba\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff1c\u30d7\u30ed\u30d5\u30a3\u30fc\u30eb\uff0f\u30bd\u30ed\u5199\u771f\uff0f\u300canan\u300d\u300cnon-no\u300d\u306a\u3069\u516820\u8a8c\u7279\u5225\u8cde\uff1e|date=2016-09-04|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=modelpress|language=ja}}</ref> Thirteen of these new members were introduced at the musical theater performance of ''16 nin no Principal deux'', the sequel to the 2012 musical, in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/article/2013/04/nogizaka46-2nd-generation-members-to-be-introduced-during-16nin-no-principal-deux|title=Nogizaka46 2nd generation members to be introduced during '16nin no Principal deux'|date=2013-04-22|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=6Theory Media, LLC|work=tokyohive}}</ref>  The group also launched their first radio program, titled {{nihongo|''Nogizaka46no, No''|\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u306e\u300c\u306e\u300d| Lit: Nogizaka46's No}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nogizaka46.com/news/2013/03/46-60.php|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u304c\u6587\u5316\u653e\u9001\u300e\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u306e\u300c\u306e\u300d\u300f\u3067\u521d\u306e\u30e9\u30b8\u30aa\u51a0\u756a\u7d44\u6c7a\u5b9a!!|publisher=Nogizaka46 Official Website|accessdate=28 April 2013|language=ja|date=28 April 2013}}</ref> and released their first photobook, titled ''Nogizaka Ha''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/article/2013/10/nogizaka46-to-release-their-1st-photo-book|title=Nogizaka46 to release their 1st photo book|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=6Theory Media, LLC|work=tokyohive}}</ref> The photobook, released in October, ranked fourth on the Oricon weekly book ranking with 27,000 copies sold.<ref name=\"oricon20160811\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2076605/full/|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u30012nd\u5199\u771f\u96c6\u304c\u30b0\u30eb\u30fc\u30d7\u521d\u306e\u7dcf\u5408\u9996\u4f4d \u30b0\u30a2\u30e0\u3067\u6c34\u7740\u59ff\u3082\u62ab\u9732|date=2016-08-11|accessdate=2016-08-12|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref>\n[[File:Nogizaka46 (14488192740).jpg|thumb|alt=Members of Nogizaka46 performing on stage|Nogizaka46 performing at the Japan Expo in Paris in 2014]]\nIn February 2014, Nogizaka46 held their second birthday concert for 13,000 fans at [[Yokohama Arena]].<ref name=\"natalie20140223\">{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/110449|script-title=ja:\u30b5\u30d7\u30e9\u30a4\u30ba\u9023\u767a\uff01\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc2\u5468\u5e74\u795d\u30465\u6642\u9593\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6|date=2014-02-23|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=Natasha,Inc|language=ja}}</ref> During the show, the group announced that their musical ''16 nin no Principal trois'' would open at Akasaka ACT Theater on May 30 and run until June 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/110435|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u300c16\u4eba\u306e\u30d7\u30ea\u30f3\u30b7\u30d1\u30eb\u300d\u7b2c3\u5f3e\u30015\u6708\u672b\u304b\u3089\u958b\u50ac|date=2014-02-22|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=Natasha,Inc|language=ja}}</ref> The group also released the DVD and Blu-ray versions of their first birthday concert, which reached number one on the Oricon weekly DVD chart, selling 12,000 copies in the first week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2033934/full/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u3011\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u5973\u6027\u30b0\u30eb\u30fc\u30d7\u521d\u306e1stDVD\u7dcf\u5408\u9996\u4f4d 2\u5468\u5e74\u3078\u5f3e\u307f|date=2014-02-12|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref> On February 24, 2014, at an AKB48 group event, it was announced that [[Rina Ikoma]] would join AKB48's Team B, and that [[Rena Matsui]] from SKE48's Team E would hold a concurrent position with Nogizaka46.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/article/2014/02/the-results-of-akb/|title=The results of AKB48 group's big team shuffle!|date=24 February 2014|accessdate=24 February 2014|publisher=Tokyohive}}</ref> On July 5, 2014, the group performed overseas for the first time, as part of a slate of Japanese performers at the [[Japan Expo]] 2014 in [[Paris]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mdpr.jp/music/detail/1386328|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u521d\u6d77\u5916\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u3067\u30d1\u30ea\u71b1\u72c2 \u30d5\u30e9\u30f3\u30b9\u8a9e\u3067\u6328\u62f6\uff1c\u30bb\u30c3\u30c8\u30ea\u30b9\u30c8\uff1e|date=2014-07-06|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=modelpress|language=ja}}</ref>\n\nOn January 7, 2015, Nogizaka46 released their first album ''[[T\u014dmei na Iro]]'', selling over 220,000 copies in the first week.<ref name=toumeinairofirstweek>{{cite news|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2047104/full/|language=ja|title=\u3010\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u3011\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u521d\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u304c1\u4f4d \u521d\u9031\u58f2\u4e0a22.2\u4e07\u679a|work=Oricon News|date=2015-01-03|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> The album reached number one on the Oricon weekly albums chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/ja/w/2015-01-19/|script-title=ja:\u9031\u9593 CD\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 2015\u5e7401\u670819\u65e5\u4ed8|date=2015-01-19|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref> The following month, the group held their third birthday concert, this time  in front of 38,000 people at [[Seibu Dome]] in [[Saitama Prefecture|Saitama]].<ref name=\"modelpress20150222\">{{cite web|url=http://mdpr.jp/music/detail/1469434|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u897f\u91ce\u4e03\u702c\u3089\u611f\u6d99 AKB48\u5c0f\u5d8b\u967d\u83dc\u3082\u30b5\u30d7\u30e9\u30a4\u30ba\u767b\u5834 7\u6642\u9593\u534a\u30fb\u516869\u66f2\u306b3\u4e078000\u4eba\u71b1\u72c2\uff1c3\u5468\u5e74\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\uff0f\u5199\u771f\u7279\u96c6\uff1e|date=2015-02-22|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=modelpress|language=ja}}</ref> Rina Ikoma returned to Nogizaka46, with Rena Matsui returning to SKE48.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/article/2015/03/akb48-announces-reshuffling-of-personnel-kawaei-rinas-graduation|title=AKB48 announces reshuffling of personnel + Kawaei Rina's graduation|date=2015-03-26|accessdate=2016-03-06|publisher=6Theory Media, LLC|work=tokyohive}}</ref> The group also launched a new television variety show, {{nihongo|''Nogizaka K\u014djich\u016b''|\u4e43\u6728\u5742\u5de5\u4e8b\u4e2d| Lit: Nogizaka Under Construction}}, to replace ''Nogizakatte, Doko?''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/10026351/|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u897f\u91ce\u4e03\u702c\u3001\u65b0\u756a\u7d44\u3067\u52d5\u7269\u597d\u304d\u3092\u30a2\u30d4\u30fc\u30eb \u30d0\u30ca\u30ca\u30de\u30f3\u8a2d\u697d\u300c\u305d\u3046\u3044\u3046\u756a\u7d44\u304b\u3089\u30aa\u30d5\u30a1\u30fc\u6765\u308b\u304b\u3082\u306d\u300d|trans-title=Nogizaka46 Nanase Nishino made an appeal about her love of animals |date=2015-04-20|accessdate=2016-03-06|publisher=Livedoor News|language=ja}}</ref> Their first television drama, ''[[Hatsumori Bemars]]'', premiered on [[TV Tokyo Network|the TX network]] in July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2053242/full/|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u5168\u54e1\u3067\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u521d\u4e3b\u6f14 \u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u30dc\u30fc\u30eb\u30c1\u30fc\u30e0\u306e\"\u9752\u6625\"\u63cf\u304f|date=2015-05-23|accessdate=2016-03-06|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref> Nogizaka46 concluded the year by appearing for the first time on the [[NHK]] nationally-broadcast New Year program ''[[K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen]]'', where they performed their fifth single, titled \"[[Kimi no Na wa Kib\u014d]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/article/2015/11/nhk-reveals-artist-line-up-for-66th-kohaku-uta-gassen|title=NHK reveals artist line up for '66th Kohaku Uta Gassen'|date=2015-11-26|accessdate=2016-03-06|publisher=6Theory Media, LLC|work=tokyohive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2064712/full/|script-title=ja:\u3010\u7d05\u767d\u3011\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u5ff5\u9858\u521d\u51fa\u5834 \u30d0\u30ca\u30ca\u30de\u30f3\u5927\u8208\u596e\u300c\u3084\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u306d\uff01\u300d|date=2015-12-31|accessdate=2016-03-06|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132017: Third generation and Japan Record Award===\nFrom February 20 through February 22, 2016, Nogizaka46 broadcast an Internet TV program titled ''Nogizaka46 4th Anniversary Nogizaka 46 hours TV'', in which the members produced and performed their own material for forty-six consecutive hours, on six websites simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2067212/full/|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u30016\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8\u3067\u300c46\u6642\u9593TV\u300d\u914d\u4fe1 \u30a2\u30f3\u30c0\u30fc\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u6771\u5317\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba\u767a\u8868|date=2016-02-20|accessdate=2016-05-25|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref> In the week following the performance, the group's twelfth single \"[[Taiy\u014d Nokku]]\" was selected for the 30th [[Japan Gold Disc Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/177777|script-title=ja:\u30b4\u30fc\u30eb\u30c9\u30c7\u30a3\u30b9\u30af\u5927\u8cde\u306f\u5d50\u304c2\u5e74\u9023\u7d9a4\u56de\u76ee\u3001\u30a2\u30ec\u30ad\u30fbAKB48\u3089\u3082\u5404\u8cde\u53d7\u8cde|date=2016-02-27|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=Natasha,Inc|language=ja}}</ref> On May 25, 2016, they released their second album ''[[Sorezore no Isu]]'', which reached number one on the Oricon weekly albums chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2070814/full/|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u65b0\u30d3\u30b8\u30e5\u30a2\u30eb\u306f\u56fd\u7acb\u65b0\u7f8e\u8853\u9928\u3067\u64ae\u5f71|date=2016-04-27|accessdate=2016-05-25|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/ja/w/2016-06-06/|script-title=ja:\u9031\u9593 CD\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 2016\u5e7406\u670806\u65e5\u4ed8|date=2016-06-06|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref> The group promoted the second album with a second broadcast of ''Nogizaka 46 hours TV''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/188010|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u30012nd\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u767a\u58f2\u8a18\u5ff5\u30572\u5ea6\u76ee\u306e\u300c\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u6642\u9593TV\u300dOA|date=2016-05-20|accessdate=2016-06-17|publisher=Natasha,Inc|language=ja}}</ref> On August 5, they released their second photobook, titled ''1 Jikan Okure no I Love You'', which sold 41,000 copies in the first week and ranked 1st on Oricon weekly book ranking.<ref name=\"oricon20160811\"/>\n\nFrom July 19 to September 4, 2016, the 3rd generation audition took place, with 13 finalists chosen out of 48,986 applicants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2077833/full/|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u30013\u5e74\u3076\u308a\u65b0\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc\u767a\u8868 3\u671f\u751f12\u4eba\u304a\u62ab\u9732\u76ee|date=2016-09-04|accessdate=2016-09-09|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref> The final stage of the audition involved an appeal by 13 finalists to internet audiences using the [[SHOWROOM (streaming service)|SHOWROOM]] internet streaming service.<ref name=\"modelpress20160904\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/199425|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u7b2c3\u671f\u30aa\u30fc\u30c7\u30a3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u3001\u5019\u88dc\u751f\u304cSHOWROOM\u3067\u30a2\u30d4\u30fc\u30eb|date=2016-08-25|accessdate=2016-09-09|publisher=natalie|language=ja}}</ref> Twelve candidates passed the final screening.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/article/2016/09/nogizaka46-welcome-3rd-generation-members|title=Nogizaka46 welcome 3rd generation members|date=2016-09-05|accessdate=2016-09-09|publisher=6Theory Media, LLC|work=tokyohive}}</ref>\n\nThe group's fourth birthday concert was held during the last three days of their summer tour, instead of earlier in the year, due to booking issues caused by [[2020 Summer Olympics]] construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nogizaka46.com/news/2016/03/4620164th-year-birthday-live.php|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u300e\u771f\u590f\u306e\u5168\u56fd\u30c4\u30a2\u30fc2016\u300f\u53ca\u3073\u300e4th YEAR BIRTHDAY LIVE\u300f\u958b\u50ac\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff01|date=2016-03-25|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=Nogizaka46 LLC|language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2064184/full/|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u8a18\u5ff5\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u958b\u50ac\u5ef6\u671f \u300c2016\u5e74\u554f\u984c\u300d\u4f59\u6ce2|date=2015-12-21|accessdate=2016-09-25|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=ja}}</ref> In November 2016, Nogizaka46 released the 16th single \"[[Sayonara no Imi]]\". It reached number one on the Oricon weekly single chart, selling 827,717 copies in the first week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/js/w/2016-11-21/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116040129/http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/js/w/2016-11-21/ |script-title=ja:\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u9031\u9593 CD\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 2016\u5e7411\u670807\u65e5\uff5e2016\u5e7411\u670813\u65e5 |archivedate=2016-11-16 |accessdate=2017-01-28 |publisher=oricon ME |language=ja |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"Sayonara no Imi\" became the group's first Million single certified by [[Recording Industry Association of Japan|RIAJ]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/d_news/detail/44093/2|script-title=ja:AKB48\u4ee5\u5916\u30679\u5e74\u3076\u308a!\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u300e\u30b5\u30e8\u30ca\u30e9\u306e\u610f\u5473\u300f\u65e5\u672c\u30ec\u30b3\u30fc\u30c9\u5354\u4f1a\u30df\u30ea\u30aa\u30f3\u8a8d\u5b9a\u3067\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc\u30b3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8\u5230\u7740|date=2016-11-10|accessdate=2017-01-28|work=Billboard Japan|language=ja}}</ref> Nogizaka46 ended the year with their second appearance on NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/215279|script-title=ja:\u7d05\u767d\u30ea\u30cf\u3067RADWIMPS\u3001\u4e43\u6728\u5742\u3001RADIO FISH\u3001\u6850\u8c37\u5065\u592a\u3089\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b8\u3078|date=2016-12-30|accessdate=2017-01-28|publisher=Natasha,Inc|language=ja}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Nogizaka46 performed their fifth annual birthday concert over 3 days at [[Saitama Super Arena]].<ref name=\"5thbirthdaylive\"/> The first day of the concert was the final performance of group member [[Nanami Hashimoto]], who retired from the entertainment industry.<ref name=\"oricon20170220\"/> In May 2017, the group debuted a new theater production based based on the manga series [[Asahinagu]], performing in Tokyo, Osaka and Aichi.<ref name=\"natasha20170225\"/> That same month they released their third album, titled ''[[Umarete Kara Hajimete Mita Yume]]''.<ref name=\"officialsite20170401\">{{cite web|title=\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u5f85\u671b\u306e3rd\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u30012017\u5e745\u670824\u65e5\u30ea\u30ea\u30fc\u30b9\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff01...\uff5c\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9\uff5c\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u516c\u5f0f\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|url=http://www.nogizaka46.com/news/2017/04/3rdal.php|website=www.nogizaka46.com|language=ja}}</ref> Nogizaka46's first feature film, a live-action adaptation of the manga ''Asahinagu'' starring [[Nanase Nishino]] in the lead role, opened in cinemas across Japan in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u304c\u8599\u5200\u306b\u6311\u6226\u3000\u6620\u753b\uff06\u821e\u53f0\u300e\u3042\u3055\u3072\u306a\u3050\u300f\u4e3b\u6f14\u306f\u897f\u91ce\u4e03\u702c\uff0f\u9f4b\u85e4\u98db\u9ce5|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2086375/full/|website=ORICON NEWS|publisher=oricon ME|language=ja-JP}}</ref> The theme song for the movie, \"[[Itsuka Dekiru kara Ky\u014d Dekiru]]\", was released as their 19th single.\n\nThe group's 2017 national tour held performances in Tokyo, Sendai, Osaka, Nagoya, and Niigata, and concluded on November 7 and 8 at Tokyo Dome, where they drew in over 55,000 fans each day.<ref name=\"natasha20170702\">{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u521d\u306e\u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u30ef\u30f3\u30de\u30f3\u6c7a\u5b9a\u300c\u3084\u3063\u3068\u6765\u305f\u306d\u300d - \u97f3\u697d\u30ca\u30bf\u30ea\u30fc|url=https://natalie.mu/music/news/239164|website=\u97f3\u697d\u30ca\u30bf\u30ea\u30fc|publisher=Natasha Inc|language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u300c\u771f\u590f\u306e\u5168\u56fd\u30c4\u30a2\u30fc2017 Final \u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u516c\u6f14\u300d\u958b\u50ac\u6c7a\u5b9a\u306e\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b...\uff5c\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9\uff5c\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u516c\u5f0f\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|url=http://www.nogizaka46.com/news/2017/07/2017-final.php|website=www.nogizaka46.com|language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u521d\u306e\u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u30ef\u30f3\u30de\u30f3\u6c7a\u5b9a\u300c\u3084\u3063\u3068\u6765\u305f\u306d\u300d - \u97f3\u697d\u30ca\u30bf\u30ea\u30fc|url=https://natalie.mu/music/news/239164|website=\u97f3\u697d\u30ca\u30bf\u30ea\u30fc|publisher=natasha inc|language=ja}}</ref> Three weeks later they performed overseas for the second time, with a selection of group members performing live at C3AFA Singapore.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u521d\u306e\u30a2\u30b8\u30a2\u9032\u51fa\uff0111\u6708\u306b\u30b7\u30f3\u30ac\u30dd\u30fc\u30eb\u3067\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8\u51fa\u6f14\u304c\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff01\u6d77\u5916\u5411\u3051\u306bFacebook\u3001Weibo\u30a2\u30ab\u30a6\u30f3\u30c8\u3082\u958b\u8a2d...\uff5c\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9\uff5c\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u516c\u5f0f\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|url=http://www.nogizaka46.com/news/2017/10/11-1.php|website=www.nogizaka46.com|language=ja}}</ref> The group ended the year by winning the grand prize at the 59th Japan Record Awards for their seventeenth single, titled \"[[Influencer (song)|Influencer]]\",<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u300e\u30ec\u30b3\u5927\u300f\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u304c\u521d\u306e\u5927\u8cde\u3000\u30ad\u30e3\u30d7\u30c6\u30f3\u685c\u4e95\u300c\u95a2\u308f\u3063\u3066\u304f\u308c\u305f\u3059\u3079\u3066\u306e\u7686\u3055\u3093\u306e\u304a\u304b\u3052\u300d|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2103390/full/|website=ORICON NEWS|publisher=oricon ME|language=ja-JP}}</ref> and by making their third consecutive appearance on NHK's ''K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen''.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u300c\u7d05\u767d\u300d\u521d\u51fa\u5834\u306fSHISHAMO\u3001\u30ea\u30c8\u30b0\u30ea\u3001\u30a8\u30ec\u30ab\u30b7\u3001JUMP\u3001\u5927\u77e5\u3001WANIMA\u308910\u7d44 - \u97f3\u697d\u30ca\u30bf\u30ea\u30fc|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/256968|website=\u97f3\u697d\u30ca\u30bf\u30ea\u30fc|publisher=natasha inc|language=ja}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: Departures and overseas expansion===\n[[File:2019.01.26\u300c\u7b2c14\u56de KKBOX MUSIC AWARDS in Taiwan\u300d\u4e43\u6728\u574246 @\u53f0\u5317\u5c0f\u5de8\u86cb (46830410112).jpg|thumb|alt=Members of Nogizaka46 performing on stage|Nogizaka46 performing in Taiwan in 2019]]\nFrom July 6 to September 2, 2018, the group held a national tour, starting with their birthday concert from July 6 to 8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nogizaka46.com/news/2018/05/462018527.php|script-title=ja:\u300e\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3000\u771f\u590f\u306e\u5168\u56fd\u30c4\u30a2\u30fc2018\u300f\u958b\u50ac\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff01\u30c1\u30b1\u30c3\u30c8\u5148\u884c\u306f5\u670827\u65e5\u3088\u308a\uff01|trans-title=Nogizaka46 Midsummer National Tour 2018 decided! Ticket sales for fan club members will start from May 27!|date=2018-05-12|accessdate=2018-05-12|publisher=Nogizaka46LLC|language=ja}}</ref> On December 1, the group held their first standalone overseas concert at the [[Mercedes-Benz Arena (Shanghai)|Mercedes-Benz Arena]] in Shanghai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nogizaka46.com/news/2018/09/nogizaka46-live-in-shanghai-2018.php|script-title=ja:NOGIZAKA46 LIVE in Shanghai 2018 \u958b\u50ac\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff01|trans-title=Nogizaka46 LIVE in Shanghai 2018 decided!|date=2018-09-09|accessdate=2018-09-09|publisher=Nogizaka46LLC|language=ja}}</ref> At the 60th [[Japan Record Awards]], Nogizaka46 won the main Japan Record Award for their 20th single \"[[Synchronicity (song)|Synchronicity]]\", marking their second consecutive Japan Record Award win.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2126711/full/|script-title=ja:\u300e\u30ec\u30b3\u5927\u300f\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u304c2\u5e74\u9023\u7d9a\u306e\u5927\u8cde \u897f\u91ce\u4e03\u702c\u3068\u767d\u77f3\u9ebb\u8863\u304c\u6d99\u306e\u30cf\u30b0|trans-title=Nogizaka46 wins 2nd consecutive Grand Prize, Nanase Nishino and Mai Shiraishi in tearful hug|work=Oricon News|date=2018-12-30|access-date=2018-12-30|language=ja}}</ref> In January 2019, Nogizaka46 visited Taiwan, where they performed at the [[KKBox]] Music Awards and held a concert at [[Taipei Arena]].<ref name=kkbox2019>{{cite web |title=\u30a2\u30b8\u30a2\u6700\u5927\u7d1a\u306e\u97f3\u697d\u30a2\u30ef\u30fc\u30c9\u300c14th KKBOX MUSIC AWARD\u300d\uff01\u4eca\u5e74\u306f\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001SUPER JUNIOR\u3089\u6d77\u5916\u30b2\u30b9\u30c8\u3082\u51fa\u6f14\uff01 |url=https://www.taipeinavi.com/special/80008200|website=Taipei Navi|date=2019-03-12|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nogizaka46.com/news/2018/11/nogizaka46-live-in-taipei-2019.php|script-title=ja:NOGIZAKA46 LIVE in Taipei 2019 \u958b\u50ac\u6c7a\u5b9a\u306e\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b|trans-title=NOGIZAKA46 LIVE in Taipei 2019 announced.|date=2018-11-18|accessdate=2018-11-18|publisher=Nogizaka46LLC|language=ja}}</ref> The group returned to Shanghai in October 2019,<ref name=shanghai2nd>{{cite news|url=https://www.nikkansports.com/entertainment/news/201910260001186.html|lang=ja|title=\u4e43\u6728\u5742\uff12\u5e74\u9023\u7d9a\u306e\u4e0a\u6d77\u516c\u6f14\u3000\u30bb\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u306a\u3069\u65b0\u4f53\u5236\u62ab\u9732|work=Nikkan Sports|date=2019-10-27|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref> and returned to Taipei in January 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nikkansports.com/entertainment/news/202001190001098.html|lang=ja|title=\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u304c\uff12\u5e74\u9023\u7d9a\u53f0\u6e7e\u5358\u72ec\u516c\u6f14\u3001\u89b3\u5ba2\uff11\u4e07\u4eba\u9b45\u4e86|work=Nikkan Sports|date=2020-01-20|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\nA series of first generation member graduations started in 2018, when Rina Ikoma, who had centered six of the group's singles, graduated from the group.<ref name=ikomagrad>{{cite news|url=https://natalie.mu/music/news/279198|language=ja|title=\u751f\u99d2\u91cc\u5948\u5352\u696d\u30b3\u30f3\u30b5\u30fc\u30c8\u3001\"\u732b\u80cc\u306e\u5c11\u5973\"\u304c\u80f8\u3092\u5f35\u3063\u3066\u4e43\u6728\u5742\u3092\u4e0a\u308a\u5207\u308b|work=Oricon News|date=2018-04-23|access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref> The final day of the 7th Birthday Live in February 2019 was a graduation concert for first generation member Nanase Nishino, who had centered or co-centered seven singles.<ref name=nishinograd>{{cite news|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2130094/full/|language=ja|title=\u897f\u91ce\u4e03\u702c\u3001\u5352\u30b3\u30f3\u3067\u767d\u77f3\u9ebb\u8863\u3068\u6d99\u306e\u62b1\u64c130\u79d2|trans-title=Nanase Nishino and Mai Shiraishi in tearful hug at graduation concert|work=Oricon News|date=2019-02-25|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> In March 2019, [[Misa Et\u014d]] held a solo concert as her final public appearance with the group.<ref name=misasenpaisolo>{{cite news|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2131842/full/|language=ja|title=\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u885b\u85e4\u7f8e\u5f69\u3001\u7570\u4f8b\u306e\u5352\u696d\u30bd\u30ed\u516c\u6f14|trans-title=Misa Et\u014d in exceptional graduation solo performance|work=Oricon News|date=2019-03-20|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> Nogizaka46's first captain, [[Reika Sakurai]], graduated from the group on the final day of the 2019 national summer tour, and was succeeded as captain by [[Manatsu Akimoto]].<ref name=sakuraisotsugyou>{{cite news|url=https://www.nikkansports.com/entertainment/news/201909010001178.html|language=ja|title=\u79cb\u5143\u771f\u590f\u300c\u8ab0\u3088\u308a\u3082\u73b2\u9999\u306e\u5fdc\u63f4\u56e3\u306b\u306a\u308b\u300d\u624b\u7d19\u5168\u6587|work=Nikkan Sports|date=2019-09-02|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> On January 7, 2020, [[Mai Shiraishi]] announced her plans to leave the group after the release of its twenty-fifth single.<ref name=shiraishisotsugyou>{{cite news|url=https://www.sponichi.co.jp/entertainment/news/2020/01/07/kiji/20200107s00041000025000c.html|title=\u767d\u77f3\u9ebb\u8863\u306b\u805e\u304f\u3000\u4e43\u6728\u5742\u5352\u696d\u3092\u76f8\u8ac7\u3057\u305f\u306e\u306f\u300c\u552f\u4e00\u306e\u540c\u3044\u5e74\u306e1\u671f\u751f\u300d|work=[[Sports Nippon|Sponichi Annex]]|date=2020-01-07|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> The following month, five [[Sakamichi Series]] trainees were assigned to Nogizaka46.<ref name=trainees2020>{{cite news|lang=ja|url=https://natalie.mu/music/news/367475|title=\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u3001\u6b05\u574246\u3001\u65e5\u5411\u574246\u300c\u5742\u9053\u7814\u4fee\u751f\u300d\u914d\u5c5e\u5148\u30b0\u30eb\u30fc\u30d7\u767a\u8868|work=[[Natalie (website)|Natalie]]|date=2020-02-16|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\n== Members ==\n=== Current members ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:small;\"\n|-\n!Name||Birth date (age)||Native||Generation||Notes\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Manatsu Akimoto]]|\u79cb\u5143\u771f\u590f}}||{{Birth date and age|1993|8|20}}||[[Saitama Prefecture|Saitama]]||1||Captain\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Erika Ikuta]]|\u751f\u7530\u7d75\u68a8\u82b1}}||{{Birth date and age|1997|1|22}}||[[Tokyo]]||1||\n|-\n|{{nihongo|Sayuri Inoue|\u4e95\u4e0a\u5c0f\u767e\u5408}}||{{Birth date and age|1994|12|14}}||Saitama||1||\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Asuka Sait\u014d]]|\u9f4b\u85e4\u98db\u9ce5}}||{{Birth date and age|1998|8|10}}||Tokyo||1||\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Mai Shiraishi]]|\u767d\u77f3\u9ebb\u8863}}||{{Birth date and age|1992|8|20}}||[[Gunma Prefecture|Gunma]]||1||\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Kazumi Takayama]]|\u9ad8\u5c71\u4e00\u5b9f}}||{{Birth date and age|1994|2|8}}||[[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]]||1||\n|-\n|{{nihongo|Kana Nakada|\u4e2d\u7530\u82b1\u5948}}||{{Birth date and age|1994|8|6}}||Saitama||1||\n|-\n|{{nihongo|Hina Higuchi|\u6a0b\u53e3\u65e5\u5948}}||{{Birth date and age|1998|1|31}}||Tokyo||1||\n|-\n|{{nihongo|Minami Hoshino|\u661f\u91ce\u307f\u306a\u307f}}||{{Birth date and age|1998|2|6}}||Chiba||1||\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Sayuri Matsumura]]|\u677e\u6751\u6c99\u53cb\u7406}}||{{Birth date and age|1992|8|27}}||Osaka||1||\n|-\n|{{nihongo|Maaya Wada|\u548c\u7530\u307e\u3042\u3084}}||{{Birth date and age|1998|4|23}}||Hiroshima||1||\n|-\n||{{nihongo|Junna It\u014d|\u4f0a\u85e4\u7d14\u5948}}||{{Birth date and age|1998|11|30}}||Kanagawa||2||\n|-\n||{{nihong